<HEADLINE>Two schools the same, but different</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880769</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Are school-cost
figures too basic to be meaningful?
asks Dick Louden
EVERY statistical tome emerging from the Scottish Office these days seems to
require the statutory health warning. It applies to the annual exam results,
the attendance and absence figures - even the apparently innocuous data on
school costs. However, if statements about playing fields not being level,
about like not being compared with like, seem depressingly familiar, they
should not be ignored on that account.
Theoretically it might be possible to find two schools which are so alike in
size and age of building, in the number of pupils they cater for, and in the
type of area they serve, that the costs of running them would be almost
identical. In practice it does not happen - or, to be more exact, if total
operational costs are very similar, a detailed breakdown would be certain to
show wide variations of spending in different areas such as property costs or
supplies and services.
Indeed, the problem with published data on school costs is that, except in the
odd case, it is of little practical value to school boards and parents. This is
because expenditure on individual schools is so massively concentrated on two
areas - staffing and building costs. Typically, these amount to around 93% of a
school's budgeted expenditure and, as a result, any significant changes in
patterns of spending elsewhere in the budget have minimal impact in overall
terms.
Though Devolved School Management increases the influence that schools and
their boards can have on deciding priorities for spending, that influence is
still exercised relatively at the margin.
Education authorities have traditionally set staffing levels for their schools,
sometimes enhanced for schools serving areas of deprivation but otherwise based
on a formula which treats all schools in similar fashion. Likewise, building
costs are determined in large measure by factors such as the level of occupancy
. . .
A building with a capacity of 1500 pupils and a roll of 1400 is much more
economical to operate than it would be if it had only 700 pupils. Thus, there
are really only two ways in which schools which are proving extremely expensive
to run can be tackled. Staffing levels can be substantially reduced (an option
which neither authorities nor parents are normally ready to countenance) or
under-used buildings can be closed (just about as popular as the staffing
option).
In cases like these, the only positive impact of national reports on school
costs is to remind people that they have an uncomfortable problem.
For those who are interested in going beyond the bland general data presented
in the Scottish Office's report, there is the opportunity to look at the
detailed line-by-line analysis contained in the budget statements issued by
authorities to their schools and school boards. These at least have the virtue
of demonstrating that schools of similar size and budget often disburse their
funds in somewhat different ways, usually beyond their control.
For instance, School A, with a roll of 556 and a budget of #1,563,000, incurs
teacher costs of #1,154,000 because, situated in a relatively prosperous area,
it has no staffing supplement. Its property costs, including #67,400 for rates,
run at the relatively economical figure of #174,700, but its only offsetting
income - #38,200 from the sale of meals to pupils - is comparatively high since
most of its pupils do not qualify for free school meals.
On the other hand, School B - situated in a deprived urban area - has a roll of
568 and a budget of #1,605,000. These figures are almost identical to those
applying to School A but there the similarity ends.
School B's staffing costs, at #1,279,000, are #125,000 higher because of extra
teachers allocated under the authority's social strategy. Its property costs,
abnormally high at #410,000 as against #174,700, include #169,350 for rates,
#96,460 for contract cleaning and #54,720 for the school's contract janitorial
service. Conversely, its substantial income of #349,900 against #38,200 for
School A owes little to the sale of meals - the majority of pupils qualify for
free meals - but a great deal (around #330,000) to payments made by various
organisations for the use of school accommodation.
The lesson to be learned from this may well be that the Scottish Office should
either go the whole way or not at all. Statistics which show that similar
schools have different overall expenditure are at best glib and at worst
dangerously misleading, since they offer no explanation for the perfectly
legitimate and unavoidable reasons behind the variations.
In its introduction, the report claims to provide ``basic information on
budgeted running costs''. Therein lies its problem. Perhaps it is too basic to
be meaningful.
</TEXT>
