<HEADLINE>The cost gulf between city and island</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Barclay McBain</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880770</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
It can be over #9000
per pupil, reports
Education Correspondent
Barclay McBain
WHEN it comes to comparing the secondary schools with the highest and lowest
per-pupil costs in Scotland, Glasgow's miles cheaper. Holyrood Secondary in the
south side of the city, with 2001 pupils on each of whom an average of #2145
was spent, is also miles distant from the school with the highest published
per-pupil costs, Sanday Junior High in Orkney. Its running cost per pupil was
#11,334, more than five times as much as the Holyrood figure.
There are, of course, very good reasons for the huge gap in spending. Holyrood,
the biggest local authority school in Scotland, can achieve unmatched economies
of scale in the state sector. Sanday, on the other hand, had only 16 pupils
over whom to spread its costs which are, in any case, higher because several
teachers have to be flown in from the mainland.
Finbar Moynihan, Holyrood's headteacher, believes that using raw data to make
comparisons between schools - whether on examination performance or the cost of
education - is invidious. He points out that island schools like Sanday which
serve isolated populations are the souls of the community, and deserve to be
supported.
He says: ``I don't think everything is relatable to size. What does it tell
you? Not a lot. We have a good school, good teachers, good parental commitment,
and a good ethos. We are working hard on the quality of teaching and learning,
on attendance, and on improving our examination results, but we do so under
constraints.''
Overcrowding is a major problem at Holyrood. The magnet Roman Catholic
secondary runs 13 first-and second-year classes with the maximum of 33 pupils,
20 in practical classes. ``There are spin-offs in terms of the timetable. We
can place more staff in the upper school, but we are still in an expanding
situation,'' says the head.
The school's first-year intake has been set at 396 by a sheriff court ruling
and the impact is working its way through the school, expected to culminate in
a maximum roll of 2147 in two years. The pressure on accommodation should be
eased, however, by expenditure on new classrooms.
Mr Moynihan is, none the less, concerned about the roll-based points system
which allows additional promoted staff to be appointed. The extra points show
big jumps at certain roll-related stages but tail off after a school's pupil
numbers go beyond 1301, perhaps reflecting the fact that there are few
secondaries with bigger rolls - 24 with more than 1300 pupils, only two with
more than 1700, only one (Holyrood) with more than 1900.
Similarly, there are concerns about whether the formula for appointing
technical and ancillary staff actually reflects Holyrood's roll. In these
circumstances the savings linked to size can actually be a deficit.
``While some people might say I should be jumping up and down, that it is
wonderful to have the lowest per-pupil costs, I don't think it accurately
reflects what is going on in the school, and whether parents are getting value
for money,'' says Mr Moynihan.
The roll at Sanday Junior High has increased to 25 since the date on which this
year's running costs are based, but headteacher Roderick Thorne recognises that
its costs will always be among the highest. Living on an island, the Sanday
pupils can transfer to Kirkwall Grammar at the end of second or fourth year.
In 1994 all pupils took the earlier option, but this year nine out of ten
stayed on, perhaps reflecting that fact that the Sanday campus has become a
community school, with its own swimming pool and dance hall.
Staffing at Sanday is a complex business. Mr Thorne is the maths teacher, and
only two other full-time members of staff live on the island, with teachers of
technical education, RE, music and home economics all flying over from the
mainland.
A similar situation applies at North Walls Junior High, also in Orkney, which
had the highest cost of #18,444 last year. This year, however, the Scottish
Office decided not to publish costs for schools with fewer than five pupils. In
September 1994 North Walls had a roll of four, which could have given a
per-pupil cost of about #25,000.
Aided by the arrival of two new families, the roll has grown to ten. According
to head teacher Kenneth Michie, removal of the threat of closure may have
influenced the decision of one pupil to become the first to stay on into third
year.
</TEXT>
