<HEADLINE>Privatisation scheme delayed after cool reaction from banks and building societies Student loan changes dropped</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880778</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's plans for privatising student loans were thrown into disarray
yesterday, with the announcement that the scheme will be delayed for a year.
Ministers had hoped that banks and building societies could be persuaded to
back a privatised scheme to be introduced next year, but Education Minister
Eric Forth said yesterday that no scheme could be brought in before October
1997 - well after the last possible date for the next General Election.
The official explanation for the delay is that banks and building societies,
which would be able to compete for the provision of loans with the Student
Loans Company, based in Glasgow, cannot get the required technology set up in
time.
However, Opposition MPs claimed that the private sector simply was not
interested and was alarmed by the weight of bad debt and the danger of
alienating students they hoped would become future customers.
Mr Bryan Davies, Labour's Higher Education spokesman, said: ``The Government
has effectively admitted that its student loans proposals are a flop. The
banks
are simply not interested.''
The announcement of the delay came on the second day of the Commons committee
stage of the Student Loans Bill, and led to immediate calls for the whole
exercise to be abandoned.
Glasgow Maryhill Labour MP Maria Fyfe, the only Scottish MP on the committee,
said last night: ``There is no point in Parliament considering this any
further
because Labour would not implement a Bill of this nature, and, following what
we have just been told, it will not come into effect until after the next
General Election. The Government's efforts to put this through have become a
shambles.''
Mr Davies said: ``Ministers should never have proceeded without first having
secured detailed agreement with the private sector. It is particularly bizarre
that when, on Tuesday morning, Labour proposed a 12-month delay in the
implementation of new arrangements with the banks, this was rejected by
Ministers. They have now performed a spectacular U-turn.''
The student loans legislation formed a key part of the Queen's Speech, but
banks and other financial institutions already had told the Government they
wanted nothing to do with it.
The Midland Bank is reported to have told the National Union of Students that
during discussions with the Department for Education and Employment it had
been
unable to resolve a number of concerns on issues such as administrative
complexity, risk identification, profitablity and customer reaction.
A spokeswoman for the department confirmed yesterday that the target date for
implementation of any scheme which could be agreed with the banks now had been
changed from October 1996 to October 1997.
She confirmed that Mr Forth told MPs the reasons cited in the committee
included the complications presented by bank mergers and difficulties over new
technology.
The spokeswoman said: ``We have listened to what the banks had to say during
consultation on the draft invitation to tender. They were concerned about
getting their scheme up and running by the beginning of the next academic
year.
We have taken account of that and are focusing efforts on getting a scheme up
and running by the following academic year.''
Asked whether any banks or building societies had committed themselves to
joining an eventual scheme, the spokeswoman said discussions were continuing.
A spokesman for the National Union of Students said: ``It was obvious that the
banks and students themselves saw the flaws in this scheme to privatise loans.
Now it is clear that the Government does as well.''
</TEXT>
