<HEADLINE>Scottish Opera crisis `driving artists away'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880779</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Political Reporter
SCOTTISH Opera's cash crisis is driving its most talented musicians away from
Scotland, general director Richard Jarman told MPs yesterday, as he appealed
for lottery funds to meet running costs.
Giving evidence to the National Heritage Select Committee, Mr Jarman said the
decision to reduce Scottish Opera to part-time working would prompt artists to
seek employment elsewhere.
``Indeed, there is evidence that is happening. Key members of the organisation
are already seeking jobs elsewhere which is an extremely worrying fact,'' he
said.
Unless Parliament agreed to change the rules and allow lottery proceeds to be
used for running costs and not just building costs, opera companies around the
UK would struggle to survive. ``I find it difficult to believe that there are
going to be enough buildings to refurbish or build in Scotland. If meantime
organisations like Scottish Opera have been allowed to wither and decline, who
is going to fill those buildings?'' he said.
In written evidence to the committee, he warned: ``The result is likely to be a
downgrading of the company's staffing, a loss of artistic quality and the
draining of talent and skills away from Scotland."
</TEXT>
