<HEADLINE>Damages threat over derailment</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880780</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POP impresario Pete Waterman could face a large damages bill after one of his
charter trains was derailed early yesterday in north London, temporarily
halting all services in and out of Euston station. No-one was hurt.
Waterman, part of the Stock, Aitken and Waterman team of music producers,
recently has become a rail buff. Earlier this year, he bought British Rail's
charter train service Special Trains and set up Waterman Railways.
A spokesman for Railtrack, which launched an inquiry, said: ``Train operating
companies can claim compensation from Railtrack if their services are
disrupted. If it turned out to be another party at fault, they might have to
pay.''
</TEXT>
