<HEADLINE>Row over figures for rail sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880781</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Industrial Correspondent
GOVERNMENT and Opposition Transport teams clashed yesterday over the likely
drain on or benefit to the public purse anticipated from the rail privatisation
programme.
Shadow Transport team Clare Short and Brian Wilson claimed that the long-term
cost to the taxpayer of selling off the rail industry would be #850m a year -
or #1600 every minute - in addition to more than #1bn of costs incurred in the
lead-in to privatisation.
However, Transport Minister John Watts dismissed these arguments as ``absurd''
and Transport Secretary Sir George Young maintained that rail privatisation
would actually provide a boost for taxpayers.
Labour published fresh analysis of the official figures, showing what the party
claims is the ``hidden cost'' to the public purse after privatisation including:
q #600m in additional subsidy paid to the 25 train operating companies by the
Office of Passenger Rail Franchising.
q #12m in additional subsidy paid to freight operators to cover track access
charges.
q #220m in higher grants paid by the Government to local authorities in
metropolitan areas to compensate them because after rail privatisation they
will be charged the full cost of using rail services by the Passenger Transport
Authorities.
q #17m to run two new ``quangos'' created to oversee the new network.
Shadow Transport Secretary Clare Short said: ``Every minute of every day,
taxpayers are going to pay #1600 extra subsidy, not for better rail services,
not for safer stations, but simply to keep the shareholders of Railtrack
happy.''
Mr Watts dismissed Labour's claims, saying that the level of subsidy would
remain ``broadly the same'' following the sell-off.
``Labour's claims about an extra #600m for the 25 train operating companies are
absolute rubbish. We fully expect that the new railways will provide better
quality of services to passengers at less cost to taxpayers,'' he said.
At a news conference in London, Mr Wilson said that Mr Major had seriously
misled the Commons earlier this week when he claimed that investment was rising
on the railways.
Mr Wilson said: ``In fact, investment in the domestic railway is currently at
its lowest level since nationalisation in 1948.''
Sir George was reacting to the July report by the all-party Commons committee
on rail finances which had concluded that privatisation would not provide
improved revenue or reduced costs.
Such an outlook was unrealistic, he said, pointing to the improvements in
efficiency and choice that would flow from privatisation.
Sir George added: ``The Government is confident that its privatisation
programme represents excellent value for money for taxpayers and passengers and
will bring significant benefits.''
Brian Wilson..................18
</TEXT>
