<HEADLINE>Abuse student says sorry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880782</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER student who conducted a long-running campaign of abuse against
Aberdeen University and its officials yesterday tendered an unqualified apology.
Peter Dow also promised a judge that he would end his campaign immediately.
Last month at the Court of Session, Lord Kirkwood found Dow in contempt of
court and breach of interdict for continuing his action in defiance of court
orders.
Dow, 29, has disrupted university meetings and issued thousands of leaflets as
part of his crusade. He has likened the Principal, Professor Maxwell Irvine, to
Hitler and Stalin.
In October 1990, Dow, of Hollybank Place, Aberdeen, enrolled at Aberdeen as a
post-graduate student. The following year his dissertation was failed by the
university.
Dow started his campaign and the university obtained an interdict banning him
from distributing defamatory leaflets but the campaign continued.
Yesterday, he appeared again at the Court of Session so that Lord Kirkwood
could consider whether to impose a custodial sentence.
Lord Kirkwood said  that while Dow's conduct had been ``quite disgraceful'' he
had now tendered an unqualified apology and given a formal undertaking that he
would cease his campaign.
In the circumstances, he had decided, with some hesitation, to defer
consideration of the penalty for 12 months.
</TEXT>
