<HEADLINE>Pressure group calls on MP to back fight against reprocessing spent US nuclear fuel Ballot rejects Dounreay plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880784</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE people of Caithness, traditionally the most pro-nuclear community in
Scotland, have voted in a referendum two to one against Dounreay accepting
contracts to reprocess spent nuclear fuel of American origin which is
stockpiled at 33 research reactors across Europe.
Friends of the Earth Scotland also published the results of a poll of 1037
voters across Scotland which showed that 94% were opposed to the plant doing
the work.
The Caithness poll was commissioned by the Caithness Against Nuclear Dumping
(Cand) group. It recorded 7091 (65.5%) opposed to foreign reprocessing; 3741
(34.5%) in favour; with only 45 spoilt papers.
Cand immediately called on Caithness and Sutherland MP Robert Maclennan, who
last month described the vote as an attempted fraud, to decide whether he was
prepared to support and fight for the clear wishes of his constituents on this
issue. Dounreay's director, Mr John Baxter, dismissed the result as a
propaganda exercise and a stunt.
The Caithness referendum is being seen as highly significant by most observers,
not least the turn-out of 52.7% which was almost 8% higher than the average
turn-out for the elections to the new Highland Council last spring.
A spokesman for the Electoral Reform Society, which conducted the poll, told
The Herald a figure of about 20% was very common in such ballots and concluded:
``There is no doubt that 50% is a fairly good response rate.''
The result means that about 35% of the existing electoral roll in Caithness
have voted against reprocessing.
Cand had to raise the #10,000 costs of the referendum from a public appeal.
Cand chairman Stephen Pottinger said yesterday: ``We are absolutely delighted
with this solid and impressive result. Our main aim was to give the people of
Caithness their say on an issue which would have a long-term impact on their
county.
``Their view is clear and their voice must be heard. Dounreay and the
Governments of the UK and US must listen to the people of the area and act
accordingly.''
Mr Pottinger, who farms in Caithness, was also scathing of those councillors
who had attacked the referendum: ``It is difficult to see how the Caithness
members of the new Highland Council can criticise the referendum when more
people voted in it than turned out for their own election. We elect them to
fight for us and that's what they should now do.''
Mrs Lorraine Mann, of Scotland Against Nuclear Dumping, said that for the past
two years the US Government had been consulting its public over the issue but,
here, Dounreay and the authorities had sought to keep the question of the
reprocessing contracts secret.
Mr Maclennan, however, put a different construction on the vote. ``This opinion
poll offers encouragement to those who want to see Dounreay's work continue.
Approximately two-thirds of the electorate have shown, either by not responding
or by voting in favour of reprocessing that they are not anxious about this
work.
``But the concerns of those who have registered anxieties do require to be
addressed. This is a job for the regulatory bodies, for the UK Atomic Energy
Authority and for Government Ministers. The public needs the facts; they must
all be presented fully, clearly, and openly.''
Mr Baxter, meanwhile, said: ``This so-called referendum was no more than
another propaganda exercise undertaken by Greenpeace International, albeit
fronted by Cand. We denounced it at the outset and do not accept its result.''
He added: ``Reprocessing of spent nuclear fuel is an activity which is very
tightly regulated and which provides valuable employment in Caithness. It would
be irresponsible for us to stop it because of this stunt.
``However, we accept that the local community is a vital stakeholder in
Dounreay and that we must be adequately open and listen to it. But a rushed
referendum is not the way to judge whether the community understands what we do
and is content with it.''
</TEXT>
