<HEADLINE>Council finances to face inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880785</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Accounts Commission is to investigate the financial administration of an
Ayrshire council following concern over its existing systems.
An independent financial adviser will be appointed in the coming weeks and will
``take an overview'' within Kyle and Carrick District Council, until the
handover to South Ayrshire Council on April 1, next year.
The move follows discussions involving senior council officials and the
Controller of Audit, Mr Robert Black, who was accompanied by senior colleagues.
Mr Ian Welsh, leader of the council's minority Labour group and shadow South
Ayrshire Council leader, last night expressed his concern at the decision, and
said he would be seeking further information.
He said: ``It is absolutely crucial that all steps are taken within Kyle and
Carrick District Council, by both members and officers, to ensure a smooth
transition to the new South Ayrshire Authority.
``I am concerned that the Controller of Audit has found something which he is
not satisfied with in the council's financial administration, and I will be
seeking more details from officials.''
While there is no suggestion of dishonesty and the financial probity of the
council is not in question, it is understood that the investigation will centre
on the devolvement of financial control to departments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
