<HEADLINE>Setback for investment prospects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880786</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's bid to woo City investors for nuclear privatisation suffered a
triple whammy yesterday.
It began with an adviser to the Tory-dominated Commons Trade and Industry
Select Committee confirming he was the co-author of a study warning that
taxpayers faced an extra bill for #3000m if the sales went ahead.
It ended with Friends of the Earth insisting that issues which forced Ministers
to scrap the 1989 bid to sell the industry are ``as real and unresolved today
as they were then'' - and Labour MP Brian Wilson calling for the latest attempt
to be abandoned.
Mr Wilson's Ayrshire constitutency, Cunninghame North, includes Hunterston B
power station, which apparently would have to be offered cheaply to attract a
buyer.
Mr Gordon McKerron of Sussex University, an expert in nuclear industry
economics, yesterday acknowledged he co-authored an unpublished report lodged
with the select committee.
His study suggested that taxpayers faced an extra bill of #3000m just to meet
the Government's target sale price of #3500m.
The taxpayers' cash would go towards removing the private investors' risks by
covering the industry's long-term liabilities - in particular, decommissioning
and clean-up costs when stations reach the end of their lives.
Mr McKerron, as an adviser to the committee, declined to comment on the
findings - commissioned by Friends of the Earth and the Coalition of Opposing
Local Authorities before his Government appointment.
However, co-author Mike Sadnicki, unrestrained by such protocol, said the City
would now want many answers over liabilities before even contemplating support
for the sale.
He added that Hunterston B - along with Dungeness B, Hartlepool, and Hinkley
Point B in England - would be hard to privatise unless their prices were
depressed, because they are not competitive with other forms of power
generation.
The Hunterston station's production costs are put at 2.79p a unit above market
rates, according to the study.
Torness, Scotland's other nuclear station to be sold, would fare a little
better, despite being 2.25p a unit above market rates - thanks to a longer
productivity lifespan. It is due to operate until 2023, compared with 2011 for
Hunterston B.
The City is due to receive Government briefings in the new year, weeks before
evidence is taken, if at all, on the findings of the academics.
Mr Sadnicki said: ``Torness comes out with a small, positive net value. But
whether it is enough for investors to think it worth while is difficult to
judge.''
Dr Patrick Green, Friends of the Earth nuclear campaigner, said concerns about
decommissioning bills led the Government to scrap its attempt to sell the
industry in 1989.
He added: ``The issues that sank privatisation then are as real and unresolved
today.''
Dr Green said there was no evidence that privatisation made sense or
represented value for money.
He warned that the Government would be in breach of European laws if the
nuclear industry were sold as a result of ``subsidies'' to the private sector
from taxpayers covering the long-term clean-up bills.
Mr Wilson, a former member of the Commons committee investigating the sell-off,
said the Government should call a halt now but predicted it would press on
because it wanted privatisation proceeds next year.
He also forecast that taxpayers would be left with a huge bill while profitable
parts were sold to the private sector.
</TEXT>
