<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jury clears bandswoman of killing lover</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880787</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHEATING wife Pollyanna Peate was cleared by a jury yesterday of the
manslaughter of her ageing lover, Mr Brian Phillips.
The 34-year-old mother-of-two, who carried on a 10-year affair with grandfather
Mr Phillips, 62, after rehearsals with Frodsham Silver Band in Cheshire, showed
no emotion as the jury delivered its verdict after less than 45 minutes.
However, her husband, Graham, 36, who sat in the public gallery at Chester
Crown Court throughout the trial, wept as he hugged her outside the court.
Mrs Peate refused to make any comment to newsmen and Mr Peate would say only:
``We are very relieved that it is all over and that Polly has been vindicated.''
Mrs Peate, a euphonium player, of Runcorn, had denied killing bass trombonist
Mr Phillips on the night of November 15, 1994.
The four-day trial heard that the couple regularly had sex in Mr Phillips's car
in a lovers' lane after rehearsals with the band. They kept the affair secret
from their marital partners but it had been ``an open secret'' among their
fellow musicians.
On the night Mr Phillips died, the couple had gone to the lane as usual for sex
in the back of the car and Mr Phillips had told Mrs Peate it was to be the last
time they would have sex together.
The prosecution alleged that Mrs Peate struck Mr Phillips about the head at
least four times, sparking the heart attack that killed him. However, the jury
accepted Mrs Peate's claim that she had not attacked him and that he had died
while they were making love.
She told the court: ``He died having sex. I'm sorry but that's how it happened.
I've got nothing to admit.''
Mrs Sybil Phillips met Mrs Peate when the band was performing but was unaware
of the relationship with her husband, whom she married almost 40 years ago when
she was 19.
She kept away from court during the trial but told police: ``I was totally
unaware . . . that Polly and my husband were having an affair . . . It has come
as a great shock to me.''
Mrs Peate had started the affair not long after the birth of her second child,
and told the court she loved her husband and had been happy with him, though he
had been a gambler.
When police questioned Mr Peate, he said: ``I would describe my marriage as
perfect. My wife and I get on together and I trust her implicitly.''
Mrs Peate is from the West Bromwich area. She worked for a while in a
supermarket and a pub, and later gave part-time music lessons. She and her
husband are ``born-again'' Christians.
The band appears to have been a fertile ground for extra-marital relationships.
Among the witnesses in the case were band vice-chairman Terence Hoppley and his
wife, Carolyn.
They, too, met through the band, had an affair, and set up home together in
Saltney, near Chester. Mr Phillips was best man at their wedding earlier last
year and was also godfather to their daughter.
Mrs Hoppley told police she was aware of a ``chemistry'' between Mrs Peate and
Mr Phillips and had heard her husband and Mr Phillips joke about ``going down
to the marshes''.
After Mr Phillips died during their sex session, Mrs Peate walked back into
Frodsham and called a taxi home, where her husband noticed blood on her face.
Mrs Peate told police that she had gone to bed with her husband and made love -
but claimed that she was thinking about Mr Phillips.
</TEXT>
