<HEADLINE>Slight drop in homeless</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES  HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880788</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHELTER Scotland yesterday claimed that its latest survey exposed the extent of
the housing crisis in Scotland.
The survey showed that, for the fourth year running, more than 40,000
households applied to councils as homeless and almost 186,000 households were
on council house waiting lists.
Despite Shelter's claims of a crisis, however, the figures showed that, in the
past two years, there had been a decline of 5% in homelessness applications to
councils. The total now stands at 40,734.
Council waiting lists have also been shortened, from 188,688 in 1994 to 185,922
this year.
The Shelter survey comes hard on the heels of the announcement by Scottish
Secretary Michael Forsyth of a 20% cut in housing investment next year.
Shelter's Scottish director, Ms Liz Nicholson, claimed that if the level of
investment were equal to that of 1989, an extra 27,000 houses would have been
built.
She went on: ``Mr Forsyth claims to be a listening Secretary of State. I would
like him also to go and see the misery and the human cost of homelessness.''
Commenting on the survey, Scottish Housing Minister Raymond Robertson insisted
that waiting lists themselves were poor indicators of housing need. Many people
registered on the lists of more than one authority and sometimes failed to
cancel the registration when a home was found.
</TEXT>
