<HEADLINE>Rebels warn over Russian elections Chechen fighting erupts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PHILIPPA FLETCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880789</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow, Thursday
FIGHTING flared across Chechnya today in a bloody challenge to Moscow's attempt
to include the rebel territory in a parliamentary poll on Sunday which looks
set to bring communists back to the fore.
The clashes, the heaviest in months, grabbed the spotlight from campaigning in
the general election in which communists are expected to make the best showing
despite President Boris Yeltsin's appeals to prevent them from securing more
influence.
Yeltsin remains in a sanatorium after suffering his second mild heart attack in
four months. One of his top aides told a television interviewer that Yeltsin
would announce in February whether he would stand for re-election in June.
The Chechen rebels seized parts of the mountainous region's second town
Gudermes in an early morning raid, sparking the heaviest fighting for months in
the battle-scarred region, where voting started early for security reasons.
``They (Chechen rebels) have taken almost the entire town,'' one soldier told
Reuters outside Gudermes after firing frantically into the air to stop a car
with reporters.
Interfax news agency quoted Russia's military command as saying that the
fighting had died down in the evening.
Sniper fire continued and the rebels still held part of the town. Russian news
reports said fighting had spread to two other Chechen towns.
The clashes added weight to rebel warnings that the poll would lead to renewed
warfare in Chechnya, where Russia has failed to crush a four-year rebellion
despite heavy casualties.
It made Sunday's vote seem virtually meaningless in Chechnya and cast a shadow
over preparations for polling in the rest of the vast Russian federation, where
43 parties and thousands of candidates are competing for seats.
Russia's State ORT television said Yeltsin had recorded a television address to
be broadcast tomorrow to the nation's 104 million voters, who are spread across
11 time zones.
Yeltsin holds the most power under Russia's 1993 constitution but he has made
no secret of his concern that the communists might form the biggest party in
parliament.
Asked whether Yeltsin would run for a second five-year term in June's
presidential election, the president's top security aide, Alexander Korzhakov
said: ``The president will speak about this in February.''
``Will he or won't he. This is indeed the greatest problem,'' said the burly
Korzhakov, who is credited by some observers with wielding great influence over
the president.
``When we criticise the president, we sometimes don't think what will start if
he doesn't run. It seems to me nothing good will come of it.''
Korzhakov also obliquely criticised Defence Minister Pavel Grachev, who is in
charge of the Chechnya campaign, saying the minister was ``particularly
talented at staging parades''.
Most polls say only five or six parties will score above five percent - the
communists, Our Home is Russia, the liberal Yabloko grouping, Zhirinovsky's
party and the moderate nationalist Congress of Russian Communities, whose main
asset is a charismatic retired general, Alexander Lebed.
But opinion surveys are notoriously unreliable in Russia, and failed to predict
the success of Vladimir Zhirinovsky's ultra-nationalist Liberal Democratic
Party in the last parliamentary poll in 1993.
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin says he expects to stay in office whatever
the result, but a poor showing by his centrist Our Home is Russia bloc could
wound him politically and rule him out as a possible successor to
Yeltsin.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
