<HEADLINE>Engine failure theory over crashed airliner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From STEFANA REBAUDO</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880790</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Verona, Thursday
ITALIAN officials said today that engine failure appeared to have caused the
crash of a Romanian airliner in northern Italy, which killed all 49 people on
board.
``We cannot rule out any hypothesis but it looks like there was a power loss in
one engine,'' said Francesco Caramuzza, under-secretary of state at the
interior ministry.
Weather conditions at the time of the crash last night were also being
investigated after one government official said the crew turned down an offer
by the airport to de-ice the plane before take-off.
The Banat Air Transport charter flight, bound for Timisoara and Bucharest in
Romania, crashed in a field in snowy weather shortly after take-off from
Verona's Villafranca airport.
The Russian-built twin-prop Antonov 24 burst into flames, killing the 41
passengers and eight Romanian crew. ``I heard a loud explosion, the house shook
and when I opened the door I saw hell - a huge fire in the darkness,'' said
Sergio Sambugara, who lives near the airport and whose wife alerted authorities
to the crash.
Thirty-one of the passengers were Italian, six were Romanian and four were
citizens of former Yugoslavia.
Only the tailpiece and a few other sections of the plane were recognisable
among debris strewn over a 200-yard area. The wreckage burned for most of the
night.
Victims' relatives helped doctors identify the bodies at a nearby military
base. Many were charred beyond recognition.
Local magistrate Carlo Giulio Schinaia said that by tonight eight bodies had
been identified, 14 others had not been named and the rest were identified with
``almost certainty''.
Schinaia, who is leading an investigation into the crash, told a news
conference that doctors would also conduct DNA tests on the victims to help
confirm their identities.
He said a transport ministry committee had been named to assist in the
investigation. A preliminary report on the cause was expected in two days and
weather conditions would be investigated.
``We offered to de-ice the plane, but the crew refused,'' airport director
Francesco Canfarelli told reporters. `During the same time period, an Air
France plane was de-iced twice before take-off.''
Romanian officials said they ruled out a terrorist attack.
The crash was the second major accident involving a Romanian carrier this year.
On March 31, a Tarom airlines Airbus A310 crashed just after take-off from
Bucharest's Otopeni international airport, killing all 60 passengers and crew.
q The search for an airliner that disappeared in the Russian Far East a week
ago widened today, and the region's chief administrator asked Japan and China
if they could provide any clues to its fate.
Rescue services told Russian news agencies they had drawn a blank yet again on
the eighth day of their hunt for the Khabarovsk Airlines Tupolev Tu-154 with 97
aboard. But they vowed to continue until the mystery was solved.
The search has been concentrated in a 50-mile by 125-mile corridor from the
waters of the Tatar Strait across the wooded and snow-covered mountains of the
mainland that the three-engined jet should have crossed on its hour-long flight
to Khabarovsk from Sakhalin Island.
Itar-Tass news agency quoted local officials at the Emergency Services ministry
as saying some of the most likely places for the plane to have come down had
already been surveyed two or three times from the air.
The multiple search, involving ski and foot patrols, 14 low-flying helicopters,
five fixed-wing aircraft, satellite photography and five warships, widened out
today, Interfax news agency quoted a local rescue official as saying.
Khabarovsk is only 30 miles from the Chinese frontier. A similar distance
separates Sakhalin from the northern Japanese island of Hokkaido.
Ishayev said the security services believed it was highly unlikely a bomb
brought down the plane, Interfax said.
The disappearance of the plane, days after two fatal crashes in Azerbaijan in
which 50 people were killed, revived concern about air safety in the former
Soviet Union.
Yesterday, three Russian Su-27 fighters smashed into a mountain in Vietnam,
killing all four aboard as they returned from an air show in Malaysia.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
