<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>French strikes begin to lose momentum</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From JOHN CHALMERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880791</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris, Thursday
A THREE-WEEK public sector strike began to falter today as a limited train
service was set to resume in parts of France and key unions held out the
prospect of a return to work despite new protests set for the weekend.
Transport chaos still gripped the country after most rail workers voted to
continue their stoppage in spite of this week's retreat by Prime Minister Alain
Juppe on pensions and a plan to streamline the indebted state rail company SNCF.
But there were signs the strikes were losing momentum.
The SNCF said that limited regional rail services would resume in northern
France tomorrow as drivers from 19 of 345 SNCF work sites voted to return to
work and the FGAAC union, which represents a third of SNCF drivers, called for
stoppages to end.
The SNCF in Lille said some trains would run from 23 stations in northern
France.
``Many trains are likely to run,'' including six high-speed TGV trains between
Lille and Roissy, home to Paris's main Charles de Gaulle international airport,
it said in a statement.
Normal service also would be operated to and from Belgium.
Trade union officials said the region was unusual in that the moderate FGAAC
drivers' union held a majority in the area.
Crippling strikes have shut down the French rail system nationwide for three
weeks as workers stay away in protest at government welfare reform proposals
and an SNCF restructuring plan that unions fear would threaten jobs, service
and benefits.
According to the SNCF, assemblies at work sites including the Saint Lazare
staion in Paris, Strasbourg, Nancy and Calais voted to call off their stoppage.
The communist-led CGT union, however, would confirm only the votes at Saint
Lazare and in the Strasbourg region.
In the capital, one of 13 Metro underground rail lines resumed briefly for the
first time since the dispute began before shutting down an hour and a half
later. Six percent of buses were running, slightly more than the recent average.
Outside the transport sector, there were more signs the strikers' resolve was
weakening. Just 3% of post office workers stayed at home compared with 6% at
the end of last week and 5% of civil servants were on strike versus 20%.
Financial markets rallied. The stock market rose 2.25% and the franc
strengthened to 3.4470 to the German mark from 3.4660 yesterday.
The two unions spearheading the strikes, the independent Force Ouvriere (FO)
and the CGT, vowed to carry on. They planned a new national day of protest on
Saturday in an effort to convince Juppe to back down further.
Air traffic controllers planned limited strikes tomorrow and three doctors'
unions planned a Paris protest on Sunday.
But in a conciliatory move, FO suggested discussing terms for a return to work.
``We feel that it is necessary, if we want to show a desire for conciliation at
this meeting, to set the traditional conditions for a return to work after a
long conflict'', FO said in a letter to Juppe.
The tough talking appeared to be an attempt to squeeze more concessions out of
Juppe ahead of what could be the unions' grand finale of mass demonstrations at
the weekend.
CGT leader Louis Viannet accused the prime minister of playing for time and
underestimating the seriousness of the crisis by delaying a labour summit
proposed for December 21.
Both the CGT and FO leaders urged Juppe to move up the summit date and expand
its agenda to include his bitterly contested welfare reforms, which the prime
minister insists are not negotiable.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
