<DOCNO>GH951215-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Syria releases 1200 militants</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880792</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Damascus, Thursday
SYRIA has freed 1200 members and supporters of the banned Muslim Brotherhood
group and prepared to free scores of other prisoners, officials and political
sources said today.
They said the measures were made to commemorate the 25th anniversary of
President Hafez al-Assad's ``correctionist movement'', a bloodless coup which
brought him to power on November 16, 1970.
It was the biggest release of political prisoners connected to the Muslim
Brotherhood, which is banned in Syria, since the government crushed an armed
uprising led by the group in 1982.
Political sources said the amnesty also allowed Brotherhood leaders who have
been in exile to return to Syria. Presidential spokesman Joubran Kourieh told
Reuters that Assad sent today an amnesty law to parliament which should lead to
the freeing of scores more prisoners.
q Leah Rabin, widow of the murdered Israeli premier, said today Pope John Paul
had told her he acknowledged Israel's proclamation of a ``double role'' for
Jerusalem as capital of the Jewish state and of the world's three great
faiths.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>German justice minister resigns</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>Foreign Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880793</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
German justice
minister resigns
BONN: German Justice Minister Sabine Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger, 44, resigned
in protest yesterday after her Free Democratic Party, junior partner in the
ruling coalition, voted to back a tough wire-tapping law.
She said she could no longer defend her party's policy credibly after a
membership referendum voted by 63 to 36% to back a constitutional amendment
that Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats have been pressing for. The
change made no difference to Kohl's razor-thin 10-seat majority in parliament.
Nigeria rapped
UNITED NATIONS: A General Assembly committee yesterday overwhelmingly condemned
Nigeria's ``arbitrary execution, after a flawed judicial process,'' of writer
Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other activists. By a vote of 98-12, with 42
abstentions, it also invited the UN Human Rights Commission to ``give urgent
attention'' to the rights situation in Nigeria.
Hong Kong talks
BEIJING: Britain and China finally sat down yesterday to discuss the ceremonies
to mark the handover of Hong Kong in 1997. Diplomats accredited to the
Sino-British Joint Liaison Group opened the talks in Beijing, journalists
reported from the Chinese capital.
Goose's revenge
AMSTERDAM: A hunter was taken to hospital with concussion and a broken
cheekbone after being felled by a dead goose. Anne Osinga said he did not see
the 6!slb goose which plunged 75ft after being shot by one of his companions.
``I was aiming with one eye shut,'' Amsterdam's de Telegraaf newspaper reported
the 60-year-old former headmaster as saying yesterday. The incident failed to
dent his appetite. ``I'm going to eat it with pleasure,'' he said.
1000 stranded
ROME: About 1000 motorists were stranded on a snowbound road in central Italy
yesterday after spending the night in their cars, police said. Tailbacks
stretched up to 12 miles on the main Bologna to Florence motorway and drivers
who were heading south were stuck for up to 20 hours.
Airline rescued
MADRID: EU transport commissioner Neil Kinnock yesterday bailed out
financially-crippled Iberia, Spain's national airline, by approving government
funding amounting to #535m. The move, which came despite bitter opposition from
rival airlines, will mean that the airline can be restructured.
Pilot hunt
WASHINGTON: Defence officials yesterday cautiously greeted Baghdad's
``humanitarian'' gesture in allowing a US military team into Iraq to search for
the body of an American  Navy pilot missing since the Gulf War. A team of 11 US
military experts and four civilians led by the International Committee of the
Red Cross searched a remote desert site in western Iraq.
EU protest
BRUSSELS: The European Union added its voice yesterday to the global clamour of
disapproval at the imprisonment for 14 years of Chinese human rights activist
Wei Jingsheng. Wei, 46, was sentenced in Beijing on Wednesday after being found
guilty of conspiring to pervert the government.
Flu epidemic
MOSCOW: An epidemic of influenza has sharply worsened in Moscow with more than
52,000 people falling ill in the past 24 hours and authorities have temporarily
closed the capital's schools to cope with the outbreak. The total number of flu
victims in the city since the epidemic officially broke out on November 28 is
approaching half a million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
