<DOCNO>GH951215-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Onassis auction set to raise #3m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880794</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New York, Thursday
THE estate of Jackie Kennedy Onassis is to go under the hammer in a major sale
at Sotheby's in New York.
The four-day sale in April is expected to raise about #3.2m for some 1200
items, including the desk on which President John Kennedy signed the 1963
Nuclear Test Ban Treaty.
Other objects offered will include a Rauschenberg portrait of the couple during
the 1960 presidential campaign and a pair of obelisks that sat in the Red Room
of the Kennedy White House.
``The sale of the estate of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis will be among the most
memorable auctions ever to take place,'' said Sotheby's president Diana Brooks.
``The objects we are selling reveal a portrait of one of the most extraordinary
women of the 20th century.''
The Kennedys' children, Caroline and John, gave thousands of items to the John
F Kennedy Library Foundation earlier this year, but the former First Lady
directed that the parts of her estate not wanted by her children should be
sold.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inquiry into Brixton speakers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880795</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN inquiry is to be held into whether speakers at a demonstration incited the
violence incited the latest Brixton riot.
The announcement was made as Home Secretary Michael Howard toured the south
London community yesterday after a night of violence was sparked by the death
of a black man held in police custody.
Mr Howard also applauded police handling of the riot. He said: ``I want to pay
tribute to the courage and professionalism of the police for the way in which
they brought last night's disturbances under control.''
Mr Howard added: ``There can be no excuse whatever for the lawlessness which
took place in Brixton last night.''
Earlier, Metropolitan Police Commissioner Sir Paul Condon said that the inquiry
into the disturbances would examine whether speeches made earlier in the
evening were inflammatory, as well as looking at other offences.
Sir Paul told a news conference at Scotland Yard that the disturbances, sparked
by the death in police custody last week of 26-year-old Wayne Douglas, were a
``setback'' for the people of Brixton, though not on the scale of riots of 1981
or 1985.
``It wasn't Brixton that rioted last night, it was a small minority of thugs
and criminals who as ever look for an opportunity to embark on criminal
exercises,'' he said.
``We have established a criminal inquiry, not just into the criminal offences
on the streets, but into the inflammatory nature of the speeches made outside
the police station and we will be exploring whether criminal offences of
incitement and other offences were committed.''
Sir Paul did not refer to any of the people who addressed the crowd by name.
But one of the most outspoken of those who addressed demonstrators, Rudy
Narayan, of protest group Civil Rights UK, said he
Continued from Page 1
stood by his remarks.
Mr Narayan insisted that his speech was ``no more inflammatory than killing a
man in police custody''.
He was quoted as telling at the protest meeting ``The Brixton police are
killers'' and adding: ``And they will not understand what they have done until
one of them has been killed.''
Sir Paul said around 100 people had gathered outside Brixton police station at
about 7pm to protest about Mr Douglas's death.
``Sadly, inflammatory speeches were made at the scene, irresponsible speeches
were made at the scene, outside the police station, then without police
agreement, the crowd was unleashed on a march, a wander about into Brixton,''
he said.
He added: ``They broke through a police cordon, and within a very few minutes
after that, missiles were thrown, and quite severe violence was offered to
police.
``From that point onwards, sporadic violence and looting took place, and we
strongly believe that shots were fired, perhaps as many as three, not
necessarily at or in the direction of police, but we believe shots were fired.''
He said three police officers were injured. One had a broken collar-bone and
other injuries, another had an eye injury, and a third had injuries to his
head. At least eight or nine civilians were injured, some in the course of the
looting. Some 22 people were arrested for a variety of offences.
About 50 business premises were damaged, three public houses were attacked, and
several vehicles either turned over, set on fire, or damaged.
Sir Paul said that Wayne Douglas's death was sad but it had to be remembered
that at the time of his arrest he was wanted for criminal offences, that it was
alleged that just before his arrest he had carried out a robbery at knifepoint,
and that when he was later confronted by police, he brandished a knife at
officers.
Mr Douglas was disarmed by ``courageous officers,'' Sir Paul said.
Asked about the wisdom of using American-style long-handled batons, Sir Paul
said there was no evidence to suggest ``that this man's death is anything other
than a tragedy involving a weakness to his heart''.
Mr Douglas, 33, was restrained by officers equipped with long batons for
possession of a knife, CS gas, and cannabis. He suffered a fractured skull and
died in hospital five days later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bombs greet the peace signing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>our Foreign Staff</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880796</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ink was barely dry on the peace treaty yesterday when sporadic violence
flared again in Bosnia, highlighting the task ahead for Nato troops.
There were explosions in districts of Sarajevo, government troops firing on a
French UN helicopter, and Croat forces clashing with pro-government Islamic
fighters.
In Paris, meanwhile, leaders from former Yugoslavia signed the Bosnian treaty,
formally ending Europe's worst conflict since the Second World War and opening
the way for thousands of Nato troops to move into the shattered country.
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, Croatian President Franjo Tudjman, and
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic signed the accord before the leaders of
major powers including US President Bill Clinton and Mr Major.
All of them pledged their support for the tough task of making the agreement a
reality, urging the warring parties to put their enmity behind them after more
than three years of war and promising military, financial, and moral support.
``I feel like a man who is drinking a bitter but useful medicine,'' said Mr
Izetbegovic.
Mr Milosevic urged Serbs in Sarajevo not to fear for their future under the
Muslim-led government and to trust the world and Yugoslavia to protect their
rights. ``I wish to use this opportunity to address especially the citizens of
Sarajevo. There is no room for fear or worry,'' he said after the signing. ``It
is clear that the war is over.'' His words were echoed by Bosnian Serb
``vice-president'' Nikola Koljevic who said he was given assurances in Paris
that those Sarajevo Serbs who wanted to stay on under Bosnian government
authority would be protected.
Some diplomats have speculated Mr Koljevic would replace Bosnian Serb leader
Radovan Karadzic, an indicted war criminal who must step down from office under
the Dayton agreement.
``Seize this chance and make it work,'' Mr Clinton said. ``You can do nothing
to erase the past but you can do everything to build the future. Do not let
your children down.''
Between two and three million people have been displaced by the war and some
200,000 have been killed. No-one was killed yesterday, but violence flared
again.
A UN official reported that Bosnian government troops had fired on a French
army helicopter. Four bullets hit it.
Moments after the treaty was signed, explosions rocked two frontline areas in
snow-bound Sarajevo, where the Bosnian Serbs have been protesting in vain
against the terms of the peace deal. There were no reports of casualties.
Two rocket-propelled grenades landed near a Jewish cemetery in the city centre
where Serb and government trenches are close together.
Four more fell near a bridge marking the division between the Serb-held suburb
of Grbavica and government-held parts of the city, and a suspected mortar bomb
slammed into the roof of a house in a southern district.
Officials of the Muslim-led government said Bosnian Serb forces fired the
grenades.
Bosnian government officials also reported that Bosnian Croat militia and
Islamic mujahideen forces clashed in central Bosnia.
In a statement issued through the French Foreign Ministry, the leaders of all
the factions involved urged their forces on the ground to ``have faith in the
future''.
In recalling the horrors of the past, such as children whose playgrounds were
shelled, young girls raped, victims piled in mass graves, ethnic cleansing,
floods of refugees and starvation, Mr Clinton and others said those accused of
war crimes must be brought to justice.
Negotiated last month in Dayton, Ohio, the agreement divides Bosnia almost
equally between Serbs and a Muslim-Croat alliance but guarantees its
international borders and fragile statehood.
French President Jacques Chirac, who hosted the signing in his Elysee palace,
said it was time to ``turn the page of war''.
The three presidents from the former Yugoslavia stiffly exchanged handshakes
with one another and with the other leaders as they stood up, unsmiling, from
signing the treaty.
Mr Clinton, Mr Major, Mr Chirac, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and Russian
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin then signed as co-sponsors.
Mr Izetbegovic pointedly failed to applaud the speeches of his fellow leaders.
PATRICK BROGAN writes from Washington: Congress gave its half-hearted support
to Mr Clinton's Bosnia policy last night. The Senate voted to support him, with
qualifications, and the House voted not to oppose him.
The White House noted that this was the best it could get, and accepted that
very tepid measure of assent. The Senate had earlier rejected a proposal to cut
off funding, and then voted 69 to 30 to acquiesce in sending troops, under
certain conditions.
The Senate resolution provides that troops may be deployed for ``approximately
one year'' and that there should be an international effort, led by the US, to
arm, train and equip the Bosnian army. Mr Clinton has accepted these terms.
