<HEADLINE>Phone dispute ends amicably</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880797</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS should find it easier to take their telephone numbers with them when
they switch from British Telecom to rival cable firms in the wake of new rules
proposed yesterday.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission settled a dispute between BT and industry
regulator the Office of Telecommunications (Oftel) by setting out a framework
for how the costs of switching the numbers should be split between the
different companies.
The MMC decided BT should bear 70% of the costs - which average out at around
#12 a time - and the new company 30%.
Both Oftel and BT were pleased by the decision.
``This is a good day for customers,'' said Oftel head Don Cruickshank. ``I am
pleased to announce that the MMC has endorsed my view that number portability
is in the public interest and that BT should not be able to recover from other
operators all its costs in bringing about portability.''
However, BT said it had been unhappy not about who paid what but because Oftel
wanted ``unfettered powers'' to decide.
``We feel it's a very fair result,'' said a spokeswoman. ``There are now firm
rules about how the costs will be apportioned...... MMC have ruled that there
will be firm rules and (Oftel) cannot just take such action as it thinks fit.''
Studies have shown that rival cable firms can offer substantial savings in
bills and Oftel argued that BT's stance was making it harder for consumers to
enjoy the benefits of competition.
</TEXT>
