<HEADLINE>Scientists try to calm beef fears</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880798</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS last night were still refusing to accept the Government's latest
attempt to reassure the public that British beef is safe to eat.
Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg and various Government experts spent almost
two hours with journalists yesterday trying to demonstrate that the latest
scare over BSE, the so-called mad cow disease which has seen wholesale beef
sales reported to have plummeted by as much 25%, was unfounded.
He also insisted that the Government had not lost the confidence of the public
- even though many education authorities have taken beef products off school
menus.
Meanwhile, Scottish farmers are fighting back and have called for the National
Farmers Union to use high-profile personalities to promote beef.
Members of Dumfries and Stewartry Area of the NFU have urged the union to
commission figures such as former Scotland rugby captain Gavin Hastings to
advertise beef and, they hope, convince the public that eating it is not
dangerous.
Within hours of Mr Hogg's meeting, 200 more schools had banned beef and the
Consumers' Association said the Government had done nothing to reassure the
public.
Chief Medical Officer Kenneth Calman, Chief Veterinary Officer Keith Meldrum,
Food Minister Angela Browning, and Professor John Pattison, head of the
committee which monitors BSE for the Government, were among those called up by
Mr Hogg to give their backing to beef.
They emphasised again that there was no evidence to suggest BSE could be
transmitted to humans and said safety nets had been imposed because the parts
of cattle which might pose even the slightest theoretical risk had been banned
from the food chain.
However, their message did not convince councillors in Dorset, who decided to
take beef off menus in 200 schools.
Ms Diane McCrea, head of food and health at the Consumers' Association, said:
``This does nothing to reassure consumers who are confused about the potential
risks of BSE and worried about what they are eating,'' she said.
</TEXT>
