<HEADLINE>GPs `face conflicts' over cholesterol</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880799</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROUTINE health checks aimed at galvanising people into healthy habits are
probably a waste of money, pioneers of health promotion in Glasgow are
admitting today.
A huge investigation into the effects of workplace health education and
cholesterol testing has shown small changes which would be massively outweighed
by the cost.
Now Dr Phil Hanlon, who led the investigation for Glasgow University's
department of public health, is warning that GPs face a barrage of conflicting
pressures over the next few months.
On the one side is the latest confirmation that cholesterol levels do little to
influence people's behaviour.
On the other side will be the drug companies who make the statin family of
cholesterol-reducing drugs, riding on the back of the West of Scotland Coronary
Prevention Study which demonstrated last month that one such product,
simvastatin, reduced the risk of heart attacks by a third in middle-aged men
with moderately excessive cholesterol levels.
</TEXT>
