<HEADLINE>Bid to defeat justice case `not proven' Police officer cleared of corruption</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880800</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GRAMPIAN Police officer was cleared of charges of corruption and attempting
to defeat the ends of justice, at the High Court in Aberdeen yesterday.
The jury of nine women and five men took two hours and 10 minutes to decide
that Constable Neil Cooper, 36, should go free.
He had denied throughout his 17-day trial that he failed to fulfil his duty as
a police officer by not investigating a crime committed by drug dealer Ronald
Cormack.
Cormack is currently serving a 15-year sentence imposed earlier this year for
drug and firearms offences.
It was alleged Mr Cooper, of Springdale Crescent, Aberdeen, had told him he was
to be investigated and to get rid of any firearms he had and, prior to
interviewing him, told him the questions he would be asked and advised him of
the answers he should give.
The jury unanimously found the charge not proven.
He was also charged with failing in his duty, with intent to defeat the ends of
justice, by not reporting or investigating the involvement of Cormack in a
housebreaking in which he told him he had taken part.
The jury found Mr Cooper not guilty of that charge by a majority and returned
the same verdict on the third charge, that he corruptly accepted #6000 and a
number of subsequent payments for providing Cormack with details of police
intelligence about his drug-dealing operations.
Mr Cooper, who along with three other officers still faces possible dismissal
from Grampian Police under disciplinary proceedings, showed no emotion as the
jury foreman read out the verdicts.
However, as she read out ``not guilty'' to the third charge, his 34-year-old
wife Catriona burst into tears and other friends and family members applauded
and cheered.
After being told by Lord Macfadyen he was free to go, Mr Cooper left the dock
turning to say ``Thank you'' to the jury as he went.
Afterwards, with his wife by his side as he left court, he said: ``I basically
just wish to thank my wife, my family, my friends, some close colleagues from
Grampian Police who have stuck by me through all this, and especially my legal
team for their efforts throughout my case.
``I at no time doubted that I would be cleared of these charges and I am
relieved the jury saw the case in exactly the same manner as I saw it and that
this ordeal is finally all over after a long, long year.''
The couple have a two-year-old son Stuart, and his wife said she was simply
``relieved''. Mr Cooper said the length of time the case had been hanging over
him had imposed a tremendous strain.
Other than ``to go for a pint'', he had no plans for the future and did not
know if he would be able to resume his police career.
``I have absolutely no idea,'' he said. ``It is not in my hands at the moment.
All I have focused on up to this point in time is seeing this trial through. I
have not looked beyond today to be honest.''
Mr Cooper was arrested in January after a three-week investigation by officers
from Strathclyde Police, who were called in by Grampian's chief constable
following Cormack's arrest.
Mr Cooper and two other officers, Sergeant Hamish Moir, 36, and Constable James
Grimmer, 35, subsequently appeared in court.
At that stage, Mr Cooper and Mr Moir were alleged to have attempted to pervert
the course of justice by inciting someone to fabricate evidence.
Mr Cooper was also charged with supplying cannabis resin and attempting to
defeat the ends of justice.
Mr Grimmer appeared on a separate petition charged with reset and possessing
cannabis.
All three, along with Constable Colin Clark, who faced no charges, were
suspended on full pay, and remain so.
Yesterday, a spokesman for the Crown Office said: ``Crown counsel are giving
further consideration to the cases against the other officers.'' No decision on
internal police disciplinary proceedings will be made until all the outstanding
criminal proceedings have been completed.
Following yesterday's verdict, Grampian's deputy chief constable David Garbutt
said: ``I am more than satisfied that the actions of my senior officers in
beginning this investigation have been fully justified.
``During the past year, all staff in the organisation have had to live and work
with the unsettling effects of such an investigation and the possibility that
criminal proceedings could be taken against some of their colleagues.
``This has, understandably, affected staff morale in many areas but it is a
tribute to those staff that their efforts to provide a first-class policing
service have continued unabated and that the same period has seen many new
initiatives and innovative projects introduced in the force.
``The four officers who were subject to the initial investigation last January
remain suspended from duty pending a decision on any internal disciplinary
proceedings which may follow.
``This decision will not be made until all the outstanding criminal matters are
formally completed.''
The discipline authority for Grampian Police is the deputy chief constable and
the decision whether or not to instigate disciplinary proceedings rests with
him.
</TEXT>
