<HEADLINE>Deedee Cuddihy considers the small-bang theory as Jennifer Cunningham lifts the lid on Christmas fare Now try pulling the other one</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Deedee Cuddihy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880801</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRISTMAS crackers seem to be a peculiarly British institution. To some of us,
they are as essential a part of the festivities as the tree and the presents.
Aficionados will have noticed a change over the years, from crackers which held
the flimsiest of hats and plastic novelties to the current trend towards more
substantial and sophisticated contents such as playing cards, tool kits, and
mulled wine mix.
We gathered together eight varieties of cracker on sale this Christmas at major
high street stores and presented them for testing to Dounja (who is from
Luxembourg and had never experienced crackers before), Bob, Graeme, Chris,
Kenny, and Mil at the Glasgow School of Art who, as product design students,
may well be the cracker creators of the future.
They gave marks out of ten for packaging, bang, joke, hat, and gift.
Woolworth's ``Gold Star'' family crackers
A dozen for #4.99, approximately 41p each, gold stars on red and green shiny
background.
A substantial looking, modern cracker, with mediocre bang and gifts: shoehorn,
card trick, plastic necklace (already broken). No jokes but dull general
knowledge questions, eg ``Who led the Labour Party before Harold Wilson?''.
Tissue hats on the thin side. Average cracker, but a bit disappointing.Score:
24 out of 50.
Woolworth's ``Poinsettia'' luxury crackers
Six for #7.99, approximately #1.33 each, gold and tartan with tartan bows.
Look nice and Christmassy, feel weighty. Rubbish bang, nice tartan hat, gifts
of shaving brush, tool kit (plastic holder already ripped), hand lotion, look
exciting but don't bear close inspection. Dreadful jokes. Reasonable
value.Score: 31 out of 50.
BHS luxury ``Starburst'' crackers
Twelve for #10, approximately 83p each, shiny gold on pink or purple.
Look and feel good, good bang, excellent designer hat, fair jokes, eg ``How do
you stop a herd of elephants from charging? Take away their credit cards''.
Good gifts, tape measure, candle, whistle, cards. Score: 35 out of 50.
House of Fraser luxury ``Mistletoe'' crackers
Twelve for #13, approximately #1.08 each, shiny mistletoe print with green
ribbons.
Traditional Christmas look, feels substantial. Good bang, more cards but in
plastic box, lovely pearl necklace, decorated tin with lid (doesn't work too
well). Traditional tissue-paper hat very boring. Good jokes. An OK cracker if a
bit dull.Score: 36 out of 50.
Boots ``Deluxe'' crackers
Six for #13, approximately #2.16 each, copper and gold foil with scroll print.
Presentation could be better. Poor bang. Excellent foil hats. Exciting gifts,
better than expected, travelling board game, velvet bag with earrings. Good to
see a drawing with the jokes. Score: 39 out of 50.
Boots ``Family'' crackers
Twelve for #10, approximately 83p each, green and red foil with pattern.
Good presentation, good bang, excellent foil hats, gifts not too exciting: more
playing cards, tool kit. Poor jokes, eg ``What's white, round, and giggles? A
tickled onion''. Score: 35 out of 50.
Marks &amp; Spencer ``Party'' crackers
Twelve for #13, approximately #1.08 each, including matching napkins and place
cards, holly pattern on white with green and gold ribbons.
Look and feel good. Matching napkins a good feature. Mediocre bang. Hat matches
cracker and napkin, equals ``holly overkill'', but nice all the same. The most
unusual gifts: keyring, false teeth paper-clip, picture frame. The best jokes
because they're visual, a bit like Gary Larson. Score: 40 out of 50.
Marks &amp; Spencer ``Children's'' crackers
Six for #10, approximately #1.66 each, snowmen and Santa characters with gold
bows and holly.
Look really nice, the best yet. Mediocre bang, old jokes - ``What waves a magic
wand and goes from Dover to Calais? A cross channel fairy'' - but children will
probably like them. Tartan hats too sophisticated for kids. Great gifts for all
the family: tiny water pistol (really works), pack of chewing gum trick, toy
car that whizzes backwards.
Score: 40 out of 50.
</TEXT>
