<HEADLINE>World `set to face food crisis'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880802</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE world will be unable to feed itself in the next century unless it curbs
relentless population growth and adopts new land management methods, it was
claimed yesterday.
Professor Jeff Maxwell, director of the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute in
Aberdeen, said that enough people to fill another Edinburgh are born every
three days and our capacity to provide food for them all will not be able to
keep pace.
``In fact we appear to be doing our best to reduce the long-term ability of our
planet to produce food rather than the other way round,'' he said.
Delivering a lecture at the Royal Botanic Garden in Edinburgh as part of a
series on bioscience in Scotland, he said that between six and seven million
hectares of land was lost each year because of unchecked soil erosion.
``Sadly, the list of past and present land use mistakes goes on and on,'' he
said.
Professor Maxwell said a more equitable redistribution of resources, even if
achievable, would not be enough to solve the problem in the twenty-first
century because the world's population was set to double over the next 50 or 60
years.
The gross imbalance would inevitably lead to political conflict unless
countries were able to control populations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
