<DOCNO>GH951215-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major arrives in Madrid with a `look before you leap' warning on monetary union Single-currency caution urged</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880803</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Madrid
MR Major arrived all guns blazing in Madrid last night for the most important
EU summit for years. He accused his EU partners of failing to understand the
full implications of forging ahead with a single currency before the majority
of member states become willing and able.
The Prime Minister, as usual in Europe these days, finds himself with few
friends on the issue.
He is known to be increasingly concerned that the pound could suffer not just
from exchange rate instability if it remains outside the planned single
currency but that there could also be a political price to pay if Britain chose
to exercise its right to opt out.
Mr Major delivered his ``look before you leap'' message on his arrival to take
part in the two-day summit which is due to hammer out final details of the
single currency programme - and give the currency a name at last.
If Chancellor Helmut Kohl has his way, Germany and hard-currency Benelux
countries will lock their exchange rates until 2002, when the new coinage will
be presented to the European public.
Mr Major fears increasingly that a small group of member states sharing one
currency might begin voting together in the EU against the interests of those
countries which choose to remain outside the new system meantime.
Britain's response to this threat is to get the ground rules laid out now, if
possible. ``If a small core of countries behaved in this way, it would be a
radical undermining of the way the European Union has always worked,'' a
British official argued.
Mr Major said: ``I think what we have to discuss in Madrid are the questions
which remain unanswered about the single currency. Many have been answered but
what has not been is what the implications will be if a small number of
countries goes ahead, and not, as was originally envisaged, a very large number
goes ahead.''
He denied his words were a tactic to put the brake on a policy to which the
Government still refuses to commit the country: ``It is not a question of
slowing down. It is a question of making sure that all the implications of
proceeding are understood. I do not believe they are.''
Mr Major went on: ``There are very many issues about the single currency which
have not been examined. If a small number of countries goes ahead, the
implications of that will not only be for those countries taking part. The
implications will apply to the rest of the EU. The ramifications are very wide
indeed. We need to examine all those ramifications.''
Tory Euro-sceptics will be pleased by the Prime Minister's stand at the summit
but nothing Mr Major says this weekend in Madrid will budge the majority from
their determination to meet the 1999 target for going ahead with the single
currency.
French President Jacques Chirac is bound to play down the long-term
implications for the currency of the deep economic crisis his country is facing
thanks to a public backlash against his government's belt-tightening measures.
The problems confronting the single currency will dominate the summit, although
there will be important talks too on next year's launch of an intergovernmental
conference to shape Europe's future.
n A deal which side-steps British objections to EU laws on parental leave for
fathers and mothers is due to be signed today in Brussels. The Government
blocked an accord between the 15 member states, triggering the use of
Maastricht provisions allowing employers and unions to negotiate social
protection measures themselves.
The deal provides a minimum of three months off work without pay to care for a
child at any period in the first eight years after birth or adoption.
The TUC predicts that pressure in the market-place will spread the benefit to
Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
