<HEADLINE>Call for Howard to appear in deportation case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880804</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JUDGE was asked yesterday to order the Home Secretary to appear before a
court to answer a claim that he has committed contempt in an immigration case.
Mr Michael Howard was alleged to be in breach of an undertaking not to take
steps to remove anyone from the country until court proceeedings are concluded.
Lord Gill was told at the Court of Session that Mr Jaswinder Singh's removal
from the UK had been ordered by the Home Office and he had lost an appeal to an
adjudicator in October.
Last Friday, Mr Singh's petition for judicial review was dismissed at the Court
of Session, but, later that same day, he raised a new petition on different
grounds.
Mr Singh, of Merrygold Square, Ayr, was arrested the next day and detained at
Greenock Prison, but released on Monday this week when he was mistaken for
another Mr Jaswinder Singh who had been granted interim liberation.
Mr Andrew Hardie QC, Dean of the Faculty of Advocates, appearing for Mr Singh
explained the Home Secretary had given an undertaking that no steps would be
taken to remove from the country anyone who had a judicial review petition
before the courts until the court proceedings were completed.
Mr Hardie argued that detaining Mr Singh had been a step towards removing him
from the country. He added: ``It is, on the face of it, contempt of this court
and I would invite your lordship to ordain the Minister to appear or be
represented at this court.''
Miss Susan O'Brien, counsel for the Home Secretary, said that the nature of the
undertaking, which was regularly given in immigration cases, was that until a
judicial review had been resolved the immigration authorities would refrain
from removal or deportation.
She added, however: ``No undertaking is given to refrain from detaining a
person who may otherwise be lawfully detained.''
She explained that what had happened in this case was the authorities had been
given notice of Mr Singh's new petition, but were not aware it was the same
person who had another petition dismissed.
Miss O'Brien added: ``The first petition having been dismissed, it was assumed,
correctly in my submission, that the petitioner had reverted to the status of
illegal entrant and was liable to removal. He was detained the next day in
preparation for re-moval.'' At the Home Office in London 17 people were
employed on correspondence relating to people called Singh, and there were
about 2500 files in the immigration department in the name of Jaswinder Singh.
In the present case, after officials had established that it was the same Singh
involved in both petitions, they immediately stopped measures to have him
removed from the country.
Lord Gill will give a ruling later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Downbeat in a grey capital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>bosnian peace deal</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880805</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BELGRADE.
CITIZENS of Belgrade, struggling with a war-exhausted economy, welcomed the
peace signing with few apparent regrets that it ends their dream of a Greater
Serbia.
This capital of Serbian-dominated Yugoslavia means ``white city'', but the
mood
here is chiefly grey, reflecting a mixture of uncertainty and perhaps
opportunity. Trade, not war, is the new byword as the generals retreat to the
sidelines.
Nationalist slogans, evoking centuries of Serb pride, have been replaced by
catchy TV commercial jingles keyed to money-making themes: ``Marketing,
marketing!.
Belgrade has been tainted with Bosnian Serb atrocities and ethnic cleansing.
As the pan-Serb vision faded with the Paris ceremony, Belgrade's citizens
trudged through drab shopping avenues cloaked in Balkan mid-winter snow to buy
newspapers.
People, whose daily lives have been reduced to meagre levels from a
once-prosperous state, queued at kiosks to read headlines trumpeting neither
victory nor defeat, but hope.
``It is good that peace has finally been signed,'' one man said at a newstand.
``After four years of war, this is the only positive happening,'' another said.
A woman nearby strongly disagreed: ``The first mistake was that Yugoslavia
(originally) was formed of six republics, six governments with six nations. We
should have had one state with one government.''
``The biggest mistake,'' she added, ``is that Serbs are being thrown out of
Sarajevo. Serbs and Muslims will never live together.''
Foreign businessmen, bringing proposals for trade deals, are arriving daily on
flights that did not exist just a few months ago.
Serbia is contemplating a major privatisation drive to revamp a communist-era
state economy now moribund after the impact of three years of United Nations
sanctions.
In another time, perhaps, Greater Serbia will surface again as a political
goal, but for now the idea has passed.
</TEXT>
