<HEADLINE>Post Office criticised over policy on drinking at work</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880806</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Post Office has been criticised for putting up with nightshift postal staff
drinking before coming to work and during breaks, then sacking them for
drunkenness.
An industrial tribunal in Glasgow heard evidence of a culture of heavy drinking
among staff, particularly at the George Square head office.
Workers were allowed to go out drinking during their breaks as management tried
to stop drinking at the sorting office. One group of workers were caught
drinking in a locker room.
Eric Frew, sacked after having seven vodkas and a half pint of beer before and
during his shift at the sorting office, had gone to the tribunal. It ruled that
his sacking was unfair and awarded him #2428 compensation, but held him 60% to
blame.
Mr Frew, 36, of York Drive, Burnside, Glasgow, had three vodkas before his
night shift and another four along with the half pint during a 20-minute break
around midnight.
Around 6.30 next morning, a manager noticed his speech was slurred, his eyes
glazed, he was unsteady on his feet, and his sorting rate was slow.
He had a similar offence on his record which was due to expire four days later.
In its decision the tribunal said it found it strange in today's industrial
climate that the Post Office accepted workers arriving for work on the
nightshift having been drinking then allowed them to go out and drink again
during their break.
``To be so tolerant of drinking within working hours and yet to punish
drunkenness - even repeated drunkenness - so heavily was not the action of a
reasonable employer and made the whole dismissal unfair,'' the tribunal added.
</TEXT>
