<HEADLINE>Drowned-out voice in the battle of the peacocks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880807</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the votes were counted in the ballot for the Labour Party's candidate in
Govan, one group of party workers knew they would be disappointed, whatever the
outcome.
To the supporters of Mrs Margaret Curran this was not a contest between left
and right, Old Labour and New, traditional trade unionism and the business face
of socialism. It was organised power bases versus community activism; a
completely new agenda versus politically acceptable reform. They knew they
hadn't a hope but they were damn well going to give it a shout.
They emerged, according to both opponents, with a lot of friends. How true
those friends will be remains to be tested.
Mrs Curran was the inspirational force behind the Scottish Labour Women's
Caucus, of which she is now convener. Active in Labour politics since her
student days, she had a break from political activity when her children, now
eight and six, were very young. She returned a few years ago with the different
perspective of the outsider to be deeply angered by the way the women were
``constantly mugged'' by the system.
For any constituency selection committee, her CV is promising. Lecturer in
community education after a solid grounding as community worker, a sterling
track record as party activist. Age 37 - oh, and mother of two primary
school-age children.
``It was tempting to leave them to it but it would have been misinterpreted. It
would have been assumed that we did not have a suitable candidate and, in the
end, it was inconceivable that we could allow these two men to go by
unchallenged,'' she said yesterday, before conceding that they knew they never
had the slightest chance of winning.
``To have contested on the basis of having an equal chance, I would have had to
have given up my job for two years and to have hardly seen my family.''
The bitterest disappointment for Mrs Curran was the number of women who said
they would not vote for her because they thought it would let the other man in.
``These were women I have shared a platform with in the campaign for 50/50
representation in a Scottish Parliament. Anyone who said they were voting for
Mike because he was the left-wing candidate could equally well have voted for
me.
``I am passionately interested in benefits, community care, and poverty, the
whole social agenda, but these are invisible issues - although to women they
are the vital ones. If we continue to legitimise men, we will reinforce the
problem that they set the agenda. The women's agenda is the world's agenda.''
For the first time in the selection process, the two main candidates produced
printed campaign leaflets, which the women's group - without even a full-time
organiser at Scottish level - had no possibility of matching. To the
disappointment of Mrs Curran and her supporters, the outside view was equally
traditional.
``The media have colluded with the male agenda that this is a political boxing
match of a couple of peacocks vying with each other,'' she said.
She added: ``People say I am a one-issue candidate but if I was only standing
on women's issues I would not be in the Labour Party. I have spoken strongly on
social policy and economic policy but I believe that if people don't take
account of the women's dimension they are only seeing half the problem.''
Real proof of her political skill, however, comes when she abandons the urgent
oratory, which is clearly second nature, for a tribute to the other contestants
as generous as it is pragmatic: ``Mike has an excellent record as a
constituency MP and Sarwar has done equally good work as a councillor and has a
vision well beyond the local.''
Whichever one was chosen, she added, she would be out canvassing for him at the
next election.
Nevertheless, there are some questions she and her supporters want answered
about qualifications for voting in selection contests and they would be
interested in the mechanisms which enabled far more than the usual number of
new members to join at the last moment.
They also have a message for party members in other constituencies: ``It is not
enough just to agree with us. More people have to put their money where their
mouth is. The Labour Party, for example, still has a lot of work to do about
how to deliver an equal number of men and women to a Scottish Parliament.
``All-women shortlists are not about feminism but about power and what women
would do with power. At a local level, women are likely to use their experience
of listening to institute a dialogue with the local community and the local
party and a feminist going into the Scottish Parliamentary Labour Party would
have more effect than five male MPs.''
</TEXT>
