n GOLLY, he's still around! Despite a decade and more of political correctness,
the Robertson's golliwog is alive and well, to the chagrin of Scotland's ethnic
community.
What's even more narking right now is that the notorious symbol has reappeared
on jars of Christmas mincemeat - when we're all supposed to be celebrating
harmony and goodwill.
Even more perplexing is the fact golly is enjoying star billing with Save The
Children: the charity has allowed its name and symbol to appear on the
Robertson's label in a Christmas card promotion netting a 15p donation until
the end of this month. It also features an offer for 21 golly brooches.
``We couldn't afford to pass up the opportunity,'' a Save The Children
spokeswoman told Check-Out. ``But we're sorry to have offended anyone.''
They certainly have - including Edinburgh District councillor Philip Attridge,
who intends raising the matter with the city's race relations sub-committee.
``I'm amazed to discover this offensive doll has been resurrected. I thought it
had disappeared along with Black Sambo. I advise shoppers to buy another brand
of mincemeat.''
His outrage may be shared by Princess Anne. It can scarcely help the President
of Save the Children in her mission to Afro-Caribbean missions.
n PILLOW talk goes electronic with what's hailed as an ``incredible
breakthrough'' in personal audio.
If you're being kept awake by festive partygoers, the Sound Pillow could
certainly help you turn a deaf ear, with soothing music or a relaxation tape
gently wafting you to sleep.
A lead from the non-allergenic pillow connects via an attached jack to cassette
players, CD machines or a TV set, transmitting the sound through stereo
speakers inside the hollow fill pillow, without disturbing anyone else.
Sound Pillow costs #15.95 (including p&amp;p) from Pure-Tec, Isberg House, Kingston
Street, Hull HU1 2DB. Phone-order on 01482 860860 or see and hear it at Gadget
Shop, St Enoch Shopping Centre, Glasgow.
n BY Boxing Day it's a sad fact that thousands of powered toys, games, personal
stereos, and other Christmas goodies will be out for the count. Only the
atmosphere will be charged, with recrimination; the batteries will be exhausted
by hours of frenzied activity the previous day.
Battery Manager Ultra, which claims to be the first fully automatic recharger,
offers a solution. Developed by Innovations, who proved it was possible to
recharge ordinary batteries, the compact, stylish unit recognises a range of
different types and sizes of battery and adjusts the charging process
accordingly, handling up to four at a time. As well as huge long-term savings,
the charger is environmentally friendly, reducing problems of battery disposal.
Battery Manager Ultra is #29.95 at John Lewis, Edinburgh and Aberdeen; Tandy
and Powerstore, or phone 01793 433500 to order.
n YOU may get sympathy, but don't expect tea at the crematorium: according to
funeral plan operator Chosen Heritage, the results of its latest survey are
``far from comforting''. One in 10 crematoria surveyed had no shelter or
waiting facilities, while only one in seven provided a phone. Hot drinks?
``Wait until the wake,'' was the usual response.
While a crematorium at Sunderland gets Brownie points for laying on TV for
visitors, these grave deficiencies suggest most mourners would be well advised
to pack a shooting stick and black coffee when they pay their last respects.
