<HEADLINE>Life for man whose victim may still die Jealous chef attacked lover with hammer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880809</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JEALOUS chef who inflicted catastrophic injuries on his lover in a brutal and
sustained hammer attack, was yesterday jailed for life for her attempted murder.
The 23-year-old victim's life is still in the balance and a surgeon has
described her injuries as the worst he has seen. Mrs Audrey Clark is paralysed
down the left side of her body and can say just two words - yes and no.
Temporary Judge Alexander Wilkinson told William Munson: ``This is a horrific
case and the attack was a murderous one of a most atrocious kind.
``I can find no way in which this case can be usefully distinguished from a
case of completed murder. You will go to prison for life.''
Munson, 33, admitted repeatedly striking Mrs Clark on the head with a hammer to
her severe injury, permanent disfigurement, permanent impairment, and the
danger of her life, and attempting to murder her.
The attack took place at their home in Linksview House, Edinburgh, on September
1 this year.
Mr Craig Scott, Advocate-depute, told the High Court in Edinburgh that Munson
and his victim had lived together as common law husband and wife for five years
but their relationship was a turbulent one.
There were numerous separations and, in February this year, the couple again
split up. The following month, Mrs Clark married another man.
In July, she and Munson began living together again but, by September, the
relationship had deteriorated to the extent that Mrs Clark was seeing her
husband.
On the afternoon of September 1, Munson met a friend in the street and said:
``I have done her in.'' Police forced their way into the house to find the
victim lying in a pool of blood.
Munson told police: ``I think I have murdered my girlfriend. I was smoking hash
and she started popping tablets and we started arguing. That's when I went into
the cupboard and got the hammer.''
The Advocate-depute explained that when Mrs Clark was admitted to hospital it
was obvious that she had suffered severe brain and skull injuries.
There were 18 to 20 lacerations to the skull, and during surgery at least 36
fragments of bone were found. The skull had been shattered in several places
and driven into the brain.
Mr Scott added: ``It is the consultant's view that if she survives she will
have major disabilities. He has been a neuro-surgeon for 15 years and it is the
worst kind of injury he has seen.''
Because of the severity of the attack, doctors had been unable to close the
victim's wounds properly and she would need further major plastic surgery to
reconstruct her skull.
``The surgeon indicates that her life is still in serious danger,'' Mr Scott
added. ``As he puts it, she could die any day.''
Mr Steven MacGibbon, defence counsel, described the case as exceptionally
horrific and tragic.
He said Munson was emotionally immature but added: ``He accepts and
understands, only too well, that the injuries he inflicted were appalling and
the consequences catastrophic.''
From the moment Munson met Mrs Clark he was besotted by her and was jealous of
the man she married.
``He loves Audrey and will do until the day he dies,'' added Mr MacGibbon.
During the weeks before the hammer attack, there were constant arguments and
Munson feared Mrs Clark was about to leave him again for the man she had
married in March.
``Her attitude was to taunt him and compare him unfavourably with the other
man.''
On the day of the assault, both had been smoking cannabis and she told Munson
that he would not be spending Christmas with her and their three-year-old son.
``That was the catalyst for the volcano, which had been bubbling for some time,
to erupt.''
</TEXT>
