<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bitter fall-out looms for Labour over Watson-Sarwar contest for the redrawn Govan constituency Knife edge to a dead heat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880810</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE big clue was the look on the face of Govan MP Michael Watson - glazed,
haggard and unsettled. And he was the winner.
For the rest, there was the wailing of Asian women on the stairs, the bristling
anger of some in the immigrant community who saw their democratic ambitions
thwarted, and the sight of the Scottish Labour Party once again fashioning a
rod to beat its own back.
An amazing dead heat in the final 245-all vote, and the banning of 52 voters
considered questionable by Glasgow party official Lesley Quinn, made an appeal
to the party's national executive committee inevitable last night.
But that appeal to Walworth Road in London by candidate Mohammed Sarwar meant
that the party would lock itself into a spiral of bad publicity. Party leader
Tony Blair will be asking why yet again his Scottish redoubt is producing the
wrong kind of headlines.
Councillor Sarwar, the millionaire owner of a cash and carry business, has been
steadily building his political profile in the West of Scotland to the point
where he had become an ideal Labour candidate for Westminster elections.
The problem was that, for reasons to do with the geography of his own support
and the availability of a seat, he was forced to focus on the new Govan
constituency, which was being sought by Mr Watson, whose Glasgow Central
constituency was being scrapped.
In stepped Pollok MP Jimmy Dunnachie to put his hat in the ring, thereby
forcing a full electoral contest betweeen himself, Mr Watson and any other
challenger. He later dropped out of the contest, but by then Councillor Sarwar
was a contender and Mr Watson had a fight on his hands.
It was a dirty campaign, by any standards, particularly those supposedly
espoused by New Labour. While mysteriously unsourced stories appeared in the
press alleging problems with Mr Sarwar's business empire, the Asian councillor
himself succeeded in commanding column inches boosting his profile.
There were two strands to the political contest assiduously fed out to the
media. One version had Councillor Sarwar as a hero among Scottish immigrants, a
self-made millionaire with a social conscience who argued for the minimum wage.
On the other hand, Michael Watson was portrayed as a bright and decent Labour
MP, the very last of the type who should be pushed aside - even to make way for
a candidate with credentials as impressive as those of Councilllor Sarwar.
By the time of yesterday's count journalists and broadcasters were in a feeding
frenzy at the City Halls in Glasgow, where it was almost impossible to get
anywhere near the stairway from which the result of the ballot was to be
announced.
In a strained atmosphere more akin to a parliamentary election result than a
simple candidate selection, there was a gasp when the figures were read out by
the Labour Party's West of Scotland organiser, Lesley Quinn. She, it was, who
had been invested with the power to scrutinise the signatures on postal voting
applications and cross-check them against membership forms.
It was her ruling that 52 of these voting forms were suspect that led to the
final knife-edge figures yesterday. That mulling-over period took several
hours, while the media presence grew and Mr Watson himself left because, he
said, he couldn't stand the tension.
Afterwards he looked queasy, not on account of anything he had done wrong, but
because of the knowledge that there will inevitably be a bitter fall-out from
such a keenly contested campaign, whatever happens to any appeal.
That process is unlikely to overturn a carefully-taken decision and, while the
Labour leadership will be unhappy about the headlines, it would be a surprise
if they intervened in the saga.
As one supporter of Mr Watson said last night: ``All it takes is one vote.''
</TEXT>
