<HEADLINE>Kalashnikov vision for drink drivers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880811</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish public was given one of its most dramatic anti-drink driving
messages yesterday: ``A two-litre car into a bus queue has just as much effect
as a Kalashnikov.''
Chief Superintendent Sandy Forrest, head of Strathclyde Police traffic
department, said the drinking driver might as well gun the bus queue down with
a shotgun or firearm from the car window.
He called for an end to the stigma on reporting drinking friends and colleagues
and reinforced the police theme of calling a cab or taking the bus. ``We are
asking people to be more responsible, to make other arrangements to get home.
It may be inconvenient to use public transport but it is a lot less
inconvenient than losing your licence for two years or ending up in jail.''
The campaign by the eight Scottish forces was hailed yesterday, at its halfway
stage, as a big success. The secretary of the ACPO(S) traffic committee,
Assistant Chief Constable Ian Mackinnon said the fear of being caught was more
evident in this campaign than any of the previous nine.
He revealed that offender profiles had been compiled and were being used to
target particular groups in particular locations at particular times. The most
persistent drink driver is a man, aged between 25 and 29, unemployed and
driving in a built-up area between midnight and 3am on Friday, Saturday, and
Sunday nights.
Mr Mackinnon emphasised that the trend this year was encouraging, with positive
tests down by 0.8% throughout Scotland on the same period last year. One in 69
motorists tested this year was positive compared with one in 43 last year and
one in five 10 years ago when the chief constables began their crusade.
However, drivers in their 20s and 30s are not heeding the message, still
accounting for two thirds of the positive tests. Of the 98 people tested
positive after road accidents, 69% of them were aged between 20 and 30.
The high proportion of repeat offenders are also giving concern, Mr Mackinnon
said.
Of those tested positive, 71 had one or more convictions for drink driving
while nine had more than five convictions for the same offence. In the
campaign's first 20 days, while the percentage of positive tests decreased, the
number of people stopped by the police soared by 58% to 38,137.
The middle aged and elderly still show the lowest number of offenders. The
police warned drivers once again to beware the morning-after effect,
particularly transport workers, delivery drivers, and commuters who might have
visited the pub after work the previous night.
The results of drink driving were revealed dramatically by a 59-year-old woman
whose husband was killed.
Mrs Mary Chisholm's husband, Alex, 63, died after his car was hit in a crash on
the A77 near Glasgow in July. The driver of the other car tested positive for
alcohol and was jailed for five years and given a life ban at the High Court in
Kilmarnock.
The court heard that, at the time of the crash, the driver was already serving
two separate driving bans and had a string of previous convictions for driving
offences both in Scotland and England.
Mrs Chisholm, of Symington, Ayrshire, said: ``I want to forget Christmas this
year. The tree is still up in the loft and, as far as I am concerned, it might
as well stay there.
``I was horrified when I heard Alex was dead. He was a wonderful man who was
loved by his family.
``It's hard to accept he has gone. Thirty-five years is a long time together
and to have him taken away from me in such a senseless way is devastating.
``It has been a terrible blow for the grandchildren especially.''
They still talk about him all the time, they really miss their papa, especially
the two-year-old, Kevin.''
Mrs Chisholm said staff and pupils at Kirkstyle primary school, Kilmarnock,
where Mr Chisholm worked as a janitor, were also stunned by his death.
``They had been planning a retirement fund for Alex when he was due to retire
in two years' time. Instead, they made a collection and used the money to erect
a plaque to his memory in the main school hall to show their respect.''
The Chisholms had two sons and two daughters and 10 grandchildren.
The couple's son-in-law, Mr Andrew McClurg, 38, from Hurlford, Ayrshire, was a
passenger in Mr Chisholm's car and suffered long-term chest injuries when it
crashed.
</TEXT>
