Short leets for
book awards
SHORT leets for the James Tait Black Memorial Prizes, Scotland's oldest book
awards, are announced today. The leets are: Fiction. Anita Brookner, Incidents
in the Rue Laugier; Kazuo Ishiguro, The Unconsoled; Ross Leckie, Hannibal;
Christopher Priest, The Prestige.
Biography. Peter Ackroyd, Blake; Margaret Drabble, Angus Wilson: A Biography;
Gitta Sereny, Albert Speer: His Battle With Truth; John Sutherland, The Life of
Sir Walter Scott. The winners of the two prizes, each worth #3000, will be
announced next month.
Court escape
FOUR prisoners escaped from Dumbarton Sheriff Court yesterday. Two were caught
almost immediately on the towpath at the River Leven and the remaining two in
Dumbarton Road, Glasgow, some hours later.
False rape claim
ELIZABETH Skene, 35, of Bonnybridge, pleaded guilty at Falkirk yesterday to
falsely accusing a man of rape. The case was adjourned until next month for a
psychiatric report.
Plunge man dies
RETIRED miner Tommy Hassall, 74, of Craigie Avenue, Ayr, died in hospital after
falling into the town's harbour and being saved by a fisherman.
Green post
THE director of Dumbarton District Council's environmental protection and
leisure services, Mr John Beveridge, has been appointed regional director for
south-west Scotland with the new Scottish Environmental Protection Agency.
Sex man jailed
A MAN who supplied a 13-year-old girl with drugs before inducing her to commit
a sex act was jailed for 12 months at Cupar. Neil Showell, 24, of Gauldry post
office, Fife, admitted supplying the girl with Temazepam, and using lewd and
libidinous practices towards her.
Centre's award
THE Gyle shopping complex in Edinburgh has won an award for being the most
accessible in Britain. The new awards are sponsored by Healthcare and
Disability Now, a monthly disability newspaper.
