<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fourteen years on, lessons have still to be learned</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>brixton riots</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880813</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LORD Scarman, the octogenarian law lord who headed the inquiry into the 1981
Brixton riots, said yesterday he was ``broken-hearted'' about the most recent
outbreak of violence and that he would be making it his business to find out
the cause.
His report effectively marked a watershed in policing policy, creating a new
ethos of community police work.
What troubles some civil liberties campaigners now, however, is a feeling that
while some of Scarman's principles have been adopted and recognised as good
police practice, those implementing them are doing so in an increasingly
hostile climate, with the Government pushing what are perceived to be more
racist policies such as the asylum Bill and new stop and search laws.
Lord Scarman found that the riots over April 10 to 12 in 1981 had been sparked
by an incident involving an injured young black youth and two police officers,
which some members of the community felt was harassment, and attracted a crowd
of black youths.
In the three days of rioting, 279 policemen and 45 members of the public were
injured, 28 buildings were burned and there was widespread looting.
Lord Scarman found that the police should carry some responsibility for the
outbreak of disorder. They were, he said, partly to blame for the breakdown in
community relations, and there were instances of harassment and racial
prejudice among junior officers on Brixton streets.
Although some people who had given evidence to his inquiry had criticised
Operation Swamp 81, an intense stop and search operation designed to counteract
the ``appalling crime wave in Brixton'', Lord Scarman found that police had
been ``wise'' to continue it during days one and two of the riot.
The main recommendations of his report were: statutory consultative committees
to make the police more accountable; a better co-ordinated attack on inner-city
problems; greater independent oversight of police complaints procedure; longer
and improved police recruit training on dealing with public and preventing and
handling disorder; racially prejudiced behaviour by police to be a dismissal
offence; no reform of the Riot Act.
Other recommendations included an urgent study into ways of improving ethnic
minority recruitment into the police, a greater role for the Commission for
Racial Equality, and scrutiny of the legislation that replaced the formed
``Sus'' law (stop and search powers).
Four years later, Brixton was yet again a scene of violence, this time sparked
by an armed raid which led to the shooting of a black woman, Mrs Cherry Groce.
Part of a new police strategy, the armed raids were aimed at identifying
criminals without engaging in the mass stop-and-search exercises like Swamp
'81, but could at times be violent.
The then Home Secretary Douglas Hurd dismissed the rioting as mindless violence
by unruly criminal elements, but local clergymen blamed poor living conditions
and worsening unemployment.
Wednesday night's riots were apparently sparked by the death in police custody
of a 26-year-old black Brixton man Wayne Douglas.
Conor Foley, policy officer with the civil rights pressure group Liberty, said
yesterday that the rising number of black people who have died in custody,
coupled with allegations of mistreatment of suspected illegal immigrants, and
the virtual reintroduction of stop and search laws under the 1994 Criminal
Justice Public Order Act had heightened tensions.
A resident of Brixton, he sees the problem as lying partly in the growing
numbers of British-born blacks growing up in an increasingly racist climate.
Looking back at Lord Scarman's main recommendations, he says that statutory
consultative committees have not been set up to make the police more
accountable.
Training is better, and senior police officers are making the right noises
about racially prejudiced behaviour by police. But, the Metropolitan Police
Commissioner Paul Condon's remarks about statistics showing that black youths
carry out the highest proportion of muggings damaged community relations
earlier this year and the wounds have not yet healed.
Of this Wednesday's riot, he said: ``It was very clearly politically motivated
- not a gaggle of people going out to rob and steal. It was a demonstration
caused because another person had died in police custody.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Schoolgirl dies from meningitis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880814</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCHOOLGIRL died in hospital yesterday from meningitis, three days before her
16th birthday.
Leanne Lester, a pupil at Banbury School, Oxfordshire, became ill on Monday
night at her home in Marlow Close, Banbury, and died in the town's Horton
General Hospital.
A 14-year-old boy from the same school is recovering in hospital from a less
serious form of the disease and two other pupils are reported to be suffering
similar symptoms.
Leanne's father last night claimed his daughter might have survived if her
school had acted earlier.
Mr Frank Lester, 36, believes all parents at the 1500-pupil Banbury School
should have been told of the meningitis scare on Monday as soon as the
14-year-old boy was admitted to hospital.
He said: ``I don't think sending a letter out to parents 48 hours later is
acting as quickly as possible.''
Mr Lester, who is divorced from Leanne's mother Marie, flew to Banbury from
Glasgow on Wednesday morning to be with his daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In search of the perfect pie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jennifer Cunningham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880815</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHATEVER your preference - roses and poinsettia leaves made from marzipan,
smooth royal icing, or glace fruits topping the richest of fruit mixes - the
commercial bakeries will let you have your cake and eat it.
It's worth reading the contents carefully if you have an anti-cherry contingent
or, more seriously, anyone with an allergy to nuts. Otherwise, by and large,
you get what you pay for in terms of ingredients, size, and decoration.
Skilled decorators can display their own craftsmanship on a variety of bases,
including or excluding alcohol and cherries for example. Those less deft with
the icing bag, but unable to countenance the circumference of uniform piping
around a central cluster of gold foil holly, should check their local baker for
the growing army of home bakers producing professional limited editions.
Few are as eye-catching as the picture-book scenes created by the imaginative
Shirley Lamb, who has just relinquished chairmanship of the British Sugarcraft
Guild. This year she has created cakes in the shape of a chimney, with Santa's
upturned boots waving wildly from the top, and in the form of a Christmas pud
topped with two rascally mice, one still nibbling, one replete.
Prices range from #5.99 for a four-inch chimney to #35 for a large commission.
Supermarket prices range from #1.69 for a 454gm iced fruit bar (Iceland/
Littlewoods) to #10.99 for a 1.36kg soft-iced, decorated square (Tesco).
n Shirley Lamb's cakes are available from Drymen Country Store or to order from
01786 870231.
IF the simple mince pie is more your idea of ideal festive fare, you might like
to take note of the judgments passed on seven varieties by our panel of
tasters. Six members of the cast from the Babes In The Wood panto at the King's
Theatre in Glasgow (running from December 14 to February 3) generously agreed
to give up their lunch hour to undertake the tasting. Oh yes they did!
We started off with Vivienne Carlyle (Maid Marion), Jim Byars (Friar Tuck),
Charles Kerney (the Sheriff of Nottingham - hiss, boo!), and Gordon Kane
(Cedric, the Sheriff's henchman). But Robin Hood (David Greer) and Little John
(Grant Stott) were feeling hungry too. Here's how the pies fared:
n Safeway (budget)
The cheapest in town at six for 57p, approximately 10p each. ``Look at that!
They're so thin there's hardly anything in them! Very unattractive, dry, and
lacking in mince. Hardly worth biting into.''
n Mr Kipling
Cost 89p for six, approximately 15p each. ``Oooh, that's good! Looks nice,
weighs quite a bit. Traditional flavour. Tasty pastry. He does make exceedingly
good pies.''
nCo-op, deep-filled
Cost 79p for six, approximately 13p each and recently voted tops by Egon Ronay.
``Cardboardy, tasteless, a bit stodgy. Looked tempting but didn't fulfil their
promise . . . Just like men,'' according to Maid Marion.
n Organic
from Grass Roots in Woodlands Road, Glasgow. Cost #1.89p for four,
approximately 47p each. ``Very crumbly, colour bad, not like a real mince pie
but an interesting flavour. Might be nice with custard.''
n Marks &amp; Spencer
Deep filled, 99p for six, approximately 16p each. ``The ones with wee nostrils!
Not too sweet, not too stodgy. Heavy on the fruit, light on the pastry, just
the way I like them. An impudent little pie which lived up to its
presumptions.''
n Peckhams luxury, with rum
Cost #1.79p for six, approximately 30p each. ``Looks good outside, strange
appearance inside, like caviar or something. Too sweet, don't like it.''
n Homemade (Herald reporter)
``Flying saucers coming up! Do you want us to be nice or brutally honest? A wee
bit too much pastry, but the intentions were good. The best mince pies I've
tasted made by a reporter. Ah, the coffee, and not a moment too soon.''
</TEXT>
