<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dog rescued from disused mine shaft</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880816</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIREFIGHTERS yesterday rescued a young girl's dog from a collapsed mine shaft
in a five-hour operation.
Kelly Archibald, eight, was broken-hearted after her father told her their Jack
Russell, Sammy, was trapped in a disused mine.
The family feared the dog would die but firefighters and mine rescue staff
climbed into the mine shaft and dug the dog free with their hands.
The dog had become trapped after chasing a rabbit. Kelly's father, Mr Alan
Archibald, 39, had taken him and the family's two other dogs for an afternoon
walk near their home by Cousland, Midlothian.
Mr Archibald said: ``The dogs are always chasing rabbits, so I just left them
to it, expecting them to follow me home.
``But by early evening I knew something was wrong when Sammy hadn't appeared at
the door.''
Mr Archibald went back into the wood and heard Sammy whimpering underground.
He tried to dig away the loose soil from the mine entrance but it was too dark
to see what he was doing.
The following morning, he took a shovel out to the mine and hoped he could dig
away the collapsed soil. He feared the rest of the mine would collapse on him
so called in the fire brigade.
Six firefighters arrived and, with the help of two mine rescue staff, climbed
into the tunnel and dug their way towards the dog.
Last night, Mr Archibald said: ``Everyone involved in helping rescue Sammy was
absolutely great.
``They had a very cold, very dangerous job, but nothing seemed too much for
them.''
His wife, Joyce, 42, added: ``Kelly had been sobbing her heart out when her dog
didn't come home.
``But the rescuers have really made her Christmas wish come true.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
