<DOCNO>GH951215-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Miners expected to approve Monktonhall buy-out offer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880817</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DECISIVE vote by miners at the troubled Monktonhall colliery in Midlothian to
accept a buy-out to save their pit is expected to be announced today.
The result of voting on an offer by Waverley Mining Finance is to be given in
Edinburgh and is expected to show that a majority of the miners favour it.
Figures for the voting were being withheld last night until an announcement
could be made on the London Stock Exchange this morning.
Acceptance of Waverley's offer means that the 158 miners will have relinquished
their 51% control of the pit and allowed Waverley to extend its shareholding
from 49% to 100%.
The result has to be put to the annual meeting of the miners at Dalkeith
tomorrow and it is expected to be given formal approval.
Waverley has offered ordinary company shares in exchange for the miners' 51%
holding.
The finance company said that if the share offer was approved, #15m would be
invested, allowing reinvestment in machinery and the opening of a new coal face
which would double production, provide 80 more jobs, and extend the pit's life
for at least 16 years.
The miners had been given three weeks to decide on the offer. Acceptance means
they cannot cash in the shares for three years.
Monktonhall was closed by British Coal in 1987 but a miners' consortium
succeeded in reopening it, only for further difficulties to arise due to a lack
of capital.
Waverley rescued Monktonhall two years ago with a package that gave it 49% of
the shares and left the miners with 51%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parkinson's drugs link</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880818</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW drugs combination used to treat Parkinson's Disease has been linked to a
57% increase in patient deaths.
The treatment involved adding a drug called selegiline to the established
Parkinson's treatment, levodopa, in the hope of protecting against suspected
side-effects and prolonging life-span.
Instead, the UK Parkinson's Disease Research Group report in the British
Medical Journal, found 76 out of 271 patients treated with the combination were
dead after five years, compared with 44 out of 249 treated with levodopa alone.
The trial group, from 93 hospitals throughout the UK, were all
recently-diagnosed patients who had not previously been treated. The
combination seemed to offer ``no clinical benefit'' over levodopa alone in
treating early, mild Parkinson's disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man who preyed on youths jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880819</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN who preyed on foreign teenage boys visiting Edinburgh was jailed for 18
months yesterday.
Kevin Drumgoole, 56, met the young backpackers, offered them a place to stay,
plied them with drink, interfered with them, and videoed himself carrying out
sex acts on the teenagers, who were oblivious to what was going on.
Sheriff Richard Scott told him the court had to send a message to other people
tempted to carry out such ``atrocities''.
Defence counsel Robert Henderson QC, revealed that Drumgoole had previously run
a football team and been a swimming coach at the city's Commonwealth Pool.
``He has always been interested in youth,'' said Mr Henderson, ``and has done a
great deal of good for youth.''
Drumgoole's video tapes were found when police raided his flat looking for
child pornography. Eighteen tapes were found and, viewing them, officers came
across scenes of homosexual acts involving teenage youths who seemed to be
unconscious.
At an earlier Edinburgh Sheriff Court appearance, Drumgoole, of Milton Street,
Edinburgh, admitted seven charges involving sexual assaults on youths.
Six involved named teenagers between the ages of 14 and 17, and the seventh
covered a further 20 incidents involving unknown youths captured on video.
The charges covered more than three years, between June 1991 and August 1994.
Depute-fiscal Neil Allan described Drumgoole as ``predatory'', preying on the
young and inexperienced.
He said that in five of the charges, when the victims were traced to Germany
and Holland and interviewed, they were unaware of what had happened to them.
Sheriff Scott told Drumgoole the court had to send out a message: ``To make it
clear to any other miserable person like yourself, who is tempted to commit
atrocities of this kind, that they must not do it.''
He also imposed a nine-month supervised release order at the end of the prison
term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Probation for driver blamed for death crash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880820</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TEACHER whose dangerous driving left one man dead and four seriously injured,
was released by a sheriff yesterday, who told him he had too much to offer
society.
Mr Donald Henderson, 41, a physical education teacher at Renfrew High School,
was placed on probation for two years, ordered to carry out 240 hours community
service, banned from driving for five years, and ordered to re-sit his test.
Mr John Hannah, 56, of Sycamore Avenue, Beith, Ayrshire, died after the car in
which he was a passenger collided head-on with a car driven by Mr Henderson.
Mr Hannah had been returning home from work. His son was driving.
His widow, Nancy, 54, was stunned by the sentence yesterday and, calling for
tougher sentences, said: ``I don't want to think about that man but I did
expect him to go to jail.
``No matter how tough the sentence had been on that man, it wouldn't have
brought my husband back but if tougher sentences make careless drivers think
twice, then it's time they were introduced.''
A jury was told that the vehicle in which Mr Hannah was travelling was hidden
momentarily from view in a dip in the road at an accident blackspot and Mr
Henderson pulled out across double white lines to make an overtaking maneouvre.
Mr Henderson was found guilty of causing death by dangerous driving, after
trial at Paisley Sheriff Court.
When he appeared for sentence, Sheriff David Pender said there would be nothing
to gain from sending him to prison.
He told Henderson: ``It is clear you are much more than a nine-to-five school
teacher and that you have much to offer. You have already destroyed one life
and if I was to send you to prison it would also destroy your life and the
lives of your wife and children.''
He and three others from the Renfrew Basketball Club were returning from a
match in Kilwinning on February 20 this year, when the crash happened on the
A737 west of the Roadhead roundabout near Netherbarford Farm, Lochwinnoch.
Mr Hannah, a dairy worker, died from his injuries on March 14.
Mr Henderson remained in a coma for two days in Glasgow's Southern General
Hospital, and spent a further two months in hospital recovering from head
injuries.
The court was told he had been left with physical and mental scars, although he
has been able partially to return to work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dirty tricks claim as councillor quits race</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880821</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN SNP councillor said yesterday that he had pulled out of the contest to be
prospective parliamentary candidate for Tweeddale, Ettrick, and Lauderdale,
because he faced a straight choice between political ambition and personal
integrity.
Mr Willie McKay, education chairman on the new Scottish Borders Council, is
accusing local activists of a dirty tricks campaign against him.
He claimed last night: ``There are divisions in the local party. I don't mind
politics getting dirty but it was becoming very personal. I was even asked if I
was a Catholic or a Protestant. I raised the problem informally with people on
the national executive and, after a lot of thought, have decided to take no
further part in the contest.
Councillor McKay, a lecturer and former EIS convener at Borders College, has
already been through one selection process in competition with NEC member
Christine Creech, an Edinburgh solicitor who doubled the SNP vote when she
stood against Sir David Steel at the last General Election.
Mrs Creech came marginally ahead in the selection process for the party's next
candidate in the Borders seat but last weekend the NEC ruled that the contest
would have to be re-run because she did not have a clear majority.
Councillor McKay said: ``I thought long and hard and I just can't face the
infighting that going through the whole process again would involve. I will
stay a member of the SNP and represent it in local government. I will probably
have to face some sort of disciplinary action but I will accept whatever
happens.''
The SNP's Tweeddale, Ettrick, and Lauderdale convener Marshall Douglas said:
``I am extremely surprised at this development. The contest has been hard
fought up to now but there did not seem to have been any bitterness and I am
certainly unaware of any dirty tricks.''
Mrs Creech, who also fought the South of Scotland for the SNP in this year's
Euro Elections, said: ``The decision to stand down is a personal matter for
Willie McKay but, knowing the quality of the membership in the Borders, I would
be amazed if there had been anything underhand.''
At the last General Election, Mrs Creech won 5244 votes, compared with 2660 in
the previous election. Her share of the vote was up from 9% to 17%.
Her selection as prospective parliamentary candidate now seems assured, unless
a surprise contestant appears before nominations close on January 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vote-rigging claims as Asian candidate loses selection contest for new seat Labour hit by race row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent, CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880822</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR was last night plunged into damaging accusations of racism, after a
selection battle in Glasgow ended with allegations of vote-rigging.
Glasgow Central MP Mike Watson emerged victorious in the contest to become his
party's prospective candidate in the new seat of Govan, but the manner of his
victory and the size of his winning margin led to immediate demands for an
appeal by supporters of one of his opponents, Councillor Mohammed Sarwar.
The Asian businessman, who had been widely tipped to become one of Britain's
first Muslim MPs, was clearly upset by the outcome, which came after 52 votes
were discounted by the party official overseeing the ballot.
``I am definitely not accepting this result,'' said Councillor Sarwar, who
represents Pollokshields on the existing Glasgow District Council and has been
elected to Pollokshields East on the new unitary authority.
``I am appealing to the national executive committee of the Labour Party. It is
extremely unfair when 52 members of the local party are declared not eligible
to vote.''
He called it an ``extremely sad situation'' that proper members of the party
were ruled out from voting, adding: ``What I am saying is that I think I was
unfairly treated.''
Mr Watson's victory involved a dead-heat with Councillor Sarwar. He won only
after a count-back procedure in which he led by just one vote, 237 to 236, in
the first ballot, which included women's caucus candidate Margaret Curran.
When the second preference votes of her supporters were redistributed the
result was a 245-vote dead heat, and under the party's voting rules the
one-vote victory in the initial ballot became conclusive.
Mr Watson was clearly discomfited by the manner of the result and the racism
allegations made by some of Mr Sarwar's supporters, but he said at the end of
the tortuous procedure: ``I wish it had been more decisive, but I am delighted
to have won. Now all I want to do is pull the constituency together.''
However, one of Mr Sarwar's supporters, constituency Labour Party vice-chairman
Mohammed Shoaib, said: ``Victory has been denied to us and we will consider
what course of action to take. Some people who have been party members for 10
years have now been thwarted.
``If victory has been denied to us by being Asian and we have been victimised,
the Labour Party should take action. I think Mohammed Sarwar did not have a
fair hearing throughout.''
He was supported by local Councillor Deirdre Gaughan, who said: ``I am in
neither camp, but when 52 people are told they were eligible to vote and are
then told their vote does not count, I am not happy.''
There appeared disquiet in the Asian community. Mr Tufail Shaheen, president of
the Islam Consul of Scotland and president of the Glasgow Central Mosque, said
that what had happened to the 52 members whose votes had been declared invalid
was ``very very wrong''.
Mr Shaheen said the Muslim community was now the second biggest in the UK with
two million members yet it did not have a single MP.
The outcome of the Govan vote had left the whole of their community ``very very
sad'' because they had thought they would have been assured of one MP when the
result was announced.
``I don't want to get involved in politics but what they have done to the 52
members is very very wrong. I don't know why they were rejected.''
He added: ``What has happened is that they don't like to see any MPs from our
community. Asians are not given any opportunities yet they are creating jobs.
``Mike Watson is my friend and a nice fellow but what has happened is bad.''
Mr Hanif Rajah, vice chair of the Pollokshaws, Strathbungo, and Langside branch
of the Labour Party, said the election had been unfair because people who are
members of the party could not cast their vote.
Mr Rajah said that he had attended branch meetings with every member who was
made ineligible to vote. ``Fifty-two members have been denied their rights and
there must be something wrong in that. Asian people have problems signing their
names but that doesn't mean to say they are fraudulent.
``I would not say it was racist. There is racism all over the country but not
in this case. It was an injustice for people with an Asian background.''
Mr Dilip Deb, a leading Asian lawyer, said that there had been nothing racist
in the vote. ``Mr Watson has been democratically elected as prospective Labour
candidate for Govan and we are sure that he will be as good an MP as Mr
Sarwar.''
The Labour Party hierarchy moved swiftly last night to endorse Mr Watson's
victory. ``The selection has been a long and time-consuming process which shows
that the Scottish Labour Party takes seriously the electorate of Govan,'' said
general secretary Jack McConnell.
``This result finalises the democratic choice of the members of the Govan
Labour Party. Everyone in the party should now accept the result and rally
behind Mike Watson to ensure a Labour victory in Govan at the next General
Election and the ending of 16 years of Tory rule.''
However, its main rivals in the seat, the SNP, also moved quickly to exploit
the situation. ``Labour's shambolic performance shows that they are unfit to
represent the people of Govan and Scotland,'' said local candidate Nicola
Sturgeon.
``The internal bitterness that the selection has generated shows that New
Labour is simply a meaningless slogan, with nothing to offer Govan or
Scotland.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Raid man guilty of drug dealing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880823</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Raid man guilty
of drug dealing
TRANSPORT depot worker Ian Gass, 26, of Victoria Park, Lockerbie, one of 78
people detained in a police raid on the Kat House nightspot in the town in
August, was found guilty yesterday of supplying amphetamine.
The jury at Dumfries acquitted him of supplying and having ecstacy. Sheriff
Kenneth Barr continued the case until January 9 for reports.
Motorist killed
A MAN was killed yesterday morning when his car was involved in a head-on crash
with a lorry on the A96 between Elgin and Lhanbryde, in Moray. Police were
withholding his identity until relatives had been told.
Book contenders
SHORT leets for the James Tait Black Memorial Prizes, Scotland's oldest book
awards, are announced today. The leets are: Fiction. Anita Brookner, Incidents
in the Rue Laugier; Kazuo Ishiguro, The Unconsoled; Ross Leckie, Hannibal;
Christopher Priest, The Prestige. Biography. Peter Ackroyd, Blake; Margaret
Drabble, Angus Wilson: A Biography; Gitta Sereny, Albert Speer: His Battle With
Truth; John Sutherland, The Life of Sir Walter Scott. The winners of the two
prizes, each worth #3000, will be announced next month.
Farmer freed
FARMER Trevor Sedgbeer, who was jailed for three months last Friday for burying
his illegally-built house under a mound of earth in a bid to fool council
inspectors, was freed by the High Court in London yesterday after apologising
for his contempt. The house has now been demolished.
Bakers' payout
TWO bakers who were sacked without warning in August from the Osborne bakery in
Macduff, Banffshire, have been given a substantial redundancy and pay award. An
industrial tribunal in Aberdeen yesterday ordered that Mr Peter Mitchell, 34,
be paid #4784 and Robert King, 59, #7544 in redundancy and lieu-of-notice
payments.
Schools inspector
THE Scottish Office yesterday announced the appointment of Mr Douglas Osler as
HM Senior Chief Inspector of Schools.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Refugees from peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>bosnian peace deal</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880824</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SARAJEVO.
THE end of the war brought no joy to the Serb-held Sarajevo suburb of Ilidza,
where many residents plan to flee before the district
reverts
to government rule.
As the peace accord was being signed, Ilidzans trudged wearily about their
business along snow-clogged streets under a banner which read: ``America -
thank you for peace but where should we go now?.
Nowhere has the end of the separatist Serb dream been more cruel and ironic
than in Sarajevo's northern and western suburbs, where Serbs maintained an
iron
grip throughout 43 months of war.
While a Serb republic within Bosnia will occupy 49% of the country, a
last-minute deal in peace negotiations transferred control of the Sarajevo
suburbs to a Muslim-Croat federation which will administer the other 51%.
``We fought and defended our homes with the blood of our husbands and sons and
the Muslims never defeated us,'' said 78-year-old Dragitsa Stanic.
``For us the peace is more terrible than the war. We will lose everything. We
cannot live with the Muslims. We will be refugees from the peace, not from the
war.''
As a suburb from which the long Serb siege of Sarajevo was mounted, Ilidza
boasted a far higher standard of living than the capital, for which it served
as a black market portal.
Now Ilidza is on the receiving end of the black market trade as Serb-held
Bosnia sags under international sanctions imposed to punish its war-mongering.
For Sanja, a refugee from the government-held town of Zenica, there is no
possibility of waiting for goverment authorities to take over Ilidza.
She fled to the Sarajevo suburb with her elderly parents and four sisters
early
in the war. Her twin was killed by a shell in December of 1992 and she
grieves
at the thought of having to leave the girl's grave behind when she goes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman cleared of scalding charges</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880825</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FOSTER carer was cleared yesterday of having left a child in a scalding bath
while answering a telephone call.
Haddington Sheriff Court heard that the two-year-old girl suffered 23% burns to
her body.
The 34-year-old mother of two, from East Lothian, who had been a foster carer
for two years before the incident, was found not guilty after Sheriff George
Presslie found no case to answer.
The woman said later: ``Thank God it is all over. These past few months have
been the worst in my life.'' She added: ``I can't put my family through this
again. I have given up fostering.''
The woman had denied causing the girl unnecessary suffering by leaving her
neglected and unattended in a bath of hot running water on August 12 and
failing to seek medical attention until August 14.
The girl, who cannot be named for legal reasons, was taken to the Royal
Hospital for Sick Children, in Edinburgh, where surgeons assessed the extent of
the scalding.
It was claimed that parts of her legs, which had to be skin grafted, may be
scarred for life.
On the conclusion of the Crown evidence, defence solicitor Simon Collins
submitted that there was no case to answer.
Sheriff Presslie, giving his ruling, said there was no evidence to show that
the woman had set out deliberately to leave the child in a bath of hot, running
water. She had checked the water temperature, waited for a while, and seen no
steam.
Insufficient evidence had been led to show there was a potential danger of the
bath water temperature rising, how it rose, that it was likely to occur, or
that it should have been guarded against.
However, there was some evidence to show that medical care was provided for the
immediate needs of the child after she was scalded.
The carer had put the child in cold water, administered medicine with analgesic
properties and had provided plenty of liquids, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Father fined for shoot-out after party for daughter Armed police surround house after shotgun blasts at the `party from hell'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880826</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BLAZING row, a blazing gun - it was just like ``the Wild West'', a leading QC
told Stirling Sheriff Court yesterday.
As armed officers surrounded a house in the dead of night, a couple from Kansas
were led to safety from a neighbouring bed and breakfast house, and had to
spend the first night of their honeymoon in a police station.
However, the showdown happened a continent away from the Wild West, in the
King's Park area of Stirling, after one of the town's businessmen turned his
daughter's 21st birthday celebration into ``the party from hell''.
Yesterday, it ended in court, with the businessman being saddled with a #5000
fine.
The court was told that Debbie MacAulay's coming-of-age ended with armed police
surrounding the family home after her father, Brian MacAulay, 59, a private
landlord, tried to shoot his way out of a bedroom where he had been locked in
by other members of his family.
MacAulay, who was represented by Mr Donald Findlay QC, admitted repeatedly and
recklessly discharging the shotgun on September 14, through his bedroom door in
the direction of his wife Marilyn, his daughter Debbie, son Colin, and his
daughter's boyfriend, Mr Fraser McGhee. He also admitted being disorderly.
The court was told that, after going out for meal to celebrate his daughter's
birthday, the family returned to their home at Park Terrace about 11.30pm.
A row erupted over a video that was being watched and a scuffle developed, with
Mr MacAulay being ``extremely abusive'' and Mrs MacAulay slapping her husband
on his face, said depute fiscal Valerie Barber-Fleming.
The trouble escalated after Colin MacAulay pushed his father into his bedroom
and Mrs MacAulay locked the door.
MacAulay, who had banged his head and was bleeding and panicking, shouted that
he would shoot his way out.
The court was told he was very keen on guns, possessing both shotgun and
firearms certificates and owning three rifles, three shotguns, and a number of
other items.
He grabbed a shotgun that had been lying in the bedroom ready for a shooting
expedition the next day and fired it five times at the lock.
Mrs MacAulay and their son managed to escape from the house and telephone the
police, despite the fact their escape route lay past the door through which
MacAulay was shooting.
When armed officers arrived, they found MacAulay still in the bedroom and his
daughter and his son's girlfriend hysterical in the sitting room.
He was arrested without fuss after Mrs MacAulay told officers he would pose
them no threat.
Mrs Barber-Fleming said pellets from the shotgun were found in a skirting board
32ft from the peppered bedroom door.
Mr Findlay said all members of the family had been drinking and what should
have been a celebration had turned into a ``party from hell''.
He said the row over the video had developed into an unseemly squabble on all
sides and, after he was locked in his room, MacAulay panicked.
``He announced that if the family didn't unlock the door, he'd shoot the lock
off the door and that's what he did.
``The result, being like the Wild West, was quite unacceptable and potentially
dangerous. Mercifully, no-one was hurt by it,'' said Mr Findlay.
He said his client accepted it had been an irresponsible and thoroughly
unsavoury episode. Since the incident, MacAulay had been living apart from his
family. His wife now wanted him back.
He said his client's chances of being allowed to continue to hold gun licences
were remote.
The court was told the family had been out together for the first time after
the shooting on the night before the court case. It was MacAulay's birthday.
The celebration passed off without incident.
Sheriff Frederick Levine said he was satisfied with Mr Findlay's professional
assaurance that Mrs MacAulay wanted her husband back and that there was no
danger to the family.
MacAulay, said to be a man of ``substantial means'' capable of paying any
appropriate fine, was fined #5000 and ordered to pay within two weeks.
Last night, it emerged that the video that caused all the trouble was a
home-made holiday video of Colin MacAulay's girlfriend's father parascending.
At the time of the incident, police, including four specially trained firearms
officers, spent nearly four hours surrounding the MacAulay home.
They entered the house at about 4.30am and MacAulay left with them a short
while later.
Houses on both sides were evacuated. Mrs Alyson Pillinger, 35, who runs a bed
and breakfast next door to the MacAulays, said at the time that four Americans
had been staying with her, including a couple who had got married in Stirling
the previous day.
The honeymoon couple, Kathy and Steve Farkas, from Kansas, were awoken by the
police at 1.30am and had to spend the first night of their honeymoon in the
police station.
Mr MacAulay owns a number of flats and bedsits in Stirling, which he rents.
Through his solicitor, MacAulay said after the case he was glad the matter was
over and wanted to put it all behind him.
</TEXT>
