<HEADLINE>Shrugs and suspicions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>bosnian peace deal</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880828</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CROATIA
THEY also know war, but the smartly-dressed Christmas shoppers of the Croatian
capital of Zagreb had only shrugs and suspicion for peace deal.
``So there will be peace. I just wonder if it will hold,'' said Velko
Puntaric,
a 43-year-old employee at the National Theatre.
``Only God knows what will happen. We have to be optimists, but I do not trust
the Serbs at all,'' said Ivana Nadj, a 45-year-old housewife.
In Croatia, no one is doing anything special to celebrate in  Zagreb because
no
one knows whether the end of war in Bosnia really marks the start of peace.
There is more talk in the bustling snowy streets about the glittering
Christmas
lights, put up in trees and on lamp posts by the city council, than about the
peace deal.
Outside the sandbagged United Nations' headquarters, an impromptu monument
known as the Wall of Shame was still standing in silent reproach to
international mediators who did not stop Serbs seizing chunks of Croatia in a
1991 war.
Each brick in the wall is marked with the name of a person who went missing in
the fighting. Fresh candles and tiny bunches of flowers are still scattered
along its length.
Croatians' hesitations are rooted partly in fears their own part in the
settlement - sorting out the return of Serb-held Eastern Slavonia to their
control and sending back thousands of Croatian refugees who fled the Serbs -
has been neglected.
A separate November agreement provided for Eastern Slavonia to be reintegrated
in Croatia after a one to two-year transition under international
administration during which 90,000 Croat refugees are to regain their homes.
But implementation of the accord is stalled by US-UN. disputes over who should
provide enforcement troops.
Other Croatian lands seized by Serbs in 1991 were recaptured last summer.
</TEXT>
