<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shops, cars, and bars join a policeman on the casualty list as trouble rears again on the streets of London In the eye of the storm Business as usual amid the debris</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Wiliam Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>brixton riots</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880829</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
An eerie calm descended over Brixton yesterday after a night of rioting took
its toll in human casualties and commercial property. William Russell walks the
not so mean streets and surveys the damage
IT was the run up to Christmas as usual yesterday afternoon in Brixton. The
strands of fairy lights suspended between the street lamps twinkled in the
afternoon gloom, and although some had gone out, victims of the previous
night's violence, the shooting stars and snowflakes attached to the lamp
standards sparkled away.
The chain stores, the inevitable High Street names, Woolworths, Boots, Marks &amp;
Spencer among them, were doing a roaring trade, as were the fast food cafes. If
there were a few boarded up windows on view, they were no more than is par for
the course in any down-at-heel shopping street in a working class area of
Britain today.
The market traders, whose stalls line the Victorian arcaded streets that curve
behind Brixton railway station, a relic of Victorian London, were peddling
their wares with vigour as if nothing out of the ordinary had happened only a
few hours before.
There were piles of cabbages and cauliflowers, oranges, and potatoes, bananas
and breadfruit, pot plants trimmed with tinsel piled in the backs of vans, and
Christmas trees lying in heaps on the pavement.
The scent of smoke in the air came not from smouldering wrecks of the burnt out
cars dragged out of the showroom and set alight in Effra Road (a familiar name
from past riots) long since removed, but from the sticks of incense a man was
peddling on the stairs leading from the tube station. Shut at the height of the
riot, it was back in business, differing only from other London underground
stations possibly in the number of security cameras in its entrance hall.
Brixton is a dodgy area at the best of times, and Wednesday night had been, if
not the worst of times, one of the bad times.
The McDonalds across the way was thronged - no worries about mad cow disease
there - and at the video store down the road which, in spite of its steel
shutters, had been looted they were repairing the broken glass and, in spite of
a depleted stock, a notice insisted it was open for business.
Some people had been lucky, others, like the recently opened Dog Star Club in
Atlantic Road had not. It was badly damaged, its expensive windows shattered,
its interior set alight, its future now in doubt.
But in spite of the apparent normality was clear something out of the ordinary
had occurred. The clue was not the number of police loitering with intent in
twos and threes at the street corners, at the zebra crossings, directing the
traffic and generally looking thoroughly fed up with their lot, but the
presence of those predators who turn up whenever disaster is in the air, who
were lying in ambush for their prey - the television companies' outside
broadcast vans with their menacing, all-seeing cameras waiting to bring the
flames and the petrol bombs and the baton charges into the living rooms of the
nation.
They were parked in a cosy little enclave, there being safety in numbers, on
the pavement opposite the red brick thirties town hall whose Christmas
greetings sign twinkled sadly.
The glass from the broken shop windows had long since been swept away, but the
boards which had been put up were not being allowed to prevent life going on.
The Midland Bank, one of several banks whose windows had been shattered, was
making the best of a bad job. Its cash dispenser was still operating through a
specially cut hole - you cannot fire bomb Mammon. Woolworth's, which like most
of the chain stores has massive steel shutters - smashed windows have happened
before in Brixton - would close at 3 pm, a notice said, while Boots, which also
boasted hefty metal grilles over its windows, admitted its customers in
carefully selected ones and twos. But that was as far as it went.
Nearby the red neon sign of the Ritzy cinema, a bourgeois enclave in this
wilderness of chain stores, seedy newsagents, and cut-price shops, shone
bravely in the gathering dusk. As usual the titles of the films on offer seemed
apallingly apt.
In the Bleak Midwinter, which it most certainly was, the wind blowing down
Brixton Road feeling as if it had come straight from the Steppes.
La Haine, or The Hate, which is a savage indictment of the violent treatment by
the Paris plain clothes police of three young French working class teenagers of
alien origin. Its account of thuggish behaviour by coppers in jeans and tank
tops seemed somehow relevant in the circumstances. Maybe everyone concerned
with Brixton's future peace should take a trip to the pictures.
And there was Apocalypse Now, except that it was clearly not the case that it
is apocalypse now in Brixton. Had it been life would not have been going on as
usual. Further down the hill towards Stockwell around Brixton police station it
got much more menacing. The streets were lined with some forty odd parked white
police vans, the riot shields over their windscreens raised, some empty, others
filled with policemen waiting their turn to go on patrol.
It was freezing. Nobody passing by wanted to talk about what had happened. They
just wanted to get on with their shopping, to return home safely and escape all
those threatening policemen and the provocative TV cameras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>System under fire as teacher is cleared</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880830</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING educational lawyer criticised prosecuting authorities last night for
dragging a dedicated teacher to court on the uncorroborated evidence of three
disruptive pupils.
Stirling Sheriff Court heard that the boys, aged eight and nine, were notorious
troublemakers at a declining primary school in Stirling.
Mr Thomas McGhee, 40, who has taught at the school for 19 years, was cleared of
assaulting the boys after a day-long trial. He had denied the charges
strenuously.
The court heard that Mr McGhee, a family man, regular churchgoer, and father of
three, had been allocated the tough primary five/six class at the beginning of
the autumn term because it needed a firm hand and had tried the patience of
many teachers.
On the second day of term, he had to tell his pupils: ``This is a classroom,
not a jungle.''
Almost immediately, he found himself at the centre of an inquiry by the family
unit of Central Scotland Police, which led to yesterday's court case.
The court heard that the children who made the allegations of assault were
among the worst behaved in the school.
An eight-year-old boy who claimed that on August 23 he had been lifted by the
chin and dragged from the classroom was so badly behaved that he once dropped
his trousers in front of one of Her Majesty's Inspector of Schools.
He had three times the previous year been excluded from school for disruptive
and attention-seeking behaviour.
Two nine-year-olds who claimed that, on August 24, Mr McGhee had banged their
heads together and thrown one of them against a wall, were disruptive and had
been fighting in class.
Colleagues gave evidence to describe Mr McGhee as a patient teacher.
Sheriff Frederick Levine said that, after hearing the evidence, he could find
no corroboration of the boys' stories.
Mr McGhee, of Buchan Drive, Dunblane, Perthshire, still faces an internal
disciplinary hearing by the education authority. He had not been suspended.
Outside the court, he said he had been deluged with messages of support.
He said: ``I'm very relieved it's all over and in a way very depressed that it
ever got to court in the first place.''
He added: ``I'm not the first and I won't be the last teacher to be involved in
this sort of thing.''
Mr Andrew Gibb, a solicitor for the EIS, Scotland's biggest teaching union, who
represented Mr McGhee in court, said he had become increasingly concerned over
the vulnerability of teachers facing false accusations.
He said teachers should in future never see a child on their own.
He said the Crown had taken no steps to test the credibility and reliability of
the evidence against Mr McGhee.
Mr Gibb said he believed procurators fiscal were being put under political
pressure to prosecute teachers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
