<DOCNO>GH951215-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A signing has signalled the ascent from the hell of war but doubts surround a lasting truce Fingers still on the triggers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>bosnian peace deal</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Map</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880831</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANALYSIS
WINSTON Churchill once described the military and diplomatic process of
peacekeeping as ``a measure designed not to get us to heaven, but simply to
keep us from descending into hell''.
It is a statement which aptly characterises the Nato-imposed ceasefire in
Yugoslavia.
The stroke of a pen may have ended the immediate conflict in Bosnia, roping
off
the warring factions behind new and artificial boundaries policed by Nato's
big guns. Whether the paper peace survives beyond the 12-month mandate of the
enforcers is an entirely different question.
The very terms of the settlement could be the seeds of a new outbreak of
bloodshed when Nato ups tent-pegs and pulls out early in 1997. In the
horse-trading for territory which followed the Muslim-Croat summer offensives,
civilians on all sides inevitably lost out.
Several hundred thousand people will now have to give up their homes as the
map
is redrawn along ethnic lines. The few who choose to remain in areas
reassigned to their former foes will have to live with the constant threat of
being caught, lonely, outnumbered and vulnerable, on the wrong side of the
divide. In a land where blood-feud has always been a way of life, that might
not be conducive to a long and comfortable existence.
Sarajevo, the focal point and poignant international symbol of the three-year
war, is the likeliest repeat flashpoint. The deal specifies that the battered
city now belongs to the Muslims.
It is not a decision calculated to endear Nato to the 70,000 Serb inhabitants
who now face the stark choice of becoming a besieged minority or refugees.
Serbia and Bosnia have agreed to recognise each other ``as sovereign,
independent states with the current international borders'', paving the way
for
the possibility of formal diplomatic relations, albeit across the gulf of a
still-tense no-man's-land. Croatia, the big winner in the three-sided
bloodbath, has stopped short of giving the Serbs that level of credence.
The 60,000-strong mainly Nato force, armed with tanks and heavy weaponry and
configured for combat rather than a police operation, will be in place within
the next two months.
That in itself is a major logistical and political achievement. While America,
Britain, and France will supply the bulk of the manpower, non-alliance
countries will also send smaller contingents to broaden the political base and
authority of the process. Russian and Czech troops will be serving under US
command for the first time.
With the armoured muscle of more than 100 US Abrams and 50 British Challenger
tanks and almost 500 Bradley and Warrior infantry fighting vehicles at its
core, the multinational Implementation Force represents a powerful deterrent.
The rules of engagement under which its men are to operate gives them more
than
adequate rights of self-defence and even offensive action if necessary.
The firepower under the IFOR banner would, in any kind of open confrontation,
leave the issue in no doubt.
However, they remain vulnerable to guerrilla tactics, particularly through the
winter now beginning. All the hi-tech Apache helicopter gunships in the world
cannot help if they are grounded by cloud or snow.
The Americans, recognising the one area where they could be made to pay an
unacceptable price in lives through hit-and-run attacks, are deploying two
National Intelligence Support Teams to keep tabs on potential rogue elements
of
the Serb, Croat and Muslim forces. Two other surveillance teams are already
in
place.
These units use satellites, unmanned drones, electronic eavesdropping and
other
clandestine techniques to collect detailed data on would-be terrorist groups
and their movements. Big Brother is already watching the most predictably
discontented individuals and units throughout the area and building up a
coherent intelligence picture for use if and when terrorist activity begins.
A major headache for the patrolling IFOR soldiers is the constant danger of
mines.
What will clearly happen, peace treaty or not, is that all of the former
protagonists will use the year-long breathing space to regroup, arm and train
effective forces of their own. The Americans have already announced that they
will offer formal military training to the Muslims to enable them to defend
themselves adequately against any future Serb or Croat aggression.
US aid of this kind was given to the Croats earlier this year to help them
build a strike force for the lighting ground offensive which recaptured much
of
the territory lost to the Serbs since 1992. It was part of the US strategy of
bringing the previously-victorious Serbs to the brink of military defeat and
to
encourage them to negotiate rather than fight.
With the lifting of the UN arms' embargo on the area, all sides will be able
to
beef up their arsenals with armour and, more dangerously, aircraft. Savage as
the three years of civil war have been, the death toll would have been
immensely higher and the results of combat more decisive if one or more of the
participants had possessed effective air power.
In the age of instability, the world is filled with nations only too happy to
provide bangs for the buck. Ironically, the coming of temporary peace may well
act as a trigger for a new arms race within the former Yugoslavia as the
precursor to a resumption of all-out war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
