<DOCNO>GH951215-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Troubled times</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>brixton riots</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880832</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
6.30pm According to police, the countdown to the riot began when peaceful
demonstrators against the death in custody of Wayne Douglas gathered outside
Brixton Police Station.
7pm There were 40 protesters and within an hour the number had risen to 125.
This group then moved off down Brixton Road and regathered peacefully outside
the Ritzy Cinema at the junction with Coldharbour Lane.
9pm The protest seemed to be losing steam and about a third of the protesters
had left. A group broke from the remaining demonstrators and marched back along
Brixton Road. It is unclear exactly what sparked the riot but the first reports
of violence occurred at this point, with missiles, including bottles, being
thrown at police. The larger group still outside the cinema then began to break
up and sporadic trouble flared across Brixton with shop windows being broken.
The police, fearing serious violence, donned protective riot gear and took out
shields and long batons. Mounted officers were also called in.
10pm Police were attacked, including an officer who was dragged off his
motorbike, cars were set on fire and dozens of shops were looted. Two gunshots
were reported at one point.
7am Morning breaks to reveal the full extent of the mayhem. A senior officer in
charge of the Brixton area defends police tactics. Paul Manning, the
Metropolitan Police assistant commissioner responsible for policing across
south-west London, rejects accusations from some protesters that officers were
heavy-handed. He blamed a ``small minority'' of people for the violence. He
denies the police over-reacted. ``Not at all. People were jumping in front of
moving vehicles, some people were clearly intent on not dispersing peacefully,
bottles and bricks were starting to be thrown -my officers were left with no
alternative than to take on protective gear and equipment and look to the
safety of passers-by and people using that stretch of road.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The boss and the departure lounge Key staff left and $590m was moved to less volatile investment houses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian McConnell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880834</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ian McConnell reports on the peculiar saga of Dunedin Fund Managers, which lost
senior members of staff and the confidence of significant investors
IT SEEMS surprising that something so simple as a clash of personalities could
have been allowed to fester until it resulted in the reduction of Dunedin Fund
Managers' senior staff and the loss of $590m of US funds to less volatile
investment houses.
The situation is even more astonishing when you consider Edinburgh-based
Dunedin is a subsidiary of the 300-year-old Bank of Scotland, a highly
conservative organisation not known for putting up with such nonsense.
There was no comment yesterday from the Bank of Scotland head office on why the
problems which have taken such a heavy toll on its fund-management subsidiary
were not nipped in the bud sooner.
This question was referred by The Mound to Eric Sanderson, chief executive of
Dunedin's immediate parent, British Linen Bank Group. He was unavailable for
comment yesterday.
The British Linen Bank chief executive was charged with the task of bringing
Dunedin to heel in October and his arrival on the scene was swiftly followed by
the departure of Dunedin's chairman, Hamish Leslie Melville, and its deputy
chief executive, Alan Kemp.
Even if Dunedin does manage to drag itself out of the mire - and many in the
industry believe a takeover is a more likely end to the saga - its troubles may
have tarnished the reputation of the Scottish financial community.
The problems which came so spectacularly to a head in October appear to have
started almost as soon as Mr Melville, the National Trust for Scotland chairman
who spent 15 years with Hambros Bank, took over as Dunedin chairman
three-and-a-half years ago.
His arrival was followed by the resignations of a few key members of staff and
the area where the senior people sat became known as the ``departure lounge''.
An industry source said of the departure lounge: ``That was a phrase that used
to be used when Melville first came. There were various people who went and
they all sat in the departure lounge.''
The British Linen Bank attributed the string of resignations which preceded
those of Old Etonian Mr Melville and Mr Kemp to ``clashes in management style''
among Dunedin's senior management.
When it was announced on October 30 that Mr Melville had resigned, Dunedin said
he would be leaving in two months' time. The Herald has been told he left
immediately.
Mr Melville's management style has been described as ``incredibly autocratic''.
He was unavailable to give his side of the story yesterday.
The source said: ``It wasn't so much a difference in (management) style as he
had a different style. He didn't know when to stop.''
Dunedin's troubles led to a ``depressed'' atmosphere within the office, which
developed into more open hostility.
The removal of investment director Gordon Anderson, in July, caused resentment
among Mr Anderson's colleagues.
Three months later, Nigel Barry, head of Dunedin's Pacific operation, and Peter
Tait, head of the European arm, handed in their notice. This appears to have
been the final straw for the Bank of Scotland and was swiftly followed by the
removal of Dunedin's top two.
But Dunedin's troubles were not over. Despite a trip by Mr Sanderson to the US
to reassure clients, one smaller and two major clients switched $590m (#383m)
of funds from the Edinburgh outfit.
Before the problems came to a head, Dunedin was making impressive progress on
the other side of the Atlantic, with more than one-third of its #5600m of funds
under management having come from US clients.
More money could go on the back of this month's news that six fund managers,
including Dunedin Income Growth Investment Trust manager Alan Clark and Dunedin
Smaller Companies manager Neil Pirie, were leaving.
Emerging markets specialist Euan Rae was another of the six casualties, which
followed steps by Mr Sanderson to ``distinguish who among the investment staff
were committed and who were not''.
With most of the US funds thought to be on 30 days' notice, it is not clear
whether more will go, with clients likely to wait until after Christmas if they
do decide to take their money elsewhere.
The latest six to depart are rumoured to be joining Castle Rock, a new
fund-management company set up by Dunedin rebels with the backing of
Philadelphia National Bank. Mr Anderson is thought to be a key player in the
establishment of Castle Rock, and Mr Barry and Mr Tait could join him.
Where Dunedin goes from here is anybody's guess. Foreign &amp; Colonial has been
cited as a potential purchaser but said this week it had ``no plans at the
present time to get involved''.
Dunedin is likely to be attractive to other Scottish investment houses such as
Ivory &amp; Sime and Abtrust, and even partnerships such as Martin Currie are being
bandied about as possible buyers. European banks are also considered to be in
the frame for Dunedin, whose Edinburgh Investment Trust is in the top five in
the UK in terms of market capitalisation.
There is a rumour that Edinburgh Fund Managers might bid and another view that
this transaction might be in the opposite direction.
Dunedin is adamant it is neither for sale nor interested in a merger and anyone
with designs on the fund management group would have to deal with the might of
the Bank of Scotland.
But Rolly Crawford, investment trust analyst at BZW in London, said: ``I think
the Bank of Scotland have to get their cheque book out. They either have to
sell it (Dunedin) or buy people or buy another company. They can't just leave
it as it is.''
Morale at Dunedin has apparently improved since Mr Sanderson arrived and the
choice of a new executive chairman will be crucial to the future of the fund
management group.
Most industry analysts believe a takeover, if there were to be one, would not
come before the spring.
</TEXT>
