<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth attacked on daylight Bill stance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880836</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Tory MP who is sponsoring a Bill to harmonise daylight hours in Britain
with those in the rest of the European Union yesterday accused Scottish
Secretry Michael Forsyth, a strong opponent of the measure, of being unaware of
changing opinions on the issue in Scotland and the rest of the UK.
Mr John Butterfill, MP for Bournemouth West, was responding to news that the
Cabinet had decided to remain neutral on his Bill after earlier reports that a
number of Ministers were urging that the Government should support it.
Mr Forsyth has been credited with persuading his Cabinet colleagues not to take
sides and arguing that the change would cause great anger in Scotland,
especially in northern parts where mornings would be made dark for longer.
Mr Butterfill said the decisions signalled that the Government was willing to
let the Commons have its own say on a free vote. He was confident that the Bill
would be given a second reading on January 19.
He added: `` I regret that my colleague Michael Forsyth has not awaited the
outcome of the debate. It would appear he is unaware that public opinion in
Scotland and the rest of the UK has changed dramatically since the matter was
last tested nearly thirty years ago.''
The last survey by NOP found that 62% of Scots favoured a change which would
provide an extra hour of daylight, with only 29% opposed.
Intimations of Cabinet neutrality indicate that the ``payroll vote'' of
Ministers and Parliamentary Private Secretaries will not be wheeled out
unofficially to vote down the second reading.
Mr Butterfill looks likely otherwise to receive a large majority for the Bill
on second reading and it will be for opponents to utilise the limited time
available to Private Member's Bills to prevent it reaching the Statute Book.
The Government, by convention, does not make extra time available for a
backbench MP's Bill which has run out of time, except occasionally if it is
uncontroversial or backed by an overwhelming number of MPs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Journalist takes on Tory post in battle of the sound bites</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880837</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Conservative Party yesterday named a political editor as its champion in
the battle of the ``spin doctors'' that will dominate the run-in to the General
Election.
Charles Lewington quit as assistant editor with responsibility for politics at
the Sunday Express to take on the #70,000-a-year job and one of the toughest
challenges at Westminster.
The urbane Mr Lewington, 36, will be pitched into a head-to-head struggle with
Alastair Campbell, the tough Labour media chief and a former colleague in the
parliamentary press gallery.
Westminster observers believe the politics of the ``sound bite'' - the use of
striking phrases to generate instant media coverage - will play a greater role
than ever before in putting across the message.
Mr Lewington faces the mammoth task of hauling back the overwhelming Labour
lead in the opinion polls in a bid to secure a fifth term of office for the
Tories.
Public school-educated Mr Lewington, political editor of the Sunday Express for
four years, claimed he had no intention of joining the ranks of party ``spin
doctors'' charged with putting political gloss on news developments.
``My approach to this job will be simple. I do not consider myself to be a spin
doctor, spin doctors invent sound bites and then spin a web of deceit around
them,'' he said.
``Sound journalists are best suited to selling sound policies. I am honoured
that the Prime Minister and the party chairman have the faith in me to do just
that.''
The Prime Minister, on the way to the EU summit in Madrid, said he was
delighted to welcome Mr Lewington to Central Office.
THE Tories received some good news with a new opinion poll showing the
Chancellor's strategy for political recovery is working.
A survey by the Guardian/ICM published today shows that when people were asked
which party has the best policies to deal with the economy, Labour has slipped
from 38 to 33 and the Tories have climbed from 20 to 24, the highest rating for
nearly three years and the best since Mr Clarke became Chancellor in 1993.
However, Labour's lead in the monthly voting intention poll remains unchanged
at 17.
Conservative Party chairman Dr Brian Mawhinney said the poll ``demonstrates
that as people turn their attention to economic matters the Government's
policies are increasingly seen to be impressive and that Labour's sums don't
add up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>War party is put on hold  Nicholas Budgen believes the truce over Europe among the Conservatives will last until the General Election, despite a shift towards the sceptics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicholas Budgen</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974880841</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILL peace in the Tory Party hold until the General Election? Since the
leadership election in July there has been an uneasy and armed truce in our
party over Europe. Will war break out again?
I believe we shall be able to stick together until the General Election. Some
arguments militate against my view. There is constant sniping. This week John
Redwood published his pamphlet against a single currency in Europe.
Immediately, there came a counter-attack from Lord Howe and Sir Leon Brittan.
Wherever and whenever the issue of Europe is raised in the House of Commons, we
the Eurosceptics are present in significant numbers and always argue our case.
The Government seems to be vaguely sympathetic to us without giving us any
specific commitment.
The Euro-enthusiasts, such as Ken Clarke and Michael Heseltine, may be very
influential in the Cabinet but their supporters on the present back benches are
few in number and many are unwilling to argue their corner in public.
Every day brings further criticism of the Government's lack of clarity over
Europe. This week David Howell, a Government loyalist if there ever was one,
said that our foreign policy is ``too busy running after the French and Germans
and being terrified they're going to pull some trick and we are going to be
left behind''.
His views are a clear indication of how the loyalist centre of the Tory Party
has shifted towards the Euro-sceptic wing of the party. No doubt, next week
some other long-serving loyalist will give the political ball another kick in
the direction away from Euro-federalism.
For all the signs of potential trouble, I still believe the truth will hold
until the General Election. There can be no war over mere expressions of
opinion. The House of Commons can only disagree formally with the Government on
Europe when there is a vote authorising more money to be paid to Europe or
where there is legislation transferring more power to Europe.
Only in those two circumstances need the Government press its view to a
confrontation with the Euro-sceptics.
Last year we had the vote on the extra money that was required after the
Maastricht Treaty. That vote gave rise to the expulsion of the Tory Party of
the eight so-called whipless. Now we are moving slowly towards an
inter-governmental conference. The inter-governmental conference will not be
concluded until mid-1997.
The timetable has been agreed by all the great powers of Europe. So for the
Tory Euro-sceptic there's no point in taking the argument so far as to damage
the present Government. It is by no means certain this Government will conclude
the negotiations on the IGC - for we must have a General Election before April
1997.
What, we ask, will happen if the Government is then led by Tony Blair? It is
clear an incoming Labour Government will embrace the Social Chapter. The Tory
Party is united and vocal in its opposition to all proposals that come under
this heading. It is not absolutely certain Labour would take this country into
a single currency.
However, we can say Labour is much more likely to favour a single currency than
is the Conservative Party. We, the Euro-sceptics, do not want a Labour
Government and above all we want to ensure the Tory Party is big enough and
united enough in the next Parliament to lead an effective challenge to any
Labour Government.
So what can we anticipate in the Tory Party between now and the General
Election? There will be manoeuvring and the taking-up of tactical positions.
But this is not war. The single currency is the greatest of the issues.
I expect that the present compromise by which we leave the issue open will last
until the General Election. On other issues, concessions of no great importance
will be made to the Euro-sceptic point of view.
Reluctantly, and eventually, a White Paper on the Government's negotiating
position at the IGC will be published. The Government will start to make
sceptical noises about the European Court of Justice. There will be arguments
about the extension of qualified majority voting. Then there will be a
discussion about the powers of the European parliament.
</TEXT>
