<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Under a quiet exterior, the inner world was a cauldron</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880842</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE few people close to Stephen Wilkinson had no concept of the bizarre
workings of his mind. He shut himself away from society and developed sickening
obsessions with death and an inflated view of his creative potential.
This led to the domination of his personality by the ``dark side'' alter ego he
knew as Winston Jinks.
Wilkinson's paranoid schizophrenia dated from his teens, became accelerated at
the time of a suicide attempt at 21, and materialised horrifically when he
stormed into Nikki's classroom.
Evidence at the trial depicted him as a complex character of deep contrasts -
his reserved exterior masking an internal turmoil.
It was thought that his three unsuccessful applications for a job as a mortuary
attendant could have been his way of compensating for his inability to have
relationships with living people.
Although he left school without qualifications, and never subsequently had a
job, Wilkinson could write with a chilling eloquence. He was judged by Mensa to
have a near-genius IQ of 149.
The short novels, stories, poems, and philosophical ramblings which surfaced
after his arrest were heavily laced with death in the most macabre sense.
No-one, apparently, had seen those writings before Nikki was killed. Had they
done so, it might have been possible to avoid the outcome because his writing
contained strong hints of what was to come.
In his six-page Thought/ Confessions, written two months before his rampage at
Hall Garth Comprehensive School, Wilkinson wrote: ``. . . I shall steal the
lives of society's weakest members; those most vulnerable and those most
treasured.''
He further warned: ``I know that if I enter that (the word `that' was
underlined) building I will have crossed the Rubicon and it frightens me. I
cannot stop myself. It will be done.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
