<HEADLINE>Campaign promotes rail in Highlands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS, Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880843</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE inaugural meeting of the Highland Rail Development Partnership took place
yesterday as the first step in a campaign to promote the Highland rail network
after years of having to defend it.
The partnership was born out of a rail conference organised by the Friends of
the Far North Line in Inverness in October. That meeting resolved that the
campaign to save the Fort William sleeper should be the last one fought in
defence of Highland rail services.
Yesterday's meeting, at the Inverness headquarters of Highlands and Islands
Enterprise, brought together representatives of ScotRail, Railtrack, the
Scottish Tourist Board, Highland Regional Council, the new Highland Council,
freight operator Transrail, HIE, local enterprise company Lochaber Ltd, and
rail campaign groups.
HIE chief executive Iain Robertson said yesterday: ``We got off to an excellent
start and the task for the partnership now will be to identify ideas and match
resources to specific schemes which can tap into resources of funding such as
local authorities, the HIE network, and the European Objective One Programme.''
The establishment of a Rail Development Officer post and the need to identify
projects had been among the principle discussion points. HIE would consider
joint-funding the proposed two-year post and would assist in drawing up a bid
for Objective One matching funds as part of a broader umbrella of potential
rail development schemes, Mr Robertson said.
The development officer would cover all lines within the Highlands as well as
feeder routes into the area from Perth, Aberdeen, and Glasgow.
