<DOCNO>GH951215-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council refuses to rule out further legal action over Lanark Blue</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880846</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE local authority which last week lost a year-long battle to destroy #27,000
worth of Lanark Blue cheese is still considering the possibility of further
legal action, it was confirmed yesterday.
The Herald has also learned that the director of environmental health who led
Clydesdale District Council's case against cheesemaker Humphrey Errington, of
Dunsyre, had no formal environmental health qualifications.
The SNP's business spokesman, Mr Fergus Ewing, has described the disclosures as
bizarre and warned that the party will ask Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
to intervene if the council does not accept full responsibility for the matter.
Sheriff John Douglas Allan last week turned down a bid by the council to
destroy 44 batches of the cheese and criticised its methods.
Yesterday, Mr Duncan McDougall, the council's head of environmental services,
refused to rule out the possibility of further legal action.
He said: ``Our legal team are still discussing the matter. Councillors will be
appraised of the situation at an environmental health committee meeting next
Wednesday.''
Mr McDougall also confirmed that Mr Bob Russell, who led the council's case
against Mr Errington as director of housing and environmental health, did not
possess any formal environmental health qualifications.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Suspicion of abuse not enough, say Lords</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE House of Lords ruled yesterday that suspicion of abuse is not enough to
remove children from their parents.
Campaigners hailed the decision as a major breakthrough and said it would end
traumas such as the ``Satanic abuse'' case in Orkney where children were taken
from their families only to be returned after allegations proved unfounded.
However, social workers warned that the judgment could lead to more dangers for
youngsters, who would lose the protection of the law while allegations were
investigated.
The Lords said orders to take children into care must be based on some evidence
that the child would be vulnerable to abuse.
They were ruling on a case involving a family from Nottinghamshire, where a
teenage girl alleged her stepfather had abused her before she left home.
The local social services department asked the county court for a care order
for three younger children still at home.
However, the court, and later the Court of Appeal, turned down the application
on the grounds that the teenager's allegations were unsubstantiated.
The council took the case the House of Lords.
The Law Lords' ruling will have repercussions on how the Children's Act is
interpreted.
Ms Beth Henderson, a solicitor representing one of the parties in the case,
said the ruling made it clear that social workers could not remove children
thought to be at risk without hard facts.
She said: ``This ruling is a very important decision as it strikes a balance
between a family's rights to privacy and the need to protect children.''
Barrister Allan Levy QC, an expert on children's law who represented one of the
minors involved in the case, said: ``This is the most important ruling on the
Children's Act since it came into existence.
``It would stop cases such as the Satanic abuse case and would stop children
being removed from their families on the basis of suspicion alone.''
However, the Association of Directors of Social Services said the ruling could
put children in danger.
Former president Robin Sequiera said: ``It is a very significant judgment which
flies in the face of the role of the lower courts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Life for the classroom killer who police say would not have stopped at one victim Teachers who halted massacre</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STEPHEN Wilkinson, a paranoid schizophrenic, would have killed all 25 children
in a classroom he raided if he had not been stopped, a detective said last
night.
It was a view echoed by parents and teachers as they poured out their feelings
in the aftermath of his trial at a news conference at Cleveland Police
headquarters.
Detective Chief Inspector Brian Leonard, who led the inquiry, said: ``He wanted
to go out in style and I suspect he went in not to kill one child but to kill
them all.''
One girl died in the incident in March last year. Nikki Conroy's killer was
sent to a secure hospital for the criminally insane for the rest of his life
after his trial came to an abrupt halt yesterday.
The jury at Leeds Crown Court was directed by the judge to return a formal
verdict of guilty to manslaughter on the grounds of diminished responsibility
after four forensic psychiatrists all agreed he was severely mentally ill on
the day of the attack.
Wilkinson, 31, of Middlesbrough, Cleveland, denied murdering Nikki Conroy, 12,
but admitted manslaughter on the grounds of diminished responsibility. He also
pled guilty to the attempted murders of Michelle Reeve, 13, and Emma Winter, 12.
Nikki died of multiple stab wounds and Michelle and Emma were also knifed after
revolver-wielding Wilkinson burst into their maths lesson at Hall Garth
comprehensive, Middlesbrough, and forced teacher Graham Nellist to leave.
Wilkinson was overpowered when the school's deputy head, Mr Chris Bielby, and
teaching colleague Dave Eland, alerted by Mr Nellist, stormed in. Only later
was the handgun found to be a replica.
Wilkinson, a jobless loner with a genius level IQ, had also been armed with
three knives and an axe. The court heard how more children would almost
certainly have died if the teachers had not charged in at that point.
Recommending bravery commendations for the teachers, Mrs Justice Smith said:
``By their actions they in fact prevented the tragedy from being any greater.''
There had been a burden on the defence during the trial, which began on Monday,
to satisfy the jury that Wilkinson was suffering from a mental abnormality. The
judge accepted that this had been done.
Nikki's parents, Peter and Diane, were in the public gallery. They were in a
very emotional state, with Mrs Conroy weeping and being comforted by her
husband.
The judge said to them: ``There is not a person in this court who does not
sympathise with your point of view but I do hope you will accept this decision
has not been taken lightly but with great care by the doctors, by counsel, and
by me.''
Wilkinson told psychiatrists that before the attack he sat alone drinking
whisky and it was then his ``dark side alter ego'', which he named Wilson
Jinks, took over.
He spoke of Jinks leaving the house in his body and he felt compelled to go
along too. He watched, he said, as Jinks carried out the attack.
The view that a mass killing could have happened was echoed by Mr Bielby and Mr
Eland. They charged in immediately they saw him stabbing at the children. He
had made them kneel on the floor in a line with their eyes closed.
Mr Bielby said: ``I believe he would have worked his way along the row of
children, having started at one end. I feel that was his intention - I don't
know where he would have stopped.
``As soon as we saw what was happening, there was no choice - we had to stop
him and get the children out. Anyone in that situation would have done the
same.''
The actions of the teachers, including Mr Nellist who was forced out of the
room at gunpoint by Wilkinson, were roundly praised by Nikki's parents. But Mr
Conroy said: ``I think at the time he was sane although now he is insane. I
will always believe he went into that school knowing what he was going to do.''
He added: ``I think the parents of the girls and boys who were in that class
should now think that if it wasn't for these three teachers their children
would not be here because he would have killed them all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sports complex a step nearer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OBAN has taken a step closer to realising a #2.1m project to create a new
sports facility with confirmation by Argyll and the Islands Enterprise of a
#150,000 package. EU funding is expected to meet the rest of the cost.
The scheme is centred on the town's swimming pool. A sports hall, health suite,
and indoor climbing facilities will be added.
Aids warning
THE man who first established the risk of transmitting HIV through sexual
contact yesterday warned of the dangers of complacency about the situation.
Professor Bill Darrow, of Florida International University, told a conference
in Edinburgh that community-based programmes were the key to preventing a
resurgence.
Bomber jailed
BUSINESSMAN John Bilsland, 39, of Orkie Farm House, Freuchie, Fife, who
petrol-bombed a Cupar video shop in August after it set up operations in direct
competition with premises run by his wife, was jailed for six months yesterday
at Cupar Sheriff Court.
DB5 stopped
AN Aston Martin DB5 which Pierce Brosnan drove as James Bond in the film
GoldenEye failed to reach its reserve after bidding stopped at #108,000 at a
London auction last night.
Santa stolen
AN 18in gnome-like Santa has been stolen from a Christmas display at Regent
Centre, Kirkintilloch.
Trust purchase
THE National Trust for Scotland has acquired Miller House, an eighteenth
century listed building in Church Street, Cromarty. It is associated with the
writer and geologist Hugh Miller, who was born in a nearby cottage and lived in
the house between 1837 and 1840.
Fire-raiser guilty
AN Inverness woman was found guilty at Inverness Sheriff Court yesterday of
wilful fire-raising in a house in Glendoe Terrace in May. No-one was injured
but the flat was destroyed. Carol Stewart, 28, of Craigton Avenue, was placed
on three years' probation and ordered to do 200 hours of community service.
No stitch in time
THE Principal of Aberdeen's Northern College, Mr David Adams, flew to Lerwick
yesterday for Shetland's first graduation ceremony for distance-learning
students and found that their gowns had not arrived in the mail. The ceremony
went on regardless.
Hat trick
CHARLIE Chaplin's black bowler hat and cane was sold at auction in London
yesterday to a Swiss museum for #44,750.
Polar Bar
EXPLORER Sir Ranulph Fiennes was presented at Buckingham Palace yesterday with
a Bar to the Polar Medal he was awarded in 1984. Dr Michael Stroud, who
accompanied Sir Ranulph to the South Pole in 1992 and 1993, also received the
Polar Medal.
All the best
A SIMPLE guide to all the events at Edinburgh's five-day Hogmanay festival will
be available to millions of computer users on the World Wide Internet. It was
designed by a local software company, NXYS Ltd.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Problem boy, 8, earns family eviction</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SINGLE mother of three is facing eviction after complaints from her
neighbours about noise and the behaviour of her eight-year-old son.
Mrs Maureen Shanley was taken to court by Edinburgh District Council, which
wanted her thrown out of the house at Granton View. At Edinburgh Sheriff Court
yesterday, Sheriff Andrew Lothian granted the eviction order.
The council had already been to court, in 1994, after complaints about Mrs
Shanley's son Craig. It obtained an interdict ordering Mrs Shanley not to allow
members of her household to damage neighbours' doors, windows, or gardens or to
cause disturbance.
Sheriff Lothian said yesterday that the neighbours, who previously enjoyed a
quiet life, had suffered ``far beyond what should be expected''.
He accepted that it was a difficult case as it involved young children, but
pointed out that problems had been persistent.
Sometimes the behaviour of Mrs Shanley and her family had been quite
deliberate, added the sheriff.
He rejected a suggestion from Mrs Shanley's solicitor that he should order the
council to rehouse the family. ``I would simply be asking the landlord to move
the problem somewhere else,'' he said.
Neighbours told yesterday's hearing that Craig had caused problems by kicking
his football against a gate and into gardens. They claimed he had also been
involved in spitting at younger children living nearby and throwing stones at
windows and passing cars.
Mrs Shanley, 41, said some of the claims made by her neighbours were made up
and others exaggerated.
One 73-year-old neighbour told Sheriff Andrew Lothian how another elderly man
was ``harassed and baited'' by a group of youngsters including Craig Shanley.
He ran from the group several times and swiped the man's face with his empty
jacket sleeve to the cheers of the other youngsters.
The pensioner also complained about a dog howling and barking, full-blast rave
music, and rows involving screamed abuse. He also said that Mrs Shanley had
recently tried to intimidate him.
Mrs Shanley said she had controlled her son as best she could since the
interdict was granted against her. She said he was hyperactive and accepted
that he had ongoing problems at school.
``I just think that things are blown out of all proportion,'' she said. She
denied allegations of late-night noise and of members of the family
deliberately jumping on the floor to annoy neighbours.
She described one neighbour, at the forefront of complaints against her, as a
``very sad old man'' who sat at his window all day noting the car numbers of
people who visited the Shanley house.
He had falsely accused Mrs Shanley and her elder daughter of being prostitutes
and her four-year-old daughter was ``terrified'' of him, she said.
</TEXT>
