<DOCNO>GH951215-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Venables loses case but feels vindicated</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880851</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND soccer coach Terry Venables last night spoke of his disappointment at
losing a court battle in which a judge questioned his reliability as a witness
and cast doubt on the way he did business.
The controversial football figure, whose claim that he has been the victim of a
``conspiracy'' to damage his reputation was also rejected, was speaking
following a ruling that his London club, Scribes West, had to pay up over a
disputed bill.
In a statement issued by his solicitor, Mr Nick Trainer, Mr Venables said he
was ``disappointed'' he had been ordered to pay a proportion of the original
claim as well as a large slice of advertising executive Jeffrey Fugler's legal
bill.
``However, I feel significantly vindicated in that the claim (for #19,379.88
plus interest) was almost halved and his outrageous tactics and allegations of
dishonesty resulted in Mr Fugler being able to recover less than half the costs
he originally applied for.''
He said the comment by Mr Recorder Williams that ``forged'' invoices Mr Fugler
had disclosed ``were an April Fool's joke or created deliberately to discredit
me is very important''.
Of equal importance was the judge's concern ``at the close proximity in time''
of Mr Fugler's witness statement and its details appearing in the Daily
Telegraph.
``My QC, David Farrer, described the use of the forged invoices as blackmail
and the judge did not disagree with him,'' said Mr Venables.
He added: ``I believe that Mr Fugler will be significantly out of pocket in
this case and I wish this to be an example that I will not yield to such
disgraceful tactics.''
Mr Venables's own legal costs are thought to be in the region of #100,000.
Together with the judge's decision that he would also have to pay half of Mr
Fugler's costs and the #11,292-plus-interest portion of the businessman's
claim, add up to a final bill of nearly #160,000 for the soccer coach.
The case centred on an unpaid bill of nearly #20,000 owed for a campaign to
promote the soccer coach's then ailing club.
Mr Fugler, 43, who carried out the work, said he had received only a third of
#30,000 that should have been due to him for distributing 20,000 leaflets.
The judge, who strongly rebuked the businessman for the way he had handled part
of the affair, said because he had failed in some of his arguments his award
would be reduced.
</TEXT>
