<DOCNO>GH951215-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MONETARY POLICY Bundesbank leads the way</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank led western European central banks in cutting interest rates
yesterday, cutting its main discount rates by half-of-a-percentage point.
The German central bank cut its discount and Lombard rates to 3% and 5%
respectively, the first cut since August. It also cut its key money market rate
to 3.75% from 3.98% at the same time.
The Swiss National Bank anticipated the German move, announcing a few minutes
earlier it was lowering its discount rate to 1.5% from 2.0%, effective from
today.
The Bundesbank's policy-making council held its final meeting of 1995 with many
markets undecided whether it would follow Britain's lead on Wednesday and cut
rates or wait until the new year.
The markets took the the cuts in their stride, reacting little to the changes
they had long been calling for.
The Bundesbank said it had also decided to set a wider growth target of four to
7% for its main monetary policy indicator, M3 money supply, next year, compared
with this year's four to 6% goal.
In a statement, it said money supply developments, coupled with the strength of
the mark and favourable inflation prospects gave it room to cut rates.
Weaker-than-expected third quarter growth data published last week showing
year-on-year expansion of just 1.5% had triggered a chorus of calls for it to
give the economy more breathing room by reducing the cost of borrowing.
But some analysts had said the loud calls for interest rate cuts from German
banks, politicians and labour groups might prove counter-productive, as the
fiercely independent central bank never liked to be seen to be bowing to
outside pressure.
The Belgian, Dutch, Austrian and Danish central banks swiftly followed the
German lead.
The Belgian National Bank cut its key central interest rate to 3.75% from
3.95%, effective from today.
The central bank cut its end-of-day rate to 5% from 5.2%. The discount rate was
cut to 3% from 3.5%.
Denmark's Central Bank said it cut 14-day certificates of deposit (CD) and
two-week state paper repurchase rates to 4.75% from 5%, also effective as of
today.
At the same time, the bank trimmed its discount and key deposit rates to 4.25%
from 4.75%.
The Dutch central bank said it cut its key secured loans rate to 2.75% from
3.25%, effective today.
The secured loans rate applies to commercial banks' daily borrowing at the
central bank under a three-month credit quota.
The Austrian National Bank cut its discount rate to 3% from 3.5% in line with
the moves by the other European central banks.
</TEXT>
