<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UK ECONOMY Inflation data show Chancellor on course</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By R E DUNDAS Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BENIGN set of inflation figures yesterday gave substance to the view, shared
by the Chancellor of the Exchequer and the Governor of the Bank of England,
that the Government is on course to reduce the underlying inflation rate to
2.5% or less by early next year.
The two men were aware of the November inflation figures when they met on
Wednesday and decided to reduce interest rates by a quarter of a point to 6.5%.
The Bundesbank weighed in yesterday with half-point cuts in its discount and
Lombard rates and a 0.23% cut its repo money market. The US is expected to
reduce its Fed funds rate by a quarter point on Tuesday.
With inflationary pressures moderating and rates falling overseas, City hopes
are high that UK rates will drop by another 0.25% when Kenneth Clarke meets
Eddie George on January 17.
Adam Cole, UK economists at stockbrokers James Capel, said that smaller changes
in rates meant they could be more frequent.
The Retail Price Index was unchanged last month at 149.8 (January 1987 = 100),
and the headline rate edged down from 3.2% in October to 3.1%. The underlying
rate, which excludes mortgage interest payments, was unchanged at 2.9%. The
RPIY rate, which excludes indirect and local government taxes as well as
mortgage payments, was also unchanged at 2.4%.
The three month annualised RPIY rate has fallen to around 2% after seasonal
adjustment. Mr Cole said, ``This was the fifth consecutive monthly fall in
inflation on this basis and the significant gap opening up between annual and
shorter term measures of inflation suggests a further deceleration over the
coming months.''
The Central Statistical Office said the biggest contribution to the annual
headline rate came from motoring costs falling more steeply this November than
last.
Motoring costs fell by 0.8% last month, compared with a decline of 0.4% in
November last year. This was mainly due to steeper reductions in car prices.
Petrol prices also fell.
Other significant effects on the headline rate came from prices for food and
household goods which had smaller rises than last year and from sharper
reductions in alcohol prices than last November.
Seasonal food prices declined by 0.7% last month in contrast to a rise of 0.3%
in November last year. Non-seasonal food prices rose by 0.2% against an
increase of 0.4% in the same month last year.
Special pre-Christmas offers on alcoholic drinks reduced prices by 0.5%
compared with a drop of 0.3% last November. A rise of 0.8% in household goods
prices was lower than last year's 1% increase.
Mr Cole said: ``Inflation in several of the key High Street sectors fell back
in the month while service sector inflation remains within a whisker of its
all-time lows.
``The latter, which is relatively unaffected by the recent rise in import
prices, underlines the extent to which domestically generated inflation
pressures are all but non-existent.''
Goldman Sachs, the investment bank, estimates that the Budget measures will
take 0.2% off the underlying rate over the next two months as a result of the
non-indexation of alcohol duties in the Budget and last year's mini-Budget
measures dropping out of the annual calculation.
David Walton, Goldman's senior economist, said: ``Our forecasts show a
plateauing in inflation at close to current levels throughout 1996, falling to
below the Government's 2.5% target in the first half of 1997.
``This should enable the Chancellor to announce further base rate cuts in
coming months and we continue to expect a fall to 5.75% by the middle of next
year.''
The CSO announced that the #50 electricity rebates due to households in England
and Wales would not be treated as a price reduction. Its inclusion would have
resulted in a sharp drop in inflation next year followed by a big jump in 1997
as it dropped out of the annual comparison.
</TEXT>
