<DOCNO>GH951215-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Norman's conquest continues unabated, despite grumbles from competitors about promotion tactics.  Asda half-time profits jump 27.2%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880855</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Archie Norman revitalisation of Asda continues with half-time profits
jumping 27.2% to #138m based on the best sales growth in the supermarket
sector. These rose 12.6% in like-for-like stores with the underlying volume
jumping 9.7% thanks in part to the increasing success of the George range of
clothing - that is now fully owned.
The City liked what he was saying yesterday and the shares initially advanced
to 109p in a flurry of analyst upgrades before closing only 1p better at
106!sp. Most revisions were around #15m to about #300m.
He dismissed speculation that he was on any Tory Party short list, telling a
press conference ``this is not a career meeting'' and that he is committed to
Asda for the next three years.
He also defended not giving #20 Christmas bonuses to some staff who had been
absent in the previous six months for whatever reason although that was partly
up to the store manager's decision. But some 95% will receive an entitlement.
He claimed 90% of Asda workers are happy in their jobs with union membership in
the past three years having declined from 72% to 19% and Asda having given the
largest pay rises in the sector, some 95% will receive an entitlement.
Asda is accepting all the vouchers, such as those from competitors loyalty
cards, until Sunday in all its 207 stores to increase quite substantially the
retailing pressure before Christmas.
Tesco has already complained to the Advertising Standards Authority about a
pilot test last week.
Last night Tesco said that it was an empty gesture and that Asda customers must
be fed up. ``Do Asda want them to stop at Tesco to qualify for cash discounts
at Asda?''
Three stores will be open for 24-hours including Edinburgh although that will
place a considerable strain on the managements.
Although thwarted at present until the Office of Fair Trading decides whether
Asda can resume selling over the counter medicaments and vitamins at discount
prices, Mr Norman is promising an alternative strategy but is saying little at
present.
The like-for-like volume gains after stripping out the additions from new
openings are appreciably higher than for Tesco and Safeway while both J
Sainsbury and Kwik Save are in decline.
That is partly due to offering the cheapest shopping basket of the big four
supermarket chains which has resulted in operating margins, although rising
0.4% to 4.7%, still well below the Sainsbury 7.8%, the Safeway 6.9% and Tesco's
6.0%.
Mr Norman said that gross margins will remain under pressure and the way
forward was through increasing efficiencies including the introduction of a
#70m information systems programme. Sales per employee rose 8% in the 28 weeks
to November 11.
Yet the advertising spend in the last six months was the lowest amongst the
majors at #6m compared with the Sainsbury figure at #16m at the other extreme.
That speaks volumes about customer acceptance.
The opening programme is for six new stores including Govan and Queensferry and
two refurbishments - Cumbernauld and Hartlepool. That is unlikely to accelerate
as a result of ever tighter planning restrictions.
Some 18 stores have so far been converted this year and there are another 80
awaiting conversion to underpin growth in the short to medium term.
The interim dividend has been increased 18% to 0.72p.
</TEXT>
