<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ELECTRICITY Hydro-Electric profits from an increase in sales of power to the south</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Hydro-Electric is steadily increasing its power sales throughout the
UK, unlike most of the regional electricity companies (RECs) which rely on
efficiency gains to boost profits in a restricted local market.
An 18% increase in the volume of electricity sold to customers in England and
Wales helped Hydro-Electric boost operating profits by 10.8% to #64.8m during
the six months to September 30.
The Perth-based company sells more than a third of its electricity south of the
Border and this is its main focus for future expansion.
Pre-tax profits nearly doubled to #61.7m, but this reflects the fact that
first-half earnings were held back last year by an #18.8m exceptional charge
for the early redemption of a bond issue.
The interim dividend was raised by 9.4% to 4.75p, because Hydro-Electric is
saving its strength for several large investments.
But investors, whose expectations have been raised by the special dividends
paid out by cash-rich English RECs, were maybe expecting more. Hydro-Electric
shares fell 2p to 359p.
The company plans to build a string of new power stations in England and Wales
and it still has a slim chance of acquiring the pumped storage business which
has been demerged from National Grid.
This consists of two hydro-electric power stations in Wales which produce up to
2300 megawatts of power at peak periods.
At other times, when electricity is cheaper, they draw power from the grid to
pump water back up hill ready for the next surge in demand.
Hydro-Electric and two US power companies are due to submit their final offers
today, but the Scottish company will probably be outbid.
One American company has already indicated that it is willing to pay up to
#600m, but Hydro-Electric would upset the City if it went much over #450m.
``We aren't willing to overpay,'' said chief executive Roger Young. ``If
somebody else bids higher than us we will be sorry, but we will not be
unhappy.''
A partnership with British Gas to build a 730-megawatt gas-fired power station
at Avonmouth near Bristol looks more likely to get off the ground.
This project would demand #150m of investment from Hydro-Electric. A final
decision was expected within six months, but Mr Young said everything depends
on the outcome of negotiations on a gas supply contract.
Hydro-Electric has no ambition to buy a REC, unlike ScottishPower which spent
#1130m on buying Manweb.
But it is keen to develop a partnership with a REC in the electricity supply
business.
This could take the shape of a joint venture to sell power to domestic
consumers throughout England and Wales after the electricity market is fully
liberalised in 1998.
Hydro-Electric would generate and supply the power and the REC would look after
distribution.
However, this project been put on hold until takeover fever in the electricity
sector subsides.
``All the discussions we had been having are in the freezer at the moment while
the chaos among the RECs settles down,'' Mr Young said.
A more immediate prospect is the commissioning of Keadby gas-fired power
station near Scunthorpe on Humberside, a #250m joint venture with Norweb.
The 680-megawatt power station is 11 months late in coming on stream as a
result of problems with its US-made turbines, but Mr Young said it would be
finally commissioned ``in the next two or three days''.
Hydro-Electric and Norweb are seeking ``tens of millions of pounds'' of
compensation from the builder, Trafalgar House, because of this delay.
But Mr Young made clear they would settle for less than the #50m initially
claimed. An out-of-court settlement is expected with six weeks. Trafalgar House
will pass on the cost to General Electric, which manufactured the turbines.
Hydro-Electric is meanwhile close to clinching its biggest ever combined heat
and power project in England.
Mr Young said it should finalise the deal worth #25m to #30m within two months.
The project involves building a power station next to a large factory to supply
it with a cheap and reliable source of energy.
Hydro-Electric already operates several similar schemes south of the Border.
Although there is limited scope for increasing power sales to Hydro-Electric's
800,000 core customers in the north of Scotland, the volume of electricity sold
to them rose 3% in the first half of this year.
This mainly reflected a bounceback from the dip in electricity consumption
which took place after VAT was imposed on heating bills in 1994.
</TEXT>
