<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>London fails to shine</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880857</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONDON Electricity, one of the few regional electricity companies that has not
yet been bid for, is suffering the impact of sharp tariff cuts imposed this
year by the regulator.
Pre-tax profits before exceptional items were little changed at #84.5m despite
a 2% increase in the volume of electricity delivered to customers.
But since #42.5m of exceptional charges for restructuring the company and
redeeming government debt were deducted from last year's interim profits, the
bottom line actually doubled.
London therefore felt able to increase the interim dividend by 21% to 11.5p. It
is also paying a 100p special dividend which was announced last month.
But the stock market was unimpressed and London shares fell 16p to 678p.
A fall in earnings from distribution had been expected after electricty
regulator Stephen Littlechild ordered London to cut its tariff for domestic
customers by 14% in real terms this year.
On a more positive note, London managed to trim distribution costs and boost
power sales to large businesses by 12%.
Unlike some other regional electricity companies (RECs) which are investing in
generation and other forms of diversification, London aims to stick closely to
its knitting as a distributor and supplier.
``London's primary objective is to be a low-cost provider of a high quality
electricity service to all its customers,'' chairman Sir Bob Reid said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Southern disappoints</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880858</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOUTHERN Electric beat all profit forecasts yesterday, but it disappointed the
City with a lower-than-expected special dividend of 50p.
Southern shares fell 12p to 916p because the market had expected Southern to
match a 100p payout by Midlands Electricity earlier this month or even beat it.
The dividend news took the shine off a 19.7% increase in pre-tax profits to
#127.8m for the six months to September 30, which beat forecasts of #105m to
#121m.
Southern raised its interim dividend by 26% to 10.5p, but with gearing low at
12.2%, many felt a higher special payout could easily have been afforded.
Turnover decreased slightly to #732.7m as tariff cuts imposed by the regulator
took their toll, but the volume of electricity sold increased 1.2%.
Chairman Geoffery Wilson reiterated his support for a proposed merger with the
generator NationalPower.
NationalPower made an agreed #2800m bid for Southern in October, but this has
been on ice since the Government referred it to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission on November 23.
Mr Wilson said: ``We continue to believe that a combination of the two
companies would create a broadly-based energy business able to complete
strongly in the UK and overseas, so we will strongly support the case for it to
be allowed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two down, one to go as Germans cut rates</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was the Bundesbank's turn yesterday to deliver the goods. It cut its
discount and Lombard rates by a full half-point and its repo rate by 0.23%.
The Lombard and discount rates set the upper and lower band in the corridor of
interest rates. The repo rate, which often moves in very small steps, is the
closest to base rates in the UK.
So there is nothing in yesterday's move by the German central bank to suggest
that they were seeking to upstage the quarter-point reduction in UK rates on
Wednesday.
Chancellor Clarke had made a virtue out of cutting rates by less than many had
expected or thought necessary. He claimed that this brought Britain more into
line with Continental and North American practice and was appropriate now that
Britain was no longer a high-inflation country.
If the Federal Open Market Committee, which meets on Tuesday, decides to ease
US monetary policy it is expected that the Fed funds rates will be reduced by a
quarter point to 5.5%.
The global economy has largely recovered from the recession of the early
nineties, though Japan has lagged far behind the rest of the pack. Currently
most economies are suffering from a mid-cycle slow-down in activity.
Both Britain and the US had to raise interest rates to apply the brakes after
periods of hectic growth. They are now cutting them again in response to the
slowdown.
Germany on the other hand was late into the recession and one of the last to
recover from it. Subsequent growth never threatened to generate fresh
inflationary pressures and activity has slowed markedly, because of the
strength of the mark rather than a tightening of monetary policy.
The core Continental countries, whose currencies track the German mark, are in
the same boat as Germany. Britain too has suffered from the lacklustre economic
performance on the Continent. Export markets there have shrunk just when
domestic orders were weakening.
As a result inflationary pressures are abating more quickly than might have
been expected. The latest inflation figures suggest that the peak is close at
hand and that the Government's target of a 2.5% underlying rate by early 1997
can be achieved.
The Bank of England has been forced to change its tune in accordance with these
trends. In May it was demanding a rise in rates to fight inflation. By
September it said this was no longer necessary. This week it was happy to claim
it advised the Chancellor to cut rates.
The betting in the City is that there will be another threequarter-point
reductions in base rates in the new year. However, it is worth bearing in mind
that the last trough in UK rates was higher and the last peak lower than the
pundits expected.
Norman era
ASDA'S tearaway rise in like-for-like volume sales which on the latest figures
were over half as much again as Tesco and twice those of Safeway, only
underline the increasing polarisation of supermarkets with J Sainsbury seeing a
drop of 2.2% and the even worse 3.3% setback at Kwik Save.
That has led to a further round of profit estimate reductions for Sainsbury and
will undoubtedly increase institutional pressure on what was once the sector
darling to liven up its management.
Asda's concentration on superstores has so far been proved correct and there is
plenty of more organic growth to come. Archie Norman is talking happily of
5%-10% annual growth for the next three years. A large proportion of that would
seem assured thanks to the on-going store revival programme with only half the
portfolio so far treated.
That is more likely to provide impetus than the openings which are likely to be
around six stores a year with planning permissions ever more difficult to win.
However, the major Norman achievement is to boost the number of weekly
customers over three years from 4.2 million to 5.5 million as the brand changes
its image of fatigue and underinvestment into a much more user friendly
environment. Despite a cheaper shopping basket than the competition the
proportion of fresh produce continues to expand.
The purchase of the outstanding half stake in the Burwood House property
company from BAe may have helped put the group into debt. But with now control
over #340m of freehold, there is a substantial reserve asset available for sale
and lease back to provide cash for acquisition.
Asda is rising the crest of the wave at present and seems likely to increase
full year profits by a sixth to about #300m and maybe #340m for next year. But
then maturity may be starting to creep across the Asda horizon as the expansion
programme slows and Archie Norman could then be re-thinking his career as he
could be the new star in the new opposition party.
Canny move
SCOTTISH Hydro-Electric does not pay out special dividends like the English
regional electricity companies (RECs), which are still flush with cash, despite
the tariff cuts imposed upon them earlier this year.
But being a generator as well as a distributor, it undoubtedly has better
growth prospects than most power companies south of the Border.
Wisely, it is putting aside much of its cash to fund future expansion.
Hydro-Electric already gets 30% of its revenue from power sold outwith its
heartland in the north of Scotland.
This proportion will rise as it builds more power stations in England and Wales
and sets itself up to supply domestic consumers throughout the UK once the
market is liberalised in 1998.
It is worth noting that Hydro-Electric increased its volume sales of
electricity by 6% during the six months to September, with sales to England and
Wales soaring by 18%.
During the same period, London Electricity and Southern Electric, only boosted
volume sales by 1% to 2%. But then again, these RECs stick closely to their
home territory.
Nevertheless Hydro-Electric often finds it difficult to be taken seriously. It
is widely viewed as a small and marginal player on the northern fringes of the
UK.
This has kept its share price in check, but perhaps fortunately, it has also
kept predators at bay.
Lacking the size of ScottishPower, Hydro-Electric cannot afford to buy a REC.
Neither does it wish to.
But there is merit in its idea of teaming up with a REC in a joint venture to
exploit the liberalisation of the domestic supply market in just over two years
time. If you can't beat 'em, join 'em.
</TEXT>
