<DOCID>GH951215-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TELECOMMUNICATIONS Securicor trades strongly helped by Cellnet subsidiary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was strong trading throughout almost all the businesses in the Securicor,
security, distribution, and communications group in the year to September 30.
This coupled with contributions from acquisitions enabled profits to climb by
23.3% to #99.4m.
Its Cellnet mobile phone subsidiary continued to make a considerable
contribution to the group with profits rising by 26% to #70.6m. Cellnet is
still outperforming its rivals in terms of growth in new subscribers and is
close to overtaking the market leader, Vodafone.
The strong growth in Cellnet's subscriber base was attributed to better
consumer tariffs and new value added business services. Although pre-Christmas
sales are not as strong as this time last year, marketing director Steve Rowley
expects to sign up another 80,000-100,000 new subscribers.
Options continue to be explored as to the future of the Cellnet business within
Securicor after the breakdown of disposal talks with BT earlier in the year.
This followed a veto by the DTI. The BT talks cost Securicor #1.2m.
Elsewhere in the group the distribution business which includes parcel
delivery, did well winning new business and increasing its profits from #9.6m
to #12.8m. The security division faced stiff home competition but expanding
overseas opportunities.
Securicor sold its UK alarms to BET in return for its manned guarding operation
Shorrock Guards. Overall, the alarms business lost #2.8m in the year.
The cash services business also faced pressure on margins although it continued
to win new business and continues to dominate the market. The rapid growth of
ATMs has provided extra business.
The custodial services business is said to have performed strongly and enjoyed
a successful year with the Metropolitan Court Escort and Custody contract in
London.
The Communications business, which includes the Datatrak vehicle tracking
system, made its first profit of #1.2m, helped by strong growth in its
subscriber base.
Business Services raised its profit by #300,000 to #3.2m. The recruitment
business benefited from the opening of new branches. Hotels continued to
perform well with high occupancy rates and the vehicle services business also
grew. It has recently formed a joint venture with Iveco Ford Truck for the
contract management of Iveco vans and trucks throughout the UK.
Heavy investment in the Securicor Group in recent years both organically and
via acquisitions has taken its toll on gearing which has risen from 18% to 60%.
The shares will continue to reflect speculation about the future of the Cellnet
stake. Yesterday Securicor shares dropped 5p to 1680p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
