<DOCID>GH951215-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Print costs bite at Mail</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880861</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Print costs
bite at Mail
NEWSPRINT costs have taken their toll at the Daily Mail and General Trust,
publisher of the Daily Mail, London Evening Standard and Mail on Sunday,
although the group is looking for a return to growth in the current year.
In the year to October 1, DMGT's pre-tax profits fell from #92.1m to #80m
before exceptional items, and to #66.8m after exceptionals.
The pre-exceptionals decline reflected the substantial increase in newsprint
prices which, during most of the period, was not passed on to customers, and
increased investment in start-up operations. Nearly #20m more was spent on
newsprint than in the previous year.
However, the downward trend in profits is expected to be reversed in the
current year. As a sign of confidence the final dividend on the Ordinary and
`A' Ordinary shares has been lifted from 12.5p to 13.5p taking the total from
16.5p to 17.8p.
M&amp;G holds profits
INVESTMENT management group, M&amp;G has managed to hold profits in spite of a
difficult trading climate and continuing short-term uncertainty.
In the year to September profits before exceptional items came to #61.2m in the
year to September, almost exactly unchanged on 1993-94. Dividends are raised by
7% to 32p after a final of 18p.
Group revenue was marginally ahead at #78m, with a #6.3m fall in initial
charges offset by a #7.2m rise in annual fees.
M&amp;G is confident for the long-term investment outlook despite short-term
uncertainties such as the forthcoming general election. The shares slipped 8p
to 1270p, where they yield 3.1%.
Medeva post
MEDEVA, the international pharmaceutical company, has announced that Garry
Watts is to be its new finance director. Mr Watts, a partner in the accountancy
firm KPMG and head of its Health and Life Sciences practice, will join the
Medeva board on February 1. His appointment follows the departure of Dennis
Millard to join Cookson Group.
Shire floats
SHIRE Pharmaceuticals, a company specialising in the marketing, licensing and
development of prescription medicines primarily for age-related diseases of the
bone and central nervous system, is planning to float on the London Stock
Exchange. Founded in 1986, Shire concentrates on the prevention and treatment
of diseases such as Osteoporosis and Alzheimer's. A placing of the shares with
institutional investors is planned. Panmure Gordon is acting as sponsor and
stockbroker to the company.
Good start
FOOD products group Albert Fisher says it has made a satisfactory start to its
current financial year in most of its businesses despite challenging market
conditions. Speaking at the company's annual meeting, chairman Stephen Walls
said that there were clear growth opportunities in many of the company's
markets.
Widows sells
SCOTTISH Widows has sold a portfolio of eight freehold commercial properties to
Burford Holdings for #48.7m. The reversionary portfolio generates a net annual
rental income of around #3.4m and within two years the yield will increase from
7% to 8%. The major property is a building in London's Covent Garden and the
package includes office space in London and large stores in various cities.
</TEXT>
