<HEADLINE>DIRECTORS `Fast track' plan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FAST-TRACK procedure is to be introduced to try and cut the growing backlog
of court applications for disqualification of insolvent company directors who
are considered unfit to manage.
Richard Scott, the High Court judge who announced the move yesterday, urged
Trade and Industry Secretary Ian Lang to consider introducing an amendment to
the law, making a court hearing unnecessary when a director does not dispute
being barred for an agreed period sufficient to protect the public interest.
At present, the DTI or the Official Receiver is required under the 1986 Company
Directors' Disqualification Act to apply to the court for a disqualification
order.
</TEXT>
