<DOCNO>GH951215-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister pledges support</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880864</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TONY Baldry, UK Minister of State for Agriculture, has given the National Sheep
Association an assurance that he will do everything possible to safeguard the
needs of the sheep industry and the auction market system when new legislation
on the transport of animals is being framed.
The National Sheep Association has asked the Minister to ensure that the new
directive proposed by Brussels should be interpreted in such a way as to
protect the UK sheep industry and traditional trading patterns, using the live
auction system.
In a meeting with the Minister, Joe Stoddart, NSA president, pointed out that
the natural, extensive system in the UK was geared to grass production. The
earliest grass production was in the south and the growth pattern moved north
and from low ground to hill.
The lamb production pattern followed that same cycle, providing a flow of lambs
to abattoirs which started in the south early in the year and moved north.
``Good, efficient, welfare-friendly transport is therefore an essential
ingredient of our business,'' he said.
In Scotland the Institute of Auctioneers and Appraisers has also been
expressing its concerns about the possible impact of new transport regulations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
