<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Training custom designed for the future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sheila Waddell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880865</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sheila Waddell reports on a scheme   which allows young people and companies to
work together to create worthwhile jobs
SCOTLAND's prosperity depends on the ability of companies to compete in world
markets. If they are to do so effectively, they must have access to a well
trained workforce. The Skillseekers Initiative addresses this challenge
directly by aiming to provide employers with the trained workers they require.
A development of its predecessor, the Youth Training Programme, Skillseekers
give both young people and employers a real say in the training involved, as
both parties sit down together and draw up a training plan which sets targets
to match the requirements of the workplace. It gives young people the
opportunity to train for their desired career and ensures that they receive
training towards vocational qualifications.
The Skillseekers Initiative was originally launched in Grampian Region in 1991.
Glasgow Skillseekers, developed by Glasgow Development Agency, started in April
1994. Around 3700 young people from Glasgow are currently participating in the
Skillseekers Initiative.
A glance through the latest Skillseekers training directory shows there is a
well established network of training suppliers in a broad range of fields.
These range from business administration, where young people can train to be
secretaries and receptionists, through artistic fields where there are training
opportunities for those interested in photography, graphic design and
floristry, to engineering occupations.
There are also several well known employers like Yarrow Shipbuilders, Weir
Pumps and the Royal Mail who have recognised the benefits and are now actively
involved in Skillseekers and contract directly with the GDA.
Skillseekers offers a range of benefits to employers:
lTraining is more clearly related to the needs of the workplace.
lThe opportunity to offer quality training to a recognised national industry
standard which will help employers to achieve more flexibility, greater
efficiency and increased productivity.
lYoung people who are recruited will be clear about their career choice. They
will therefore be motivated to succeed, accept responsibility and contribute to
company success.
lA direct contribution toward the cost of training young employees.
Willie Fortucci, Director of Training within Glasgow Development Agency, said:
``The success of any company depends largely on the quality and commitment of
its staff. Having a motivated workforce is a vital asset in today's business
climate. Skillseekers enables companies to recruit and develop their employees
to ensure a competitive advantage.''
All Skillseekers will work towards the achievement of vocational qualifications
(VQs) which prove that they can carry out an employer's work to recognised
Iidustry standards. VQs are designed for industry by industry, to standards set
by Lead Bodies and Industrial Training Organisations such as the Engineering
Training Authority, the Hotel and Catering Training Company and the
Construction Industry Training Board.
Skillseekers gives the employer the option of having greater control over the
management and delivery of training. As Shirley Davison, Skillseeker's
Development Executive, said: ``Employers can become involved in Skillseekers in
a number of ways. They can have a direct contract with the Glasgow Development
Agency either as an approved centre, delivering the training themselves, or by
sub contracting elements of the training. A third alternative is to appoint a
training supplier to deliver and manage the training on their behalf.
``Our Skillseekers employer team, based within the Training Directorate, can
advise on which route is best suited to meet the needs of the company.''
Where a company has opted for the direct contract route - funding, which is
reviewed annually, is based on the type of job and the level of vocational
qualifications being sought. For each Skillseeker the funding for employers
will range from #4200 and #8000 and is released when training outcomes have
been achieved.
All 16-18-year-olds leaving full time education and resident within the city of
Glasgow are eligible for Skillseekers. In addition, any of Glasgow's
16-18-year-olds who are employed but not currently working towards the
achievement of a recognised Vocational Qualification are eligible, provided an
appropriate VQ is available.
All sewn up:  Andrina Bisset, of Claremont Garments, and Joanne Adams show the
programme is tuned to employers' needs
</TEXT>
