<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>On a structured path  to lifelong learning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN today's rapidly changing world it has become increasingly important to train
people and provide them with the skills to enable them to compete and perform
at the highest level.
Both the CBI report Towards a Skills Revolution and the TUC report Skills 2000
advocated the introduction of credits for young people and led to the launch of
the Government Training Credits initiative in March 1990. This recruitment and
training initiative aimed to promote lifelong learning and provide a sound
basis for progression into employment.
Glasgow Skillseekers was developed from the credits initiative and offers an
alternative route to employment through training for young people aged 16-18.
The initiative is designed to use increased involvement of employers in the
training process to support the recruitment of young people as they enter the
labour market.
A key feature of Skillseekers is empowering young people by giving them the
support and spending power to purchase training relevant to their needs. The
main aim of the initiative is to enable young people to realise their full
potential through training and development which will increase the level and
volume of skills achieved.
Skillseekers also aims to maximise ``jobs with training'' opportunities through
the increased commitment of employers, while developing a more flexible and
responsive training market, reflecting the demands of both young people and
employers.
All young people are involved in action planning prior to leaving school. This
encourages them to assess their progress, be aware of opportunities, identify
career aims and set themselves targets to enable them to achieve their goals.
Before young people leave school they receive a vocational guidance interview
with a careers officer.
They are then issued with a Skillseekers Information Pack which includes their
personal card. This allows them to purchase approved training from employers,
colleges or training suppliers participating in Glasgow Skillseekers.
Once in employment, or training, the Skillseeker then agrees a training plan
with an employer or training supplier. This details the agreed route to
vocational qualifications, appropriate milestones (when particular skills,
competencies or targets are to be achieved) and any support required.
As each milestone is reached, young people use their Skillseekers Card to
authorise payment to the relative party for training they have received, as
detailed in their Individual Training Plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quality service in stationery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Andrew Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880867</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE opening of Office 1 in Glasgow brings to the city one of the first
superstores of its kind, one that is dedicated to supplying all the
requirements that are demanded of the modern office. Located at 30 Finnieston
Street, at St Vincent Street, the superstore has ample off-street parking and
is within a two-minute walk of the Exhibition Centre Station.
Under the one roof, its massive 20,000 sq ft of floorspace allows the company
to display its stock in an attractive and pleasing manner. More than 5000 items
are carried, and everything from ballpoint pens to bookcases and sharpeners to
shredders can be viewed and compared.
The first Office 1 was opened in Bristol and this was followed by three others
in England. Glasgow is the fifth superstore to be opened by the group, which is
a sister company of Ofrex, which in turn comes under the umbrella of French
company, Guilbert.
Jim Duffy is manager of the new store and he outlines the company's philosophy:
``The company guarantees to offer the lowest prices. This means that if a
customer finds something that has been purchased from Office 1 at a lower price
elsewhere, and within 14 days, we will refund the difference.''
Office 1 is certainly far removed from the generally perceived idea of an
office stationery store. Everything that is part of the office is on display.
And computers, which have been a feature of the office for many years, have a
special section. Leading makes are on display, as are a large range of
associated accessories, and all at significantly reduced prices.
The store may be viewed in four main sections: stationery, printing/copying,
office furniture and technical section. There is also a small janitorial area
within the store which offers the basic requirements of the office/kitchen.
In the breakneck speed of the modern world, when orders placed are often of an
urgent nature, required immediately, Office 1 has a service that should appeal
to the local business community.
Orders placed before 1pm that are in excess of #30 enjoy a same day delivery
provided they are within G1, G2, G3, G4, G5 postcode areas. Similarly, orders
placed with Office 1 that are in excess of #30 have free next day delivery
anywhere in Scotland.
But there is much more to Office 1, as Mr Duffy explains: ``We offer our
customers a complete printing, copying, laminating and binding service. And
where required, we can send or receive faxes. Compared with our competitors our
aim is to offer a higher level of customer service.''
Loyalty is also rewarded and customers earn points when they make purchases.
Eventually the points are converted into vouchers that can be used in leading
stores.
For the out-of-town customer who is unable to visit the store, a catalogue is
available that shows a fair percentage of what the company has to offer. One
telephone call with your order and if it is more than #30 in value, the goods
will be with you the following day and at no extra charge.
Keen to provide quality service, the company is open to suggestions from its
customers, and in place around the store are suggestion slips which may help
the management identify areas where local needs have not been fully met.
Staff have been undergoing training for three weeks, an area which store
manager Jim Duffy recognises as being vital to a smooth and efficient
operation. ``It is important that our 30 staff are conversant with the stock,
and training is very much an on-going operation. Some training has also been
carried out by suppliers such as Canon who familiarise staff with their
products.''
Office 1 seems certain to revolutionise the office supply market in Scotland,
especially when savings of up to 65% on the normal retail price can be made.
And although the store will be a boom to business, it will also be a wonderland
for the public who, when faced with what masking tape to buy, will be
confronted with six options.
Perhaps it is best left to Mr Duffy to sum up: ``Our motto is that we are first
for savings, selection and service. Visit us and I'm sure you will agree.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Let's hear it for Derek Ringer, says Ross Finlay Champions at the the double... Colin &amp; Co</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880868</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUT for the French transport strikes which caused the event to be abandoned,
two Scottish world champions would have been in Monaco to receive their
trophies and the plaudits of the international motor-sport community......
While Colin McRae is the new world champion rally driver, his Glasgow-based
team-mate Derek Ringer won the FIA World Championship for Co-drivers. The two
titles do not always go in tandem, but the McRae/ Ringer partnership, seen for
the first time on the 1986 Jim Clark Memorial Rally, has been one of the most
consistent - and most exciting - in the world during the Nineties.
Derek Ringer became involved in motor-sport purely as a hobby, as a student in
the Seventies, and then as an engineer with Ferranti. He had absolutely no
thought of making it his profession. A few years later, he teamed up with
McRae, who had already competed in the West of Scotland autotest championship
when he was too young to have a licence to drive himself to the events.
In 1987 they won their class in the British national championship, and the
following year won the Scottish championship outright, as well as taking class
wins in the British national and British open series. Their cars included a
partly works-supported Peugeot 309, a Vauxhall Nova, a Ford Sierra Cosworth,
and a Nissan 240RS. McRae was already seen as very much a ``coming man''.
The next two seasons were with Ford, rallying Sierra Cosworths in the UK as
well as in Belgium, Sweden and New Zealand. In November 1990 they were sixth on
the RAC Rally, but Ford dispensed with their services for the following year.
As a result, 1991 was fairly bleak; but then they signed for the official
Subaru team run by Prodrive of Banbury.
Looking back now, Derek Ringer appreciates how Prodrive put them through a
``well structured apprenticeship'' for the really big time. Their 1994 season
culminated in a win on the RAC Rally, and this year's repeat victory won them
the world championship - or, rather, a world championship apiece.
After the RAC Rally, Ringer headed off, without McRae, for Subaru testing in
Kenya in advance of next year's Safari Rally. Soon there will be promotional
work in England and the Far East, then testing for the Swedish, followed by
official practice for that opening round of the 1996 championship in February.
Practice sessions may involve 14 hours per day in the car.
Altogether, he is pretty busy, expecting to be away from home for perhaps 200
days this year. His suggestion that ``the further up you are in this sport, the
less you actually know what's going on'' simply confirms that self-promotion is
not a priorit y for either member of the McRae/Ringer crew.
There are nine rounds in the 1996 world championship, which is a logistical
nightmare. In order, the events are held in Sweden, Kenya, Indonesia, Greece,
Argentina, Finland, Australia, Italy, and Spain.
No RAC Rally. That is not a full-scale championship event in 1996. But Prodrive
may go for the RAC hat-trick with Colin McRae and Derek Ringer, two of that
rare breed - Scottish champions of the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>But money can't buy you the fire-breather</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANY Subaru customer who asked for an exact replica of Colin McRae's
fire-breathing RAC Rally-winning car would be pole-axed by the Ferrari-like
price demanded. Actually, there is not the remotest chance of an ordinary
customer being sold a brand new World Rally Championship car of any make.
However, the showroom Turbo 2000, best-seller of the Impreza range, is a
remarkably potent machine at #17,998 for the four-door and #18,499 for the
five-door. Subaru also offers an extra-cost ``Series McRae'' version, with
improvements to paintwork, interior equipment, wheels and tyres.
Looking out over a vast bonnet-top air intake, the driver controls an all-alloy
flat-four engine, complete with turbocharger and intercooler, which peaks at
208bhp. Turbo-charged engines should always be left to idle before being
switched off following a bout of hard driving, and the Subaru is one car which
displays a sticker advising this.
Despite the flat sounding beat of the engine, and the fact that it catches
light only as it approaches 3000rpm, the Impreza Turbo sprints to 60mph in an
astonishing 6.5 seconds. It will go on to a test track maximum over 140mph, but
the really impressive feature is the slingshot rolling acceleration.
Four-wheel drive comes as standard. The road car is quiet and biddable. It may
not be much of a looker, but it has the advantage of being, in contrast with
many high performers, a full-size four-adult saloon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ferrari comes powering back to the west</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Best-seller of the current Ferrari range: the F355 for the enthusiast who can
spare at least #88,965
q.IF keener interest in high-performance cars is one sign of a more optimistic
economic outlook, it must be good news that Ferrari has come back to the West
of Scotland. Glenvarigill in Bearsden has been appointed the franchise-holder,
as it is in Edinburgh.
Ferraris have been officially imported since 1960. There are more than 4000 on
British roads, and 275 cars are likely to have been sold in the UK once the
1995 tally is complete.
Best-seller is the 375bhp F355, with Berlinetta, Spider or GTS-style bodywork
at prices from #88,965. These striking cars - using classic 90-degree V8 power
units, complete with four overhead camshafts, five valves per cylinder and a
mid-engined location - account for two-thirds of all Ferrari sales here.
The 456 is a V12 5.4-litre front-engined two-plus-two coupe which increases the
power play to 436bhp. Ferrari has always been keen on GT as well as out-and-out
sports cars, and the lavish specification helps to explain the #156,445 price.
Ultimate expression of Ferrari's commitment to ultra-high performance is the
F50. This 4.7-litre V12 supercar peaks at 520bhp.
While its #329,000 showroom price looks stratospheric, it is worth remembering
that Ferrari is in the performance car business for the long haul. The F50 has
rivals costing up to almost twice as much, but would you put money on their
survival till the turn of the century?
You can be sure that Ferrari will plug steadily on.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What they meant to say</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Benedict Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880871</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO ASSIST readers in navigating the increasingly murky world of Westminster
politics, today's Sketch is pleased to offer, free of charge, our exclusive
guff-and-rhubarb translation service, which turns an MP's partisan question and
a Minister's predictable reply into what they really meant to say.
Mr Major is in Madrid for the Euro-summit and so left yesterday's Prime
Minister's Questions to Mr Michael Heseltine. The First Secretary of State's
current obsession is exposing Labour spin doctors, a breed he has compared to
child molesters, Nazis and Rangers football fans. (Actually he hasn't - he
merely said they were the greatest propaganda machine in British history - but
he would if he could).
Mrs Ann Taylor, deputy-deputy to Mr Tony Blair in the absence of Mr John
Prescott, took railway privatisation as her theme. She asked Mr Heseltine to
confirm privatisation will cost the public #850m a year.
An indignant Mr Heseltine said this was ``absolute rubbish'', an oft-used
Government phrase meaning ``we know, don't remind us''. The figures, published
by Labour yesterday, are drawn from Government sources.
Mr John Townend, a right-wing Tory MP, asked Mr Heseltine if the troubles of
the French were not in fact the result of their pursuit of European monetary
union. What subtitles above the Chamber would have shown was: ``the frogs are
really squirming; don't ya love it?''
First to raise events in Brixton was local Labour MP Keith Hill, who asked a
long, long question in which he outlined his sense of shock at the ``wanton
destruction and looting.''
Unrest in ethnic neighbourhoods is a tricky subject for both parties. Mr
Hill's question was, legitimately, a way of saying Labour is as resolute as the
Tories in condemning mischief.
Mr Heseltine was generous in sharing Mr Hill's condemnation and in praising
Vauxhall MP Kate Hoey (Lab.) for ``eloquently'' condeming the violence. But
there was a whiff of something else on the Tory back benches, almost an
unspeakable desire to say something that might produce a return from those
voters easily alarmed by bad news from ethnic neighbourhoods.
The moment passed and instead we turned to an increasingly popular theme for
Tory back benchers with little to do: the Union. Mr Peter Luff, Tory for
Worcester, asked Mr Heseltine to confirm that neither he nor Mr Major would
threaten the Union by introducing a Scottish parliament.
He asked; ``If you ever were tempted to such an idea, can you confirm that you
certainly wouldn't think of giving it tax-raising powers and then trying to
deceive the Scottish and British people into believing you wouldn't actually
use those powers?''
What this really meant was: ``I've just noticed that devolution seems to be a
hot issue. The whips have kindly provided me with a question to ask. Aren't I
clever?'' Mr Heseltine trotted out the usual Tory rah-rah about a tartan tax,
but it was what he wasn't saying that mattered: ``keep those questions coming,
it's the only thing we have to hurt them with''.
</TEXT>
