<HEADLINE>Two bosses who have a winning way</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROLE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Appointments</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880877</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.SCOTLAND'S first ``upward appraisal'' management award has been jointly won
by Gordon Brown of the Scottish Office Agriculture and Fisheries Department and
Peter Finnie of the National Savings Bank.
The aim of the Prime Award was to find the country's best managers - in the
opinion of their staff. Aware of the potential value of upward appraisal to
Scottish management, the leading training organisation Eglington Management
Centre agreed to sponsor the award contest, launched in September. Six hundred
applications were received and five finalists selected by the judging panel
chaired by Peter Casebow of the Royal Bank of Scotland.
The result was announced at a dinner in Edinburgh last week by Margaret Ford,
managing director of Eglington Management Centre, who said: ``The award is
important because it comes from the judges who really matter - the staff.
``The winners show that, despite all the management theory and jargon, what
counts is motivation, support and loyalty, good communication and clear
direction-management characteristics which never go out of fashion."
Brown's team of 16 in the Agricultural and Fisheries Department felt he was an
obvious choice because of the way he motivates - he is a good listener who
takes a genuine interest in them. Finnie, head of Finance and Faculties
Management at the National Savings Bank Cowglen, Glasgow is responsible for a
team of 200. His staff find him approachable and a good listener with a desire
to respond to suggestions.
They were presented with rose bowls and #15,000 of personal development and
team development training.
</TEXT>
