<HEADLINE>Keller plans to turn Claymores around</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE LIVINGSTONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880881</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Claymores found it tough going in their inaugural World League
season, with only two wins from 10 matches. But yesterday their new general
manager, former Dallas Cowboy Mike Keller, outlined his vision to bring
gridiron success to Scotland next year.
His plans include a reduction in ticket prices, an improved team and coaching
staff, a move to involve the west coast, and a visit from National Football
League commissioner Paul Tagliabue early next year.
Keller, general manager of Sacramento Surge when they won the World Bowl in
1992, took over the Claymores after Sandy Waters returned to the USA during the
summer. Keller, who has a dynamic approach to marketing, said: ``We are putting
together a blueprint for success. I can't guarantee the World Bowl, but we'll
be in much better shape to challenge for the championship than last year. I can
promise a better job will be done.''
Ticket prices for unreserved seats are down from #20 and #15 to #10, and Keller
expects to see 15,000 fans at each home game.
He also announced a deal with Glasgow's Central Hotel being used as a base for
players and coaches, who will train at Stepps playing fields next term.
Keller hopes to give the Claymores a higher profile in the west but he added
that the team's offices would remain in Edinburgh, with the addition of a
merchandise and ticket sales shop, which will open in George Street on January
15.
STEVE LIVINGSTONE
</TEXT>
