<HEADLINE>Big demand in Pantoland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCIS SHENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Appointments</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880884</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Pantoland employment statistics show it has been a very good year for
Cinderellas, with a corresponding increase in demand for qualified Buttons and
Ugly Sisters, writes FRANCIS SHENNAN. They have been recruited for Aberdeen's
Arts Centre, Ayr's Gaiety Theatre, Dundee's Repertory Theatre, Edinburgh's
King's Theatre, and Perth Theatre.
There is also strong demand for Babes in the Wood, sometimes with a related
recruitment drive for Robin Hoods. The Babes' jobs boost has come from the
King's Theatre, Glasgow, Magnum Theatre, Irvine, the Arts Centre, Paisley, and
the Civic Theatre, Motherwell, where additional language skills may be needed
to judge from the title Weans in the Wood.
There are some employment prospects still for Sleeping Beauties, along with
wicked witches and charming princes, most notably in the Adam Smith Theatre,
Kirkcaldy, Palace Theatre, Kilmarnock, and Brunton Hall, Musselburgh.
Central Scotland remains an unemployment blackspot for Jacks, cows and giants,
with only the Eden Court Theatre, Inverness, recruiting them this year. Dick
Whittingtons and cats are having a bad year of it outside the Arts Guild,
Greenock. Snow Queens and Pinocchios, too, are in low demand outside of
Stirling's MacRobert Arts Centre (in the case of the former) and the Citizens'
Theatre, Glasgow (the latter).
In fact, if you have reached December 15 without any offers from Pantoland,
it's probably time to start trying for a summer season somewhere.
</TEXT>
