<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stewart triggers young Scot's new driving ambition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORSPORT:
IF you heed omens, then a most significant one was there to be observed
yesterday, when Scottish driver Ewan Fraser took to the Donington Park track.
The 24-year-old Edinburgh man's mentor is Jackie Stewart, and like the former
Formula One champion, Fraser has arrived behind the wheel after first making a
sporting impact with his finger on the trigger of a gun.
Like Stewart before him, Fraser was Scottish national trap shooting champion in
1991 and competed internationally.
Stewart, who began shooting at 14, won the Cup de Nations in 1959 and '60 and
was reserve for the Rome Olympics that year. He did not make his first
breakthrough as a driver until three years later.
Stewart had no thoughts of projecting Fraser into the world of motor sport when
he hired him as an instructor for his Gleneagles shooting school. But Fraser,
who had worked for his father as a garage mechanic and had maintained rally
cars for customers, soon became infused with Stewart's enthusiasm.
Last year, Fraser won the Vauxhall Young Driver of the Year competition, and
yesterday he took out a Formula Vauxhall machine for the first time, with
Stewart advising him. ``Many of the factors in shooting - co-ordination, speed
of reaction, the ability to maintain concentration - are common to the two
sports,'' said three-times world grand prix champion Stewart.
For him, shooting was much more than just the first step on the sporting
highway. Dismissed academically because of what was later to be diagnosed as
dyslexia, Stewart left school early to man the pumps at the family garage in
Dumbarton.
``In shooting I was provided with something at which I could excel,'' said
Stewart, who went on to win the UK, Scottish, Irish, Welsh and English trap
titles.
``Those years were important for the formation of my thinking processes in
dealing with competition, with success and with failure. It provided the
foundation for a beginning in motor racing.''
Stewart was 24 when he made his driving breakthrough, in 1963, joining Ecurie
Ecosse. More than three decades on, Fraser, also aged 24, has turned the clock
back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When Bill felt moved to join the Elite club</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLIN Chapman's original Lotus Elite, which went on the market in 1958,
combined very attractive lines with brilliant handling and remarkably good
performance from a Coventry-Climax engine of only 1216cc. Lotus built fewer
than 1100 examples, and something like 650 are still on the road.
Ian Scott Watson was an early customer, and it was one of his Elites which gave
Jim Clark his first-ever Lotus drive at Brands Hatch. Clark also raced an Elite
at Le Mans, where Lotus outpaced the 1300cc opposition six years in succession,
as well as winning his class in home-ground events at Bo'ness, Winfield, and
Charterhall.
One of Club Elite's Scottish members is Bill Hope, who has owned a 1960 example
for the last 13 years. He has records of the eight previous owners. Somewhere
along the line it may have done some racing, because at one time it was fitted
with twin Weber carburetters and a high-lift camshaft, although now it runs on
twin SUs.
Bill Hope saw his first Elite years ago, in a garage in Fife, and thought it
was ``absolutely marvellous''. Now that he drives one of his own, he
understands its reputation as a racing car for the road.
The light construction, with glassfibre body, means that there is a healthy
power-to-weight ratio despite the engine's modest size. With the high-lift cam,
the power comes in about 4000rpm - ``and it really rips after that''. But the
great attraction of the Elite is its handling, always a Lotus speciality.
Bill Hope's car is still the subject of an on-going restoration which has been
under way since 1982. The engine has needed liners and big-end bearings, but
little else in the way of replacements. He tackled the bodywork by spending a
couple of hours every night for two weeks, stripping down the glassfibre with a
one-inch chisel. Now the finish is excellent.
This is a car seen at events in many parts of Scotland. During the past year it
has taken part in rallies at Biggar, Stonehaven, Forres, Leven, Dalmeny House,
and elsewhere.
Until now it has been off the road in winter, but with the recent Budget
dispensation abolishing road tax for cars more than 25 years old, it may be out
and about in all weathers.
Focus on the Lotus that's
`a racing car for the road'
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>West Indies aim to revive fortunes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE West Indies go into today's opening match of a one-day tournament against
Sri Lanka and Australia diverted by the turmoil surrounding star batsman Brian
Lara and beset by poor form.
Lara dropped out of the Australian tour after being fined for misconduct during
this year's England Test series, and the West Indies face the Sri Lankans in
Adelaide after Tuesday's humiliating one-day defeat by Australia's Cricket
Academy, who routed them for 92.
Australia, who begin their defence of the World Series title against West
Indies in Adelaide on Sunday, have dropped 34-year-old batsman David Boon for
their first three fixtures. The gritty right-hander is likely to be replaced by
Michael Bevan.
Meanwhile Boon made a confident start for Tasmania on the second day of their
Sheffield Shield match in Melbourne yesterday.
After Dean Jones had declared the Victoria innings on 430 for six, Tasmania
were 171 for one, with opener Jamie Cox not out on 75 and Boon on 23. Opener
Dene Hills made 54 in a stand of 124.
OTHER CRICKET
</TEXT>
