<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Oh, yes they are</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Francis Shennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Appointments</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880890</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Who are
what? you
ask. The
pantomime
producers
are major
employers
of talent
at this
time of
year, says
Francis
Shennan
SETTLE down now, boys and girls, because this week we are going to talk about
pantomimes which are major employers of talent at this time of year. It's hard
to imagine such occasions of broad-humoured slapstick as serious business-but
they are, aren't they, boys and girls?
The box-office returns from British pantomimes are more than #10m, with the
biggest shows taking more than #1m each. Much of this will pay wages which can
range from #10,000 a week for top-line celebrities to #250 a week for a dancer.
A typical production will travel around different cities for seven years. By
the time different casts have been assembled, though, and new headline stars
booked, the shows manage to appear fresh and new...... but not too new. Even
so, the production cost for a new panto is around #350,000, with the music
score alone costing perhaps #5,000.
Audiences want all the traditional ingredients, in the same way that they do
not like their traditional Christmas dinner to be tampered with, although
certain liberties are tolerated.
Comedy stars Cannon and Ball are teaming up with Scottish veteran Jimmy Logan
for The Adventures of Robin Hood and the Babes in the Wood at the King's
Theatre in Glasgow. It is a traditional combining of storylines which were once
completely separate.
The storylines and the jokes will certainly be recycled, but they are always
dusted down and given a fresh coat of glitter. Recent news stories will be
quarried to give a topical flavour. What are the odds on Princess Diana's
Panorama interview cropping up?
For all that, it takes a year to plan a top panto and for a few people it is an
all-year-round business. On one industrial estate in Lincolnshire eight
carpenters are employed full-time building sets, and five seamstresses work all
year to stitch 15,000 costumes.
Despite the continuing popularity of panto it took the sponsorship business a
while to get in on the act - at least in modern times (in fact the first car to
appear on stage was as Cinderella's coach at Drury Lane in 1895, when it was
one of only 15 cars in Britain).
Cadbury's was the first major company to understand the potential for
nationwide sponsorship. Last year its panto sponsorship around the country
involved providing 250,000 chocolate bars for the dames to throw into the
audience.
This year the Scottish confectionery company Lee's, along with Clyde 2, is
sponsoring Aladdin at Glasgow's Pavilion which stars The Krankies. Forth FM is
sponsoring Cinderella at the King's in Edinburgh, which stars Jonathan Watson
as The Baron.
Even more conventional theatre companies offer seasonal fare. The Royal Lyceum
Theatre Company is presenting Merlin the Magnificent. Scottish Ballet's
seasonal production this year is Peter Pan, and next month Northern Ballet
brings A Christmas Carol to Edinburgh's Festival Theatre.
The reason, of course, is that the Christmas season is a prime market. Income
generated now will help to finance productions during the rest of the year. The
value of theatre and the performing arts to employment tends to be dismissed.
However, Glasgow City Council's Department of Performing Arts and Venues
recently published the Cultural Statistics Framework which attempted to
quantify this value. It reported annual attendances of 1.3m for the performing
arts, and that excluded popular music events.
The cultural sector as a whole employs 9000 directly and probably as many again
indirectly.
The total annual value of the sector in Glasgow alone was put at #420m and, as
a percentage of employment in the economy as a whole, was put at between 2.7%
and 2.9% for 1993. The Christmas panto season is a boom time for jobs. And for
theatrical agents it is a dream period with any name that has any celebrity
attaching to it being crammed into the cast list. The Pavilion's Aladdin has
Linda Nolan, formerly of the Nolan Sisters, in the title role, Mike Hayward who
plays Allun Morgan in Scottish Television's Take The High Road as Abanazer, and
Eunice Huthart.
And who? She is billed as the People's Champion from the Saturday evening TV
contest Gladiators, which apparently qualifies her to play the Genie of the
Ring.
Panto has disproved Andy Warhol's assertion that ``one day everyone will be
famous for 15 minutes''. At Christmas in Britain, you can be famous for seven
weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Christie hopes to lose his plaster</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAMPIONS Menzieshill may be without captain Johnny Christie for the final
phase of the men's indoor championship tomorrow at the Bell's Sports Centre,
Perth. The internationalist has a broken right hand and could miss the club's
remaining five matches.
Christie's prospects will depend largely on his powers of persuasion when he
reports to hospital today, hoping that the plaster will be removed.
Menzieshill's problems could boost arch-rivals MIM, who lost 5-1 when they last
met, with Christie scoring four.
Examinations rule Richard Forsyth out of Indespension Western's first two
games, while Touche Ross Gordonians' captain Richard Freeland is still
recovering after having been knocked down last weekend.
q.ANDREW Scoular, coach to the Scottish women's indoor squad, has lost another
key player, Gill Messenger, for the finals of the European Nations Cup at
Glasgow's Kelvin Hall from January 26 to 28.
Her withdrawal, because of mental and physical exhaustion, comes on the heels
of Great Britain star Pauline Robertson, who wants to concentrate on the
Atlanta Olympics.
The absence of this pair will damage Scotland's prospects of a medal, and so
the team's visit to Vienna for the Arminen tournament from January 5 to 7 will
become even more significant in Scoular's build-up plans for the Kelvin Hall.
Messenger, meanwhile, will play for Edinburgh Ladies in their league match
tomorrow at Perth against Clydesdale.
JOSEPH DILLON
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Paceman shines before the gloom sets in  Martin strikes to send South Africa reeling</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880893</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Martin made a sparkling return to Test cricket in Durban before bad
weather took just a little of the shine off England's day at Kingsmead.
Lancashire fast bowler Martin grabbed three wickets to leave South Africa
reeling on 89 for five.
But then a stubborn stand of 50 between Jonty Rhodes and Brian McMillan -
followed by bad light - prevented England from strengthening their position
still further.
When play was interrupted 10 minutes after tea, the home side had steadied to
reach 139 for five. But that scoreline still represented a real triumph for the
tourists - and Martin especially.
He shared the early third Test honours with another comeback bowler - spinner
Richard Illingworth - after England had put out an attack barely recognisable
from that fielded in Johannesburg a fortnight ago.
Martin, whose last Test appearance came midway through the summer series
against West Indies, began badly yesterday morning when 17 runs were taken off
his first two overs.
But he responded admirably to dismiss Gary Kirsten (8), Daryll Cullinan (10),
and debut-maker Jacques Kallis (1) as South Africa wasted a solid 54-run
opening stand.
With Angus Fraser and Devon Malcolm both omitted and hamstring injury victim
Darren Gough on the sidelines, England retained only Dominic Cork from their
second Test bowling line-up.
For 78 minutes, there was little reason to suggest the policy might work.
Neither Cork nor Mark Ilott - back on international duty after a 28-month
absence - could shift South Africa's opening pair with the new ball as Andrew
Hudson threatened to put together a substantial score on a good-looking batting
pitch.
When Martin replaced Ilott, Hudson crashed his fourth, fifth, sixth, and
seventh deliveries through the covers. Two expensive overs from the big
Lancashire paceman left captain Mike Atherton no option but to remove his
county colleague from the attack.
Illingworth, however, provided the control England needed - beginning a superb
22-over spell spanning almost three hours which deserved even better figures
than the two for 33 he walked away with.
It was Martin, though, who produced the breakthrough which Atherton desperately
needed when brought back at the other end.
Kirsten, having contributed just eight to the half-century stand, tried to cut
a ball too close to him during Martin's second over back - and succeeded only
in edging a shoulder-high chance which Graeme Hick made look comfortable at
second slip.
Eight deliveries later, Illingworth's economy was rewarded as Hudson, whose 45
included nine boundaries, thrust forward a pad which the ball obligingly ran
up, brushed a glove, and landed gently in John Crawley's hands at silly point.
From 54 for nought, South Africa were wobbling at 56 for two, and 17 runs later
- with lunch only 10 minutes away - home skipper Hansie Cronje (8) rashly moved
down the pitch at Illingworth, dragging his attempted straight drive to Martin
at mid-on.
England refused to let their advantage slip after the interval. Illingworth,
who conceded just 13 runs from his first 14 overs, tied up one end while Martin
took advantage at the other.
Cullinan, bogged down, launched himself at a loose delivery, failed to get on
top of the shot, and drilled his cover drive into Robin Smith's hands.
Just nine deliveries later, 20-year-old Kallis pushed fatally at a ball that
left him just enough to clip the outside edge on its way through to Russell.
Rhodes and McMillan dug in before heavy rain, accompanied by thunder and
lightning, ended any hope of play resuming.
q.SHAUN Udal is ready to take out all his frustration on Pakistan A in the
three-match one-day international series, starting in Peshawar today.
The 26-year-old Hampshire off-spinner, still a World Cup contender according to
England's selectors, has endured a tough seven weeks in Pakistan.
He has played in just three of England A's first-class matches, taking only
three wickets in 66 overs, and for the past month has been counting down the
days before he sees for the first time the baby daughter born during the first
Test at Multan.
But Udal has played in all of England's past 12 limited-overs internationals -
a run that stretches back 18 months.
He said: ``I seem to be regarded more as a one-day player at the moment with
England - it was the same last winter when I was on the senior tour in
Australia.
``It has been disappointing not to have had much of an opportunity so far on
this tour, but I must knuckle down now and prove my worth in these one-day
games.
``I am hoping that I am still in with a shout for the World Cup - I am sure
Richard Illingworth is going to be one of the specialist spinners selected but
in 1987, when the World Cup was last held in India and Pakistan, England played
two spinners in every match.''
England A team manager John Emburey said: ``It's important that, having won the
Test series, we keep going and all the lads are determined to maintain our
unbeaten tour record.''
