<HEADLINE>Santa's gift for charming children</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joan Grady</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>training and development </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU better not shout, you better not cry...... this week we fly through the
working day of the most famous festive figure of all - Father Christmas himself.
The big chap in the red suit took time out of his hectic schedule to grant an
exclusive interview to one of his longest admirers. Despite a heavy workload,
he remains (of course) jolly and cheerful about his work.
``I thoroughly enjoy it,'' he said. ``The kids are great and it's lovely to see
their faces light up when they come in to the grotto.'' The grotto in question
is at Parkhead Forge and at present it's pulling in almost 400 children (and
adults) every day.
The day of our visit, being a weekday, began at 9.30am. More than 100 happy
children from local nurseries were having their Christmas outing to Santa's
beautifully presented grotto. The children were no problem, patiently waiting
their turn at the gates. The adults, on the other hand, were getting a bit
over-excited. One wonders for whose benefit it is all arranged.
My suspicions were confirmed when I spoke to Santa's helper, Sarah Jane
Morrison. Adults can be as keen to see Santa as their offspring are. In fact,
those without offspring to use as an excuse have been known to visit the grotto
by themselves. ``We get high school pupils coming in, adults on their own, all
to see Santa,'' said Sarah Jane.
``The kids are brilliant, no problem at all. Usually they wait their turn and
watch the displays, but sometimes parents get them so excited by the time they
actually meet Santa they get a bit of a fright. If they're left alone to talk
to the other children they're usually quite happy.''
Two-year-old Shannon was visiting with her childminder, Geraldine Bracelin.
``She's a bit shy,'' said Geraldine. ``I'm not sure how she'll react.''
While waiting in the queue, Shannon got over her shyness enough to tell me what
she wanted for Christmas. ``I've been very good all year,'' she said, perhaps
not surprisingly, ``and I want a Barbie doll and a Barbie car to drive her
in.'' No problem, all we've got to do is get Santa out here and...... oh, dear.
Shannon's shyness made a sudden comeback when the Big Man himself tried to give
her a Christmas cuddle. Just one of the many awkward situations a public figure
has to deal with on a daily basis.
Eventually, by dint of much coaxing and, frankly, bribery from Geraldine,
Shannon recovered enough to enter the grotto. She emerged a few minutes later,
clutching her present. ``Was that fun?'' I asked. Such a small child should not
have been able to deliver such an old-fashioned look.
Santa told me he rarely has problems with timid kiddies. Quite the reverse, in
fact. ``A much bigger problem is the kids who come in, jump into my lap and
then refuse to leave,'' he said. ``They get upset when they're told they have
to let the next visitor in.''
Usually the children are simply coaxed into leaving with a present and a big
kiss from Santa - well, it worked for me.
By 10.30am the queue was continuing to grow, and Sarah Jane told us that often
they have to turn people away. ``At the weekends people are usually still
queuing at 6pm,'' she said. ``We have to close the centre then, so a lot of
children are disappointed, but we're open right up until Christmas so there's
still plenty of time to meet him.''
How does he cope? He needs the patience of a saint - which of course he has -
but it does take a toll on his social life. Not much time for relaxing in the
evening.
Mums and dads all over the world know that Father Christmas is partial to a
drop of sherry, and the Parkhead grotto informed me that it is normally his
wont of a Saturday evening to pop down the local for a few of the same.
Not during the Christmas season, however. ``He doesn't like to go out on a
Saturday night now,'' said my informant. ``Partly because he needs a good
night's rest, but mostly because if he went out the kids could smell `sherry'
from his breath in the morning.'' Doesn't he ever get bored? ``I've been doing
this for a long time now,'' said he. ``No, I don't get bored, the children are
very entertaining. Each one has a different question and a different outlook.
It's just a lot of fun.''
Joan Grady meets the big man with the jolly challenging job
</TEXT>
