<HEADLINE>Sheppard is keen to see the benefit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880895</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH many leading Scots lured south to the Uncle Ben's Winter Challenge in
Sheffield, national squad members Alison Sheppard, Pauline McLean, back-stroker
Richard Hope, and butterfly specialist Cameron Black aim to prove that next
year's Olympic Games can be more than a dream when they line up in today's
Scottish Winter Championships at Ayr.
Sheppard, already a veteran of two Games at the age of 23, has entered six
events, and is eager to prove the advantage of her winter trip to Canada, where
six weeks' training in Calgary fuelled her enthusiasm for the final countdown
to the Olympic trials in March.
``I'm certain it was a huge benefit, and the highlight was finishing second in
the 50 metres free-style at the Canadian championships,'' she said. ``I was
also fourth in the 100m and both times were close to my best.''
McLean will be challenging Sheppard in the back-stroke and free-style.
In yesterday's heats, Graeme Smith, the European championship silver medallist,
made an unspectacular start to his defence of the 1500m free-style. He finished
third-fastest qualifier behind great rival Ian Wilson and Glen Hudson, but will
be hoping to come out on top in today's final.
Fraser Walker qualified for the final of the 50m back-stroke, fourth in
26.62sec, while Dundee's Katie Lawson made it through to the final of the 200m
free-style in sixth place.
ELSPETH BURNSIDE
