<HEADLINE>The spirit of Spain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
It might be in the Volkswagen group now, with all the quality
improvements that implies, writes Ross Finlay; but Seat's
new Toledo TDi (above) and updated Cordoba still capture . . .
SEAT brought a batch of its 1996 model year cars to Perthshire a few days ago,
featuring the new Toledo TDi and the updated Cordoba. There has been a turbo
diesel Toledo in the Spanish manufacturer's range for a while now, but the
90bhp TDi engine shares the latest VW group technology to bring in direct
injection, an intercooler and exhaust gas recirculation, so that it has
enhanced performance, economy, flexibility, and emission control.
Always a notably roomy car for both passengers and luggage, the Toledo in its
TDi guise manages exceptional economy for a bulky 1.9. On test it has returned
76mpg at 56mph, 53 at 75 and 51mpg on the urban cycle.
With a 15bhp advantage over the less sophisticated turbo diesel engine in the
range, the TDi is noticeably quicker off its mark. It will hit 60mph in 12
seconds, and offers really meaty torque from about 1900rpm onwards.
Seat has loaded the TDi with extra equipment. Costing #12,895 as the SE and
#13,795 as the SXE (which is fitted with anti-lock braking), the latest Toledo
comes with twin airbags and even air conditioning as standard.
On the road the mid-range performance is very impressive, and the TDi will pull
heartily from speeds at which some other turbo diesels are just grumbling into
action. But this is an uprated version of a saloon designed some time ago, and
in sharpness of handling, ride quality and general ``roadability'', it hardly
matches a similar car just out of the wrapping paper.
The freshened-up Cordoba demonstrates the difference. A later design, and to my
mind very under-rated in some quarters, the Cordoba is livelier to handle, more
composed on bumpy roads, and generally more of a driver's car.
It also has a neatly designed and trimmed interior, as well as a luggage volume
which is almost unbelievable if you have tried to estimate it first of all from
a glance at the rear body lines. As with all Seats, you can see immediately
what Volkswagen has contributed to the fascia and control layout.
The Cordoba is a very nippy car on country roads, with pleasant handling and a
slick throw-across gear change. There is a wide range of performance levels,
from the 1.4-litre CLS at #8795 to the two-litre GT at #12,795 - which will
sprint to 60mph in ten seconds, can go on to more than 120mph, and has brakes,
suspension fettling, wheel and tyre sizes to suit.
As part of the VW group, Seat has greatly improved its quality-control
procedures. But models like the Cordoba show that the Barcelona cars manage to
retain a Mediterranean spirit of fun on the road.
</TEXT>
