<TEXT>
HAMMY McMillan's defence of the European title is still on course after a 5-4
win over England in a tense quarter-final yesterday evening at the European
Championships in Grindelwald, Switzerland.
He hit for a single at the first end, and English skip Alistair Burns blanked
the second and third ends before being forced to take a single in the fourth
when McMillan played a freeze with his last stone.
In the fifth end England's second player, Andrew Hemmings, missed a take-out
and allowed McMillan to build up the head and score 2 with a draw to the button.
At the sixth end Scotland's third, Norman Brown, had a stone removed for a
hog-line offence and McMillan had a complete miss. England were able to score 2
and bring the game back level.
England's third player, Alan McDougall, caught a guard in the seventh end,
allowing the Scots to build the end and score 2 with a McMillan hit.
Hay made up for his earlier mistake with a spectacular triple take-out in the
tenth end, and, when Burns could not dislodge two Scottish stones nestling in
the house with his last stone, the Scots had victory.
McMillan now faces surprise semi-finalists Italy this evening, while the
Scottish women, led by Kirsty Hay, are in quarter-final action against Denmark
this morning. Men's quarter-final results:
Scotland 5, England 4; Norway 5, Sweden 4; Germany 5, Switzerland 7; France 4,
Italy 6.
