<HEADLINE>Trials storm brews</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHLETICS
BRITISH athletics, in attempting to defuse one row, yesterday almost certainly
lit the touch-paper for another, with the credibility of David Cropper, the
chairman of the international selection committee, at stake.
Athletes' representatives, fronted by former European 400m champion Roger Black
and Scotland's triple Commonwealth high jump medallist Geoff Parsons, welcomed
the announcement of major changes in the Olympic selection process. Yet a
misplaced English obsession with upholding tradition still threatens to prevent
the best British team going to Atlanta.
The plan presented by the British Athletic Federation, after consultation with,
and approval from leading athletes, will stop competitors making a mockery of
the AAA Championships, as did Linford Christie and Colin Jackson last summer.
However, a row is brewing over a refusal by the AAA of England to exclude
foreigners from their championships, which double as the Olympic trials.
The system of choosing the AAA winner - plus two others per event at the
selectors' discretion - has been axed.
Instead, the first two past the post will be guaranteed an Olympic place, with
just one discretionary choice if each has fulfilled the qualifying standard.
Competitors must perform in their intended Olympic event at the AAAs in
Birmingham from June 14-16.
This will eliminate the fiasco of this year's AAA event, the World Championship
trials, when 10 athletes failed to compete, claiming various injuries.
Others switched events. Christie failed to get through his 100 metres heat, yet
was resinstated to the final. World hurdles record-holder Jackson declined to
race his specialty, ran the 100m heats instead, qualified, but then withdrew
pleading injury. Less than 24 hours later he hurdled in Italy.
Tony Ward, the BAF spokesman, said: ``It's tough, but fair. If athletes have
injuries serious enough to keep them out of trials, they are unlikely to be fit
for the Olympics.'' But he added: ``The AAA have so far been unable to
acquiesce to the BAF's request that the championships be closed.''
In recent years this has conspired to keep leading British competitors out of
finals. In the 800m, for example, only heat winners qualify, and perhaps two
fastest losers. Several Kenyans have reached the final, denying UK men the
chance of running for their country.
It is clearly ludicrous to persist with this open policy when the objective is
to select Britain's best Olympic team.
The AAA of England, of which selector Cropper is chairman, has defended their
open championships. This posture is incompatible with selecting the best UK
team, and he surely must decide where his allegiance lies.
DOUG GILLON
</TEXT>
