<HEADLINE>Land of the supermodels</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VISITORS to Barcelona often see train-loads of Seats leaving the factory
complex at Martorell. Elsewhere, European and Japanese manufacturers have
satellite Spanish factories which turn out vehicles such as the Ford Maverick,
the Nissan Terrano and Serena.
But Barcelona has always been the heart of the Spanish motor industry, which
built some spectacular and ambitious cars before the grim era of the civil war.
La Cuadra and Castro flourished briefly around the turn of the century, and in
the Twenties Elizalde was turning out an 8.1-litre straight eight.
Hispano-Suiza, succeeding Castro, was one of the genuine prestige marques of
Europe. The company took the second part of its name from the nationality of
its great Swiss designer Mark Birkigt. In the Fifties, when the nationalised
Pegaso truck company decided to go into cars, another notable (and wildly
eccentric) personality was in charge - Wilfredo Ricart. The sports Pegasos,
built in the old Hispano-Suiza factory, were among the fastest production cars
in Europe, officially timed in Belgium at speeds approaching 150mph.
There was a touch of the Salvador Dali about Ricart. In the Thirties he had
worked with Alfa Romeo, encountering a supremely unimpressed Enzo Ferrari.
Ricart wore shoes with exaggeratedly thick rubber soles. Ferrari asked him
about this, and was solemnly told that ``a great engineer's brain should not be
jolted by the inequalities of the ground, and needs to be carefully sprung''.
</TEXT>
