<TEXT>
NOW, as you and I and all the children of the world know, there is only one
Santa, writes JOAN GRADY. However, due to      the very great demand for his
presence,     he occasionally must take on helpers. Finding the right man for
that job is no easy task.
``We do have a selection procedure to identify possible helpers,'' says Mark
Stangroom, marketing coordinator at The Forge. ``They must, of course, be jolly
and good-natured and be confident with children. It gets very hot inside that
grotto so this is not a job for someone who is likely to get impatient with the
kids.''
Training is a case of trying to give ``Santa'' the ability to handle the
unpredictable situations which crop up around children. He is encouraged to ask
them questions, to chat them about his life in Greenland, his reindeer and his
elves.
``It's an acting job, really,'' says Mr Stangroom. ``Our stand-in is John
Kirkwood, who is usually a security guard at The Forge. He's worked as a Santa
before and he has a jolly personality and an ability to interest the children.
He has children and grandchildren of his own and was the ideal candidate for
the job.''
The visit to Santa's grotto is an important part of Christmas for children but
it takes a lot of effort to keep the magic going.
``We've had a grotto every year since the centre opened eight years ago. It's
always been something of a feature and the kids love it. John has to stay very
sharp - if he's not enjoying himself it comes across to the children and that's
a major disadvantage. For four weeks of the year he needs to be very
disciplined. It's a very responsible position.''
</TEXT>
