<TEXT>
Volleyball
BALERNO High School will host a two-a-side volleyball tournament for Under-18
and Under-15 players on Sunday. A dozen teams are expected to compete in the
event, which is sponsored by TB Mackay Energy Services.
Rugby league
RUGBY all-rounder Graham Thompson leads a Scottish rugby league team into
battle for the first time ever on home soil tonight when the national students'
side face France at Meadowbank.
Thompson, who is also Gavin Hastings' understudy at Watsonians, said: ``The
sport is taking off in a big way in Scotland. The students' team can be a
direct stepping stone to the full Scotland squad - and there will also be
places up for grabs in the line-up to play in next year's Students World Cup.''
Basketball
FOR the second time in three years, Glasgow Brightsiders have had to pull out
of Scotland's top tournament, this weekend's Edinburgh 95 at Meadowbank.
Two years ago it was injuries, this time a rearranged Scottish Cup tie means
that the Glasgow club tomorrow face City of Aberdeen Leopards in a game
postponed because of a mix-up over the tip-off time.
Brightsiders men - without potential match-winner Phil Birch, who has damaged
ankle ligaments - will be hoping for better luck than their women's team, who
travelled to Aberdeen last Saturday only to return some four hours later
without playing their national league game with Leopards - who were waiting at
a different venue.
The Boroughmuir Christmas event continues on Sunday with the play-offs and
final (4pm). Boroughmuir and holders Livingston Bulls join Edzell Enforcers in
one group, while previous winners Edinburgh Burger Kings have Strathkelvin and
Paisley.
In the competitive women's tourney, capital sides Polonia Phoenix, Team
Caledonia, Beefeater Kool Kats, and Boroughmuir Aces join unbeaten Livingston
in a round-robin.
A welcome new event arrives in the West, with Troon staging an international
invitation club event for under-17 boys over the same two days. Marr College
teacher and organiser Tom Campbell has attracted teams from Ireland, Wales, and
England as well as three from Scotland.
Delta Notre Dame, who have won Irish honours at every age from under-13 to
under-22, join Flintshire from Wales, England's North Staffs and South Cheshire
Jets, and Cumnock Team Corsa, Arbroath Musketeers, and hosts Troon.
Squash
CLAIRE Waddell faces the first serious challenge of the season when she starts
the defence of the Scottish Championship at Heriot-Watt University today.
The 20-year-old Stirling University student is unbeaten and has won three
domestic grand-prix titles this season, but shares top billing this weekend
with London-based Senga Macfie, Scotland's top player at world No.21, but yet
to win the national title.
In the men's event, Martin Heath, the world No.30, has benefited from a string
of call-offs. Peter Nicol, winner of the Mahindra International Challenge in
India earlier this week, is not defending the title he has won for the past
three years, and Stuart Cowie (injury) and Alasdair Taylor (illness) have since
dropped out as second seeds.
Newlands' Barry Sutherland, who played in last month's World Championships, is
expected to reach the final but faces a stiff semi-final against former
internationalist Graeme Sword.
