<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>arena</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974880902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEXT year will continue to see the newspaper circulation battle hotting up, and
sponsors will continue to pour cash into football and, in some cases, clubs
will squander it as fast.
Newspapers and sports sponsors have at least one common denominator value for
money. Newspapers should be giving value, and sponsors should receive it. Yet
the circulation battle will be fought almost totally on a reactive basis.
If you have scratch cards then so will we. As one carries one promotion the
other will follow. Management in the newspaper industry cannot be so naive
that, in a shrinking market place, they are going for extremism and
sensationalism when the public simply looks for value for money and content.
Balanced topics from news through to sport, is that not what the public wants?
Honest, truthful reporting with interesting features.
Sport, now there's a thing. Most tabloids have pull-outs on Mondays with page
after page of football. Reactive again, one following the other. The coverage
is unbelievable. Some games attract 250 people and the space given to that game
is incredible, so much so that if you wanted to purchase that space for
advertising, it could cost you thousands.
Football, in this country, has fallen short of world standard and needs all the
hyping it can get, but what does it attract in the way of people each week?
Attendances from four leagues, 80,000 in total. Is that a fair average with
Rangers and Celtic contributing in the main to that figure? Perhaps 250,000
viewers at peak TV time on a Sunday afternoon, is this giving value for money?
Are the participants, that is the players and the clubs, aware of the
responsibilities to sponsors? I fear not.
The SFA, club chairmen, are urged by the media to clean up the game, in some
cases rightly so. But sponsors possibly hold the key to the disturbing elements
creeping onto the football pitch. They should be demanding that football clean
up its act, and that clubs and players meet their responsibilities.
In an equally competitive industry, knitwear, The Sweater Shop is probably the
most successful manufacturing retailer of its kind in the high streets of
Britain. They probably have the most up-to-date, state of the art plant in
Western Europe, if not the world, and as a result of their sponsorship
commitment to snooker, and Stephen Hendry in particular, a plant in Scotland
was opened three-and-a-half years ago and now employs more than 400 people.
Their sponsorship commitment was total, they expected nothing less in return.
They insisted that people such as Hendry, Dean Robertson, Dennis Taylor, etc,
give value for money to public and media alike, demanding that those stars
remember who and what they represent. If we let them down, there were stiff
penalties. Therefore we ensured they were never let down. Surely there is a
lesson to be learned by the two parties sharing a common denominator.
If football in this country, and newspapers, are serious about their future,
they have to source out questions which first they must ask themselves, and,
secondly, they must answer. If the product is not value for money in the case
of newspapers, advertising revenue will drop, and in the case of football,
sponsorship will decline.
Snooker suffered these problems in the late '80s and early '90s and had to
learn the hard way. It has been difficult, but learn we did, and our values and
responsibilities are now to the people who pay the piper.
In the end, with companies such as The Sweater Shop who have invested at grass
roots, our game is booming in Scotland. Through client and high-profile event
sponsorship, their profile has blossomed, and success is there for all to see.
I am proud to be Scottish, and it upsets me to see our national football team
branded second-rate. I do not believe it has to be that way.
Scots are ranked first, second, and sixth in the world at snooker; No.1 and 2
in Europe, at golf. That is because these sports have been prepared to adapt,
and give value for money to sponsors and public. In football, that is not the
case. These people are not prepared to change their comfortable, traditional
habits.
There is a warning here for football and newspapers, and they should take heed
before it is too late. Waste not, want not.
</TEXT>
