<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Farewell to Irish legend</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK Charlton is poised to announce his retirement as Republic of Ireland
manager early in the New Year, after exactly a decade in the job.
The 60-year-old Englishman recovered from Wednesday's Euro '96 play-off defeat
by Holland insisting he still has an open mind about his future. ``I honestly
don't know what I'm doing - I don't know whether to stick or twist,'' he said.
But he dropped a broad hint when he added: ``I would like to be in the job for
10 years, not nine years and 10 months, and that's the end of January.''
The Irish FA's chief executive, Sean Connolly, insisted: ``No-one is pushing
him to stay, and no-one pushing him to go. We believe it is a decision that has
to be Jack's alone.''
Charlton says he will wait and see what the reaction is in Ireland over the
next few weeks, enjoy his Christmas and then take a holiday in Spain. ``When I
come back, we will have a meeting with the FAI and sort out what's happening.''
But he clearly suspects his time has gone, reflecting on the lack of spare
parts for his worn-out squad and a modern passing game that has now by-passed
the Irish pressing style.
On the other hand, he is still moved by the passion of the Irish fans, who will
always revere him for taking them to the finals of two World Cups and the 1988
European Championship.
They stood in the Anfield cold and demanded his presence after the 2-0 defeat
ended his dream of finishing his reign on a more upbeat note on home soil next
summer. ``I was very moved by that,'' he admitted.
His side ran their hearts out against the world-class Dutch but, for the third
time in four major meetings, they were simply second best. The narrow gap of
Gelsenkirchen in '88 had become a yawning chasm.
For players like 37-year-old John Aldridge and 36-year-old Paul McGrath,
retirement certainly beckons, even though Charlton cannot see their successors.
``We've wrung as much as we can from Paul. He's been magnificent for us but
there is a limit,'' said the Ireland manager. ``But where do you find new
players, the players who might make you a good or reliable side?''
Minimum Irish requirements are a quick centre half to become Phil Babb's new
partner, a lively and genuine goalscorer and a fit Roy Keane.
</TEXT>
