<HEADLINE>Firefighter loses his foot</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880904</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FIREFIGHTER yesterday relived the moment when his foot was amputated as he
fought to put out a blaze in a grain dryer.
Leading firefighter Francis Paterson told a court he had never been trained on
how to deal with such fires.
``I have never had any special training on how to fight fires in machinery,''
the retained fire officer told Peterhead Sheriff Court yesterday.
Mr Paterson, 40, of Copeman Place, Peterhead, described how he lost his footing
as he was coming out of the dryer and his right foot was caught in the
machinery.
``I slipped downwards and my foot went into the augur,'' he said.
In the first case of its kind in Scotland, a local authority is facing charges
under health and safety legislation for an accident involving a firefighter.
On trial is Grampian Regional Council which operates Grampian Fire Brigade. The
council denies failing to provide suitable training for fighting fires in grain
dryers and not preventing Mr Paterson from entering the dryer when it was
working, as a result of which he was injured.
The accident happened on August 1, 1994, when the retained unit from Peterhead
was called to a fire at East Longhill Farm, near the Aberdeenshire town.
Earlier, Mr Paterson agreed with defence counsel Gerry Monaghan that he had
been told to isolate the source of power before fighting a fire.
``Do you accept that what you did was contrary to your training? '' asked Mr
Monaghan.
``Yes'', replied Mr Paterson.
</TEXT>
