<DOCID>GH951215-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murray's warning to those who still want change No crumbs of comfort from rich man's table</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Traynor, Chief Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880905</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WINTER finally bit into Scottish football yesterday. The signs were all there,
with club chairmen taking sides, and the game's administrators, who have the
unenviable task of trying to follow the often peculiar logic of football
people, preparing the way for what seems now to have become an annual debate.
League reconstruction is back on the agenda.
Next week the Scottish League management committee will gather, and the main
topic of discussion will be a first-division propelled move to restructure the
leagues, even though clubs had agreed to persevere with the current set-up of
four groups of 10 clubs for five years.
This system is in only its second season and already many have deemed it a
failure. Various people have their own notions, and while it might be
comforting to believe the clamour will rise from altruism, the reality remains
that the most powerful incentive for a new shape is born from financial needs.
Some clubs, like Partick Thistle, for instance, say they can survive without
playing each of the Old Firm four times a season, but there are many more
outfits who continue to regard Rangers and Celtic as meal tickets, and would
like a slice of that action.
They want a top division of 16 or 18 clubs, and even though the Old Firm were
united yesterday in opposition to the change, the smaller clubs could carry
enough votes to have their way at Thursday's management committee meeting.
Much could depend on how they handle the subject of the Coca-Cola Cup, which
would have to be altered if a 16-club top division is given life, because the
League Cup competition is one of the most exciting of its kind. Part of the
proposal for change would involve the early stages of the cup becoming
sections, a system which was lacklustre when tried before.
The Scottish League came up with a shorter, sharper competition which has been
a resounding success, and it would be a pity to dismantle the set-up to help
tempt clubs to vote for league reconstruction. If the top division becomes one
of 16, that would guarantee clubs only 15 home matches, which would hardly be
sufficient for most of them, and one way of compensating would be to ensure
additional home matches through League Cup sections.
However, if the main division was extended to accommodate 18 clubs, the cup
competition could be left unaltered, but the chances of a reconstruction
leading to an additional eight teams in the premier division are remote. The
clubs pushing for change realise they will have to go for 16 and, even then,
they will face stiff opposition.
``I don't think this kind of main division would suit the customer,'' said
Celtic chairman Fergus McCann. ``People pay for quality, not quantity. We are
not represented on the league management committee, which itself is a
regrettable situation, but we would prefer the current set-up.
``Bringing in more clubs would lead to an increase in the number of mediocre
matches, and I'd rather see us all look at other aspects of the game, such as a
split season, which would allow more football in the summer.''
Rangers chairman David Murray, who was a main force behind the ill-fated Super
League a few years ago, pointed out his club would not support change simply
for the sake of it. Before casting a vote in favour, he would need to be
convinced change would lead to a healthier product, and he does not believe
this latest proposal means a better set-up.
``There would have to be certain criteria before we would vote for change, but
as the proposal stands, we are not in favour.
``I'm not for letting other people come to the party and take the crumbs off
the rich man's table,'' he said. ``I think these people are in danger of
changing for the wrong reasons.
``We need new equity in football, and clubs need funding by someone, or a group
of people with money, and until we have that new funding, we can't go forward.''
Murray fears also that a top division of 16 would not be an encouragement to
television. ``It would become boring,'' he said.
It is thought Hibernian and Aberdeen will vote against change also, while
Partick Thistle, Raith Rovers, Kilmarnock, Hearts, Motherwell and, possibly,
Falkirk are in favour, and with those numbers as well as the bulk of clubs
below, the chances are good that a special general meeting of the Scottish
League will be called. It would be at this meeting the real voting would be
conducted, with 75% of the votes necessary to enforce change in time for the
start of next season.
This rule was written in to protect the current set-up for a five-year term,
but if the clubs wish time to ease in a new structure, and accept the status
quo should remain throughout season 1996-97, then only two thirds of the vote
will be necessary to enforce change for the following season.
Premier division clubs each have four votes, two each in the first division,
and clubs in the second and third divisions each have only one, although it
should be remembered the two new clubs, Caley Thistle and Ross County, are
still associate members and do not have votes.
Dundee United's chairman, Jim McLean, argues that change now could be crucial
to the development of the game, stressing there are too many negative aspects
attached to a small top division of 10 clubs.
``We have all had time to look at the set-up and as far as I'm concerned, young
players are not being brought through, games are not attractive enough, and the
financial implications can be severe to some,'' he said.
``There is too much pressure on people and, while we should never try to take
the competitiveness out of our game, I have to say that if I were a player with
any ability, Scotland and England are the last places I'd want to bring my
talents.
``I can honestly say that Dundee United are not important in this. The product
is what matters most, and that product is questionable. We are playing
desperate football.''
There are no guarantees that a change will lead to better football, only
properly co-ordinated youth development work will do that.
Many argue four divisions of 10 prevents the use of young players, while others
ask for proof that three divisions of 16, 12, and 12 would be a more suitable
world.
It would be comforting to believe votes will be cast with the wellbeing of the
entire game in mind, rather than individual needs. Supporters would be wise to
proceed with a healthy degree of scepticism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
