<HEADLINE>A starter for 80 from Daly</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From RAYMOND JACOBS at Montego Bay, Jamaica</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH Australian Wayne Riley deservedly took a three stroke lead with his
first round score of 66, five under par, in the Johnnie Walker World
Championship in Jamaica yesterday John Daly, who won the Open Championship at
St Andrews in July, the week after Riley's victory in the Scottish Open at
Carnoustie, also commanded attention, but for very different reasons.
Daly, as always predictably unpredictable, had a score of 80 over the 6760-yard
Tryall course. Having arrived too late even for one practice round, he incurred
five penalty strokes, three from drives hit out of bounds, and two from
unplayable lies. The former US PGA champion played the first 11 holes in 11
over par and covered the last seven in two under.
Yet Daly, at the end of a day characterised by 90F heat and high humidity, as
well as a swirling Caribbean breaze, did not occupy the last of the 20 places.
That dubious distinction belonged to the Swede, Anders Forsbrand. who, having
match Daly's 43 to the turn, forged steadily backwards to be home in 40 for a
three-stroke ``lead.''
Daly's mishaps echoed those when he played in the first championship four years
ago. Then he was disqualified after having signed an incorrect card for a score
of 86, 36-50 each way.
There was controversy then when Daly was given the same prize money as was
earned by the professional occupying last place, having played all 72 holes.
Now to collect the $57,000 pittance twentieth place carries, the player must
have completed all four rounds, unless the committee decrees otherwise.
Meanwhile, at the sharp end, so to speak, Riley, aged 33, and whose victory in
the Scottish championship was his first in Europe and was one of eight last
season achieved by five players using a long-handed putter, chipped in from
30ft at the first and subsequently showed admirable control in adding five more
birdies and conceding only one stroke to par.
Remarkably, given Riley's command of awkward rather than exacting conditions,
only three other players broke par - the Fijian Vijay Singh, on 69, Riley's
partner, Loren Roberts and Fred Couples, another American Ryder Cup player on
70. Bernhard Langer led the European challenge on level par.
As is often the case in this season-ending event, some of the scoring gave
every evidence of player burn-out. When so much prize money is available to
professionals already gorged with riches it is not difficult to understand that
loss of interest and purpose can set in if matters begin to go wrong.
Thus the holder, Ernie Els, who began with two 64s last year, took 15 strokes
more and Colin Montgomerie and Sam Torrance, first and second on the 1995
European Order of Merit, had scores of 75 and 77 respectively. Nick Faldo,
watched by his new inamorata, lent respectability to his score of 74 with two
late birdies.
66 - W Riley (Aus).
69 - V Singh (Fiji).
70 - L Roberts (US), F Couples (US).
71 - B Langer (Ger).
72 - D Duval (US), P Mickelson (US), M Calcavecchia (US).
73 - A Cejka (Ger).
74 - N Faldo (GB).
75 - P Azinger (US), B Mayfair (US), L Janzen (US), C Montgomerie (GB).
77 - P Senior (Aus), S Torrance (GB).
79 - E Els (SA).
80 - J Daly (US), T Izawa (Jap).
83 - A Forsbrand (Swe).
</TEXT>
