<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coming in from the cold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Julia Langdon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880908</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I'm glad to say work and friends have been a great consolation
to me
-- DAVID JASON
This year David Jason had to cope with the tragic death of his long-time
partner, Myfanwy Talog. But now he is ready to return in a new series of A
Touch of Frost. Julia Langdon sees the actor step back into the frame
DAVID Jason does not give interviews. David Jason does not like meeting the
press and, indeed, it seems he tries to avoid being in the same building as a
journalist if at all possible. So the fact that he has at least turned up for
the press launch and screening of his new television series is a great relief
to a large bunch of harrassed-looking media executives.
And there he is: sitting in a corner of the reception, hemmed in by a gaggle of
showbiz writers and looking hideously ill at ease. He is almost literally
squirming with discomfort and it is not merely because his suit, with its very
expensive sheen, is just a little too tight.
There is something oddly disconcerting about spending two hours in a cinema
watching an actor play a chirpy Yorkshire copper who fearlessly takes on
homicidal maniacs, and then emerge to find the man himself is disconcerted by a
bunch of journos. (Although I myself jumped when I found I was standing beside
the actor who played the aforementioned maniac. ``Ugh, you!'' I said,
involuntarily).
Unreasonably, we expect actors to relate to the character with whom we identify
them, and here is poor David Jason who may be a superb actor, but cannot
disguise himself, cannot hide his own feelings, when talking about himself. It
reminded me of an occasion when I did a television programme with a famous
journalist war photographer who had spent most of the previous five years
dodging death in Beirut, and here he was sitting in the safety of a studio in
Manchester shaking with nerves at the prospect of appearing on screen.
In fact, of course, David Jason is not actually talking about himself to start
with but is, rather, talking about his character, Detective Inspector Frost,
who returns in a five-part series in January. Could he possibly be hiding?
Almost certainly.
He is smaller than you expect, balder, too, and quite tubby when he is sitting
down. The word dapper seems to apply, certainly in contrast to the the rather
rough-hewn appearance of Frost. He rattles on about how much he feels the
character of Frost has developed - echoing the press release which we all
already have in our hands - and how pleased he is with it, and with the
script-writers, and then there suddenly comes an echo of his own personal
misery and why he is radiating all this unhappiness.
The press release tells it in words that Jason himself does not, cannot, use.
``He has moved away from the sadness of his wife dying and all that heartache
and adapted more to the normal self,'' it says of Frost. And, of course, what
has happened to Jason is a ghastly mirror image of that: with the tragic death
from cancer of his own long-time partner, Myfanwy Talog, in March this year.
It is this which hangs unsaid in the air as we all struggle to try to reach the
real David Jason. There is another four-part series of A Touch of Frost being
filmed between February and August. It is very hard work and particularly
trying for Jason because he is in practically every scene. He ends up doing 12
to 14-hour days, five days a week, and has to spend every evening swotting up
the scripts. Each episode takes five weeks to film and it is all totally
concentrated effort.
``One doesn't grizzle too much at the time,'' he says, ``but after a year your
brain starts to get a bit sponge-like.''
He is uncertain about whether there will be a further series after this year.
He won't say ``never'', but his future is clearly very undecided. He is
uncertain about much which lies ahead. He has had a punishing schedule in the
last decade: four years of doing Frost, four years before that of The Darling
Buds of May. He is quite obviously fed up with being committed for a year at a
time, ``being processed'' as he calls it, and thus unable to do anything else.
His agent doesn't even tell him about half the things he's offered, he says;
there's no point, he can't do them. He couldn't do a major part in a movie; he
couldn't do a play at the National or the RSC; there was an Alan Ayckbourn he
was quite interested in - but, no, he couldn't do that, either.
What about another crack at Only Fools and Horses? ``What, on crutches, you
mean?'' he says. He sniffs. It seems to be a nervous sniff: he does it to
emphasise his jokes, to show that he is not really uncomfortable. He fiddles
with his tie. ``You have to wonder whether you can go back,'' he observes.
Someone asks if he means he might be getting on a bit for the part. ``Yeah,''
he says, ``but I'm always open to bribery, as Del-boy would say.''
This year he has found time to do a pilot for a proposed series about diving -
its working title is Around the World in 80 Dives - and he enjoyed looking for
the best diving site in the world, in the Virgin Islands and the Caribbean. He
does not, quite clearly, like any intrusion into his privacy and he volunteers
how much he appreciated going unrecognised.
``Basically the Americans don't know who you are and they don't want to have
photographs taken with their kids and their snotty-nosed dogs. It's quite
refreshing to be able to get away and not be hassled.''
A little later, when someone asks him about taking time off, he says he will be
spending some time working on his house, and then immediately erects the
barricade.
``With my guard dogs!'' he says, ``And my guns! I'm repairing the electric
fences at the moment.'' Everyone laughs, nervously.
He has a nervous laugh, too; a short little sharp bark which does not convey
much humour. He does it now when someone broaches the unmentionable, murmurs
that he has had a difficult year and asks if he has thrown himself into work in
consequence. There's a moment's silence and the questioner, attempting to ease
it, suggests that Jason might be thinking: ``I'm getting older.'' Jason
replies: ``Oh, are you?'', trying to break the tension.
He concedes there is some truth in that, but part of his cover includes
throwing questions back at his interrogators. It is, interestingly, a trick
Margaret Thatcher used to employ when she was put on the spot. ``What would you
do?'' she would ask.
Jason does it to me when I ask if he is anxious about not taking too many parts
that are vehicles for him, the star, carrying the rest of the cast. ``I beg
your pardon,'' he says, pretending to mishear, and trying rather too hard for a
laugh, ``Is it a contraceptive?'' But he has heard perfectly well because he
then answers seriously, acknowledging it is a factor, that he doesn't want to
take anything on just to keep working.
That might have been true in the past because of the classic actor's
insecurity, the deep-rooted fear that one will never work again, but maybe now
he might slow down a bit. This is a recurring theme. At one point he puts on a
silly voice of an old codger: ``Maybe now is the time that I ought to take it
easy,'' he warbles, ``because I'm getting older and need the crutches to get
about on.''
He wouldn't mind a bit more free time if only he could afford it. He addresses
this over our heads to the executive producers and denies the apparently
published suggestion that he gets #100,000 for an episode of A Touch of Frost.
``A bloody joke,'' he says.
``You're better scriptwriters than some of my blokes.'' Not true then?
``Christ, I wish it was.'' But it has been rewarding, he acknowledges.
And then, at last, someone asks how he is coping. ``It's been very, very
difficult and I'm glad to say that work and the friends I've had at Yorkshire
TV have been a great help and a great consolation for me. I don't really want
to go into great detail . . . '' he hurrumphs. ``I've had nicer years, let's
put it like that. Working so hard - well, one just had to do it; the amount of
energy and concentration needed, you know, eased the burden, as it were.''
There's another cough and a sniff and an ironic ``huh!'', and someone asks
about Christmas. ``I've always hated Christmas, anyway,'' he says miserably,
and makes some fairly banal observations about commercialism.
He endures it for a few more minutes and then a public relations person finally
rescues him. One misery, at least, is over for the time being.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
