<DOCID>GH951215-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mathis pours pity on Tyson on eve of battle of giants</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BOXING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880909</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIKE Tyson is primed to seriously invest in the hurt business in Philadelphia
tomorrow, but the recipient of his formidable power game is the one
entertaining the sympathic thoughts.
``I feel sorry for the guy,'' confessed Buster Mathis Jr. ``I believe Tyson is
insecure about boxing after being off for a long time. There is pressure in his
life.
``All that money, all that fame, all that recognition, and to me he doesn't
seem happy.
``I don't envy Mike money. To me it's a curse as well as a blessing. Money and
fame can destroy a man. If I was earning $50-60m a fight, I couldn't change.
I'd be wearing the same clothes as I do now.''
Mathis Jr has a different philosophy, influenced by his father. Mathis Sen was
a top-class boxer in his day, fighting Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier in the
golden heavyweight era, but died in September soon after the Tyson fight had
been signed.
``He knew the politics of the game. He couldn't read or write, but he was good
at reading people,'' added Mathis, who will not be embarrassed by a career-best
pay day of $565,000, about a tenth of Tyson's purse.
``I invest my money, I don't have a car, don't buy fancy clothes, and there's
no lady in my life. I live at home with my mom. I'm a mommy's boy, big time.
Tyson has found an opponent with the steely thread of dedication in the
unbeaten 25-year-old heavyweight, Mathis Jr, for his second comeback fight.
``I often feel when I walk into the ring that I've got to fight for my life,''
admitted Mathis.
``But some fighters perform better when they are frightened. My father used to
say: `fear is my friend'.''
Mathis comes from a religious family. His mother is a Jehovah's Witness. Mathis
senior studied the persuasion and Mathis junior learned about it while growing
up.
``I'm not a dedicated Witness. But I believe I control my own destiny,'' added
Mathis.
Mathis, already a BSc in Computer Engineering, used his time well between the
postponement on November 4 and his return to training, and passed a Real Estate
crash course.
He also took time to study the tape of Tyson's 89-second fiasco against Peter
McNeeley in August.
``It's taught me a lot. It seems Tyson missed with 80% of his punches. McNeeley
shoved him back.
``Tyson's nowhere near the fighter he was at 21. Now he's going on 30 and has
had a four-year lay-off.'' If Mathis pulls off the shock of the decade he could
take Tyson's place in the ring with Frank Bruno on March 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McCoist admits to be entering the last lap European glory is now the goal for top striker</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880910</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLY McCoist cast his mind back yesterday, with humour and affection, to his
boyhood as an athlete, and his first sporting success. Then, with more guarded
emotions, looked forward to the day he fears more than any other, when the
final whistle blows, and an illustrious football career has to end.
``I watched the World Cup draw - I think it is a great one for Scotland,'' said
the Rangers striker. ``But I have to be realistic. At my age, I have to admit I
am unlikely to be there.''
McCoist was speaking after having presented trophies to some of Scotland's
leading young school and club athletes, infusing and charming them with his
infectious enthusiasm at the TSB Thistle Awards ceremony in Edinburgh. He
confirmed, however, that his personal tape is in sight.
``I've set my stall out this season. The real goal is the European
Championships - to be involved in the finals, in England. I am not getting any
younger. It is not impossible that I will never play in another major
championships. But realistically, this is my last chance at the Europeans, and
it could be my international swan song.
``Not to have qualified for the finals, with them being in England, would have
been a disaster for Scots. I take great personal pride in having scored the
goal against Greece which was a major one in helping us qualify.''
He will be in London, working in a media role, this weekend when the European
draw takes place. ``We could do without getting Holland,'' he ventured. ``I
can't believe it took that play-off to see them through. All these youngsters
from Ajax, just 19, 20, and 21 - it's frightening. These kids will just get
better and better.''
McCoist is not averse to learning even at his advanced years. ``The Ajax youth
coach is coming to Ibrox on Sunday, and I will be going along to have a look.
We need a boot up the backside. Holland's a small country, like us, and their
methods seem to work. Maybe we should alter our ideas and methods a bit. That
could be the way ahead, to watch the likes of Ajax, and learn from their
coaches.''
It is not the lure of that elusive fiftieth cap, the entree to the Hall of
Fame, which is his motivation, just undiluted passion for the game. ``When you
speak to the guys who coach, the players who have finished, they say how great
it is still to be involved. But they admit it is no substitute for the real
thing, that there is no bigger thrill than playing.
``So I want to play as long as I can. I lost the best part of two years with
the leg-break, but that's two years I wasn't damaging ligaments and tendons.
Perhaps I can stretch it out a bit longer. I'd never say `never' to the World
Cup, but you have to face reality.
``The World Cup draw was great for us - I'm not saying it won't be difficult -
but it was magic. Look at what happened to Northern Ireland - Germany and
Portugal. Or England - Italy, Poland, Georgia, and Moldova - that section is
murder.
``Getting Sweden is another boost for us. We're one of the teams they did not
fancy. We have to be happy.''
Some might have thought McCoist's presence at an athletics ceremony out of
place - he did have European Cup 400 metres champion Melanie Neef there to keep
him right - but he confessed to modest track success of his own, before his
chemistry teacher, former Clyde manager Archie Robertson, lit his football fuse.
``I took a silver medal for 800m as a 12-year-old at Hunter High, East
Kilbride, and I used to do the Thistle Awards.''
Dismissing invitations to race Neef, who is helping make a video to launch the
twenty-fifth year of the awards, he laughed: ``Sprinting? I'm the guy who got
lapped in the 100m - and that was by a girl.'' Forty per cent of Scotland's
schools use the Thistle scheme, or Magic Mac Awards. But as Richard Ellis, head
of TSB sponsorship, says, ``that means 60% do not get the message.
``They helped develop Ally's agility, skill, speed, and strength - qualities
all sports need. We are anxious to get across the message that the awards can
be a valuable part of the curriculum. There's a preconception that they're
complicated. But they're much easier to operate for primary and secondary
schools, than in the past.
``We are trying to explain that they're valuable to the development of any
sport.'' Thistle Award winners:
Primaries - 1, Denholm (Hawick); 2, Hilton (Inverness); 3, Coldstream.
Secondaries. Male - 1, Castlehead (Paisley); 2, St Mungo's (Glasgow); 3,
Hamilton College. Female - 1, Castlehead (Paisley); 2, Wellington (Ayr); 3, St
Columba's (Kilmacolm). Atletic clubs. Male - 1, Shetland AAC; 2, Elgin AAC; 3,
Edinburgh AC. Female - 1, Shetland AAC; 2, Elgin AAC; 3, Babcock Pitreavie AAC.
</TEXT>
