<HEADLINE>Union fights for minimum wage</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880911</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By ROY ROGERS
Industrial Correspondent
THE Transport and General Workers Union, one of the largest Labour Party
affiliates, will have no truck with any regional or sectoral variations for the
statutory national minimum wage a Labour Government is committed to introduce.
Nor would the TGWU favour any reduced rate for youngsters except possibly in
situations where it was linked to acceptable training programmes. Otherwise,
where young workers perform an adult job they should receive adult rates,
general secretary Bill Morris stressed yesterday.
At the same time as keeping pressure on Labour on the make-up of the statutory
minimum, the TGWU was proceeding with its industrial campaign to win a minimum
of at least #4 an hour for its members.
The biggest such deal to date involved 7000 members employed by the Ministry of
Defence although Mr Morris is hoping for a major breakthrough in forthcoming
negotiations for local authority workers. However, he concedes his union's #1m
fighting fund might have to be deployed to force employers to accept the #4 an
hour minimum.
Summing up the year, Mr Morris said membership losses appeared to have bottomed
out, with numbers rising by 300 to 902,000 in the quarter to September - the
first gain for 16 years.
Finances too were looking healthier but the TGWU was to continue running down
its Labour Party affiliation.
</TEXT>
