<DOCNO>GH951215-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Point to prove</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880913</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT has been 11 years since Derek Ferguson was ``coached'' through an Old Firm
match by the then Celtic midfield player Tommy Burns.
Times have changed, of course, and Ferguson, just 17 when he lined up for
Rangers against the current Celtic manager, must push that memory to the back
of his mind as Ferguson's new club, Falkirk, go to Parkhead in search of points
tomorrow.
``I remember my Old Firm debut well,'' said Ferguson. ``I was 17 and only found
out the day before when manager Jock Wallace called me into his office and told
me I was playing.
``I was in the middle of the park against Tommy Burns and I couldn't believe it
when he started giving me advice and telling me to keep things simple. For a
guy who wanted to beat me - and I was desperate to beat him - it was something.
That has always stuck in my mind.''
That December, 1984, Parkhead clash ended 1-1 - but the Falkirk player knows
his side will have to turn in a top show to achieve the same result tommorow."
</TEXT>
