<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Personal touch in store</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Jennifer Davis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974880914</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE place where shopping hasn't lost its community spirit these days is De
Courcy's arcade, just behind Byres Road in Glasgow's West End.
Even in the season of festive cheer, the fun can go out of choosing gifts when
your purchase is just one of thousands of anonymous transactions in a busy
department store.
In Cresswell Lane, where De Courcy's has been in business for 15 years in a
converted stable, more than 20 individual traders operate within its pristine
whitewashed walls.
Choose from a selection of clothing, furniture, gifts, curios and services in
the knowledge that the personal touch has not been lost. The person you deal
with will most probably be the owner of the business, not some disinterested
sales assistant.
For the very young there's a children's bookshop, with plenty to interest and
amuse, and a new and secondhand clothes shop where you can pick up some unusual
outfits, or spot a bargain among the rails. For adults, the arcade's your
oyster.
If you're keen on handicrafts, you can either buy a sewing machine or have one
serviced, but if you prefer not to do the hard work yourself, there's a
dressmaking and alteration service. The linen and lace place has some
delightful offerings which will give your furniture a rich and classy tone, and
can be functional as well as decorative.
For the more trendy there's a selection of American clothing, and hobby
enthusiasts will be interested in the records, tapes and CDs collections, and
the computer games store. The book shop has a marvellous selection of old
comics, as well as a satisfyingly diverse range of titles. Staying with the
written word, there's a full range of printing and photocopying services.
For the home, the art section offers some exciting original works, and if you
have your own prints, there's a picture framing shop.
Good traditional furniture can be difficult to find but the arcade has both
antique and reproduction items. Advice and estimates on having furniture of
your own renovated or french polished are available.
If your home has everything, then don't despair, there's still something to
interest you. Garden pots in lots of shapes, sizes and colours may appeal.
The friendly cafe will provide a relaxing backdrop for wondering how your bank
balance is going to stand up to all this delightful shopping, but perhaps
that's best left between you and the resident clairvoyant.
</TEXT>
