<DOCNO>GH951215-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>50p slip-up on cost of TV licence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Heritage yesterday owned up to asking 50p too much for next
year's television licences.
An ``administrative error'' resulted in the price of a colour licence being
announced to Parliament two weeks ago as #90.
The figure should have been #89.50, the Department said.
It said that the change would not affect the BBC's ability to provide its range
of TV and radio services.
The mistake arose because when the new figure was calculated, using the Retail
Price Index, it was rounded up to the nearest 50p instead of being rounded down.
This year, a colour licence costs #86.50.Black-and-white licences still will be
#30 after April 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots stand by luck of draw</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974880916</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By KEN GALLACHER
THERE will be no attempt by the Scottish Football Association to have
alterations made to the format of the European Championship finals' draw which
takes place in Birmingham on Sunday afternoon.
Concern has been expressed in various quarters over the possibility of Scotland
being drawn in the same group as England, sparking a major invasion of London
by the Tartan Army.
So far UEFA have resisted any change to the manner in which they will conduct
the draw. Four seeds have been named, including the host nation, England, and
they each will be allocated to one of the groups. As for the remainder, it is
an open draw, although there is a possibility that this could be changed at a
UEFA meeting this morning.
Yesterday the chief executive of the SFA, Jim Farry, revealed: ``We will abide
by the rules of the tournament as to how the draw is made.
``The organising committee know how both we and the English FA feel about the
possibility of playing each other in a group game, but that is as far as
anything has gone.''
Farry has no fears about the behaviour of the international team's followers
who will cross the Border in massive numbers in the summer. He is quick to
point out that the Tartan Army were given a fair play award after their
invasion of Sweden four years ago.
So far, of course, the two associations have ducked out of staging the meetings
on the former annual basis. Trouble at Wembley and at Hampden brought them to
an end. But the SFA are looking towards a resumption of the game's oldest
international match when the refurbishment of Hampden is complete, and they are
sure to ask the English to play there in the opening game.
Meanwhile, as UEFA sit down in Birmingham for preliminary committee meetings as
the countdown to the draw begins, another major decision will be made in Europe
when the Court of Justice hands down its judgment in the case concerning the
Belgian player, Jean-Marc Bosman, who has won the first leg of his battle to
allow players complete freedom of contract.
Now he expects the court to ratify the opinion given in September by Advocate
General Carl Otto Lenz.
If the case goes as expected transfer fees will be abolished, and the current
ban on the number of foreign players who can appear for a club in European
competition may also go.
</TEXT>
