<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ENERGY Nuclear industry looks to future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan Hunter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974880917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXECUTIVES from the Scottish nuclear industry will meet in Edinburgh today  to
discuss the way towards privatisation, writes ALAN HUNTER.
This was announced yesterday by the chairman of British Energy, John Robb, as
the company moved into new headquarters on Edinburgh Park, where he emphasised
that industry health and safety standards would be maintained.
A total of 70 executives will meet, said Mr Robb, who deflected reaction to a
statement from the Scottish National Party that a referendum of local people at
Dounreay in Caithness had overwhelmingly rejected the prospect of American
nuclear waste coming to the plant.
The SNP is insisting that Scotland should not become a ``laundry'' for the
world's nuclear installations.
Chief executive Dr Robert Hawley said that re-processing was undertaken by
Sellafield, and would not be drawn on the Caithness issue.
British Energy, the holding company set up to privatise the advanced gas-cooled
reactor and pressurised water reactor assets of Nuclear Electric and Scottish
Nuclear, unveiled its new logo, aimed at symbolising a momentum of power.
</TEXT>
