<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hamish Morrison to stand down</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974881044</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER 15 years at the helm of the Scottish Council Development and Industry,
Hamish Morrison is stepping down as its chief executive.
His resignation, announced yesterday at the SCDI's annual general meeting in
Glasgow, will not take effect immediately - Mr Morrison will stay on to supply
``an extra pair of hands'' while it prepares for its 26th International Forum,
which will be held at the end of March.
Alan Wilson will take over as chief executive. Mr Wilson joined in 1980 and is
currently serving as general manager and secretary.
Mr Morrison, 51, said he intended to spend the next two to three years working
as a self-employed consultant, after which he plans to start his own business
specialising in some aspect of economic development.
``The real reason for the change is that if I don't leave now, as the years go
by, it will get harder and harder to go,'' he said. ``The Scottish Council
isn't the sort of organisation that should be lumbered with the same leader
decade after decade.''
Most of Mr Morrison's remaining time with the SCDI will be devoted to preparing
for the 1996 Learning To Compete forum, which will be held in Perthshire.
One of the issues to be addressed at the forum is changing employment patterns
in Scotland.
The concern, Mr Morrison said, is that as many as 40% of Scotland's workers are
not in a permanent position with a standard labour contract. As full-time
tenured jobs have become scarcer, more and more people have had to settle for
temporary and part-time employment.
``The Scottish Council is very interested in this,'' he said. ``It is one of
the few organisations with enough breadth of represented interests to really
understand this phenomenon.''
Mr Morrison said one possible solution could be to focus more energy on
``neglected'' industries such as tourism, which have the potential to create
permanent indigenous employment. But other alternatives must also be considered
because many of Scotland's jobs are with multinational companies that are
unlikely to change their employment practices.
``I think we also need to look at changing the social security and tax systems
to help people that need to earn their living in this flexible way,'' Mr
Morrison said, ``because the people who are affected by this are becoming more
and more alienated from society.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951215-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951215-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951215</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Innovative Scottish businessman knows what to do with last year's computer model From garage to the world stage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974881045</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
APPLE isn't the only computer company which started life in someone's garage.
Liam McKenna, who emerged last night as the 1995 winner of the televised
Business Game on Scottish, started in the same humble surroundings as Steven
Jobs.
But the McKenna garage, in Clarencefield near Dumfries, was not the launchpad
for some innovative approach to personal computing. Instead, the ideas first
hatched inside his lock-up helped answer a major issue nagging away at the
whole PC industry: What to with second-hand 286s nobody seems to want, or the
main manufacturers' production over-runs of last year's obsolete models?
The traditional answer is straight landfill or, at best, recovery of the memory
chips, precious metals from the circuitry and, possibly, some of the plastic
casing, followed by dumping of the remains. One estimate suggests 100,000
tonnes of electrical equipment is landfilled in the UK each year.
But landfill is about to get much more costly, thanks to Chancellor Clarke's #7
a tonne tax, announced in last month's Budget, and a growing raft of regulation
from Brussels which will prevent the more hazardous components, like
cathode-ray tubes, being dumped at all.
Rutherglen-born McKenna, who spent most of his career as an IBM executive
overseas, spotted his niche and pounced. His business - known as R.Frazier for
reasons which will be explained shortly - takes all those redundant and
obsolete computers, monitors and printers, and now telephones as well,
re-engineers them where necessary, and recycles them by selling them into those
parts of the world where the appetite for information technology is vast, but
this year's models are beyond most people's pockets.
From Vietnam and China to Zimbabwe and Colombia, he is finding ready markets
for de-badged but functional machines, by the hundred and thousand. From that
garage base, in just three years, R..Frazier has burgeoned into the former
McGeorge knitwear factory, 130,000sqft of space piled high with yesterday's
computers and phones, largely destined for new life and fresh uses all around
the globe. Only 5% of what arrives at the Irongray premises ends up as genuine
waste.
McKenna buys for as little as #20 a tonne, on the basis that he shares the
final resale profit with his suppliers. Thanks to a remarkable network of
contacts in key target markets, the fruit of more than 20 years on the Big Blue
payroll, he can turn that #20 of high-class scrap into as much as #13,500 of
resale business.
Turnover, which was less than #250,000 in the initial ``garage'' year, topped
#5m in year three and is projected at a remarkable #20m in year four. ``I
already know exactly where every pound of that will come from'' says McKenna,
with a grin. ``Of course things could go wrong, but I don't think they will.''
The inbound deals typically return between 50% and 75% of the profits to
suppliers, like BT, many of the biggest computer OEMs, and a host of large
commercial organisations re-equipping their own electronic infrastructure. ``We
make our money on the 25% to 50% we keep,'' says McKenna. ``And we're making
money. We're hugely profitable.''
R.Frazier is also expanding its operations. Last May, it opened a second
European base in Amsterdam, a joint venture with a Netherlands waste group.
Next month it will open a wholly-owned subsidiary in Malaysia. In the third
quarter of 1996, it will open another operation in New Zealand.
An associate company in the US has opened in Atlanta and San Jose, Costa Rica,
and is also looking at Austin, Texas. Some of these locations, like Penang in
Malaysia, are designed to be near the manufacturing plants, where the
production over-runs occur. Others, like New Zealand, are a conscious response
to strong resale markets, where the local culture values a functional bargain.
New Zealand, McKenna points out, is one of the biggest second-hand markets in
the world.
McKenna's career with IBM had taken him to Johannesburg, Paris, Brussels and
London. In 1991, at the age of 49, he took advantage of the restructuring
sweeping through the multinational and got himself a deal. ``I had always
wanted to get into business for myself. I had been director of marketing for
network services in Brussels. But, in a really big machine there are very few
really big cogs. When the scheme came along allowing management to depart on
good terms, I jumped at it.''
A friend in IBM had spotted an American, Randy Frazier, who had a plant in
Virginia recycling obsolete computers. ``They bought them in, sorted them and
sold them on. There was almost no re-engineering. But they were selling in very
big volumes.''
Initially, McKenna sold some of that Frazier kit from his garage. Then, with
Frazier as the only outside shareholder, using his IBM pension money, he
launched the company which won him last night's award, which is sponsored by
Bank of Scotland and Scottish Enterprise. His operation is now bigger than the
American role model.
``We decided to call it R.Frazier to give us an international image'' he says,
hinting that that's what gives a Scottish start-up the right kind of appeal to
enterprise support organisations. McKenna is far from complementary about the
way the banks treated his early appeals for modest funding support. ``We still
have no bank loans apart from on property. But, now that we're a success, they
are falling over themselves to lend us money'' he says.
One of the keys to McKenna is a two megabyte palmtop computer containing a vast
array of contacts around the world, gleaned from his years in IBM. ``It's
absolute drivel to say that you don't need to travel any more to do business.
You have to meet people across the table to strike deals.''
His own prodigious itinerary in the past year, from China and Australia to
Russia and Canada, would fell a man half his years. ``Doing business
internationally is not difficult, it's fun,'' he insists. With R.Frazier's
phenomenal growth, some of the 105 people who now work for him in Dumfries are
beginning to get their own taste of that excitement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
